<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 0020EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Assemblies-Glance     02-22 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Assemblies-Glance,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Assemblies of God At-A-Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Swaggart, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Some facts and figures on the Assemblies of God church:
   _ Founded in 1914 during a convention in Hot Springs, Ark., the
Assemblies of God moved its headquarters to Springfield, Mo., from
St. Louis in 1918. It employs more than 1,300 people in
Springfield: at the headquarters, its seminary, three colleges and
a retirement center.
   _ The Assemblies of God is pentecostal, a branch of Christianity
emphasizing personal experience of God, manifested in ``gifts of
the spirit'' such as speaking in tongues and healing.
   _ It is the largest pentecostal demonination if the United
States, claiming nearly 2.5 million adherents, plus 14 million
overseas _ 9 million of them in Brazil.
   _ There are nearly 11,000 Assemblies of God churches in the
United States and more than 30,000 ministers _ about 3,700 of them
women, according to a 1987 survey.
   _ The church is composed of 57 districts, primarily broken down
by geographic boundaries.
   _ Ordained ministers and church delegates form the General
Council, a body which meets biennially to conduct church business,
formulate procedures and policies, and elect top executive officers
to the 13-member Executive Presbytery. The general superintendent,
who is the top executive officer, is elected to a four-year term;
all others are elected to two-year terms.
   _ Ministers can be disciplined not only for moral indescretion
but also for straying from church doctrines, inefficency, being
contentious or non-cooperative, or trying to assume dictatorial
power over a congregation.
</TEXT>
