<DOCNO> AP880222-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 0037EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Cyprus-Vassiliou     02-22 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cyprus-Vassiliou,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Political Newcomer Is Fourth Cyprus President Since Independence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Cyprus-Election</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Vassiliou, elected as Cyprus'
fourth president since independence from Britain 28 years ago, had
never belonged to a political party or been involved in political
activity until he decided to run for office.
   The 56-year-old millionaire businessmen ran as an independent
backed by the Moscow-oriented Communist Party, AKEL, which controls
about one-third of the votes among the 363,000 voters on the Greek
Cypriot side of the divided Mediterranean island.
   On Sunday, he defeated a veteran conservative politician to
become the nation's leader.
   Until his campaign, Vassiliou concentrated on his research and
marketing company, worth about $5 million. It is the largest in the
Middle East.
   The campaign was a first for the communists as well. Until this
poll, the party had always supported centrist candidates, never
fielding its own man.
   But the millionaire's endorsement by the communists was not as
contradictory as it sounds. His parents, Vassos, an eye doctor, and
Phofo, a dentist, were founding members of the party in 1941.
   His father took the family to Greece in 1945 to fight on the
communist side in the civil war.
   The pro-European Vassiliou has stressed his political
independence from the communists, particularly on foreign policy,
and is expected to adhere to Cyprus' non-aligned status.
   The election of the urbane Vassiliou, an economist who speaks
seven languages, breaks the Greek Cypriot nationalists' grip on
power since independence.
   The island's first president, Archbishop Makarios, hero of the
independence struggle in the 1950s, was elected for three five-year
terms with huge majorities.
   His successor, Spyros Kyprianou, was considered his political
heir and served for two terms _ but only with AKEL support, which
was withdrawn in 1985.
   Vassiliou's election breaks the mold. He has said his first
priority is to break the deadlock between Greek and Turkish
Cypriots and seek to reunite the island.
   It has been divided since the Turkish army invaded in 1974,
after a short-lived coup by militant supporters of union with
Greece that installed Nicos Sampson as president for eight days.
   All efforts to find a political settlement have foundered. But
Vassiliou has said he will form a national unity government and is
willing to reopen negotiations without preconditions.
   Vassilou, who was born in Famagusta, now part of the breakaway
Turkish Cypriot republic in the northern third of the island, was
educated in London and Budapest, Hungary. He is married with three
children.
</TEXT>
