<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CommuterPlaneCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0841</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commuter Plane Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0841,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers Search Pond For Clues in Fatal Commuter Plane Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with comment from NTSB
official, saying debris shows that plane hit water first, and that
officials believe first officer, not the plane's captain, may have
been flying the plane. Picks up 4th graf pvs, `About 25...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MEG REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MORRISVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators in motorboats raked the
bottom of a shallow pond at Raleigh-Durham Airport on Sunday,
pulling up debris that may be a clue to a commuter plane crash that
killed 12 people.
   No one survived Friday night's crash of American Eagle Flight
3378, which went down shortly after takeoff en route to Richmond,
Va.
   Because of debris found in the water, investigators believe the
twin-engine turboprop hit the pond before plunging into a wooded
area and exploding, officials said Sunday evening. Earlier, they
had said the plane had barely skimmed the pond, a flood reservoir,
before crashing.
   Parts of the plane, including a portion of the hydraulic system,
were found within 40 feet of the bank, said National Transportation
Safety Board member James L. Kolstad.
   He also said that investigators believe the 28-year-old first
officer, Kathy Digan, was flying the plane when it crashed Friday,
because the captain, Walter Cole, was talking to the control tower
when the plane took off.
   ``The person that does the flying doesn't usually do the
radio,'' Kolstad said.
   Ms. Digan, who was hired by American Eagle last May, had 2,150
total flying hours and 450 in the Metro-III, the craft type
involved in the crash.
   ``She was qualified,'' Kolstad said. ``There is no doubt about
that.''
   Weather at the time of the accident, although poor, was not so
severe as to endanger the flight. Visibility on the runway was
between 2,400 and 3,000 feet when the crash occurred. The flight
could have taken off down to 1,600 feet, Kolstad said.
   Earlier, NTSB spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz, said officials hoped
that the search of the reservoir would show ``how (the plane) broke
up. It helps determine the sequence of events.''
   About 25 investigators, including some from the NTSB, sifted
through the roped-off wreckage site on the pond's bank, peering at
small bits of debris and examining larger plane parts for signs of
malfunction.
   Beyond them, men in lifejackets piloted two motorboats around
the surface of the pond, using poles and hooks to retrieve small
pieces of crash debris. The pond measured about 4 feet deep and 75
yards wide, officials said.
   The debris will be used to determine the state and angle of the
plane when it struck the bank, since the aircraft carried no flight
data or cockpit voice recorders, Lopatkiewicz said. Neither is
currently required by the Federal Aviation Administration on
commuter aircraft, although they will be as of March 1989, he said.
   ``If it was flying upside-down, that tells you something,'' he
said.
   Some trees were broken and others were skinned as much as 200
yards beyond the water when the aircraft hit the wooded bank. The
wreckage, including the entire silver tail, was strewn over an area
measuring about 50 feet by 150 feet, Lopatkiewicz said.
   Rubble and bits of shiny metal still littered the tall grass.
The largest plane piece, a red-, white- and blue-striped shard from
the fuselage measuring about 15 feet, lay amid several broken pine
tree trunks. Wheels from the landing gear had broken off their
axle, while about 30 yards away, a piece of the aircraft's
emergency door lay twisted in the mud.
   The remains of the 10 passengers and two crew members were
removed Saturday night from the crash site and taken to the North
Carolina medical examiner's laboratory in Chapel Hill, said Teresa
Damiano, an airport spokeswoman.
   Officials were using fingerprints to help identify the victims,
she said.
</TEXT>
