<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF-ShipCollision     02-22 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF-Ship Collision,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese, Soviet Cargo Vessels Collide, One Reported Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese cargo ship capsized today after
colliding with a Soviet freighter in Osaka Bay. All five crewmen on
the cargo ship were rescued and no one aboard the Soviet vessel was
injured, a maritime official said.
   Two tug boats sent from Osaka rescued the five crew members from
the 499-ton Ryusei-maru after it collided with the 10,152-ton
Alisher-Navoi, said Mariko Sugai, spokeswoman of the local Maritime
Safety Agency.
   There were no reports of injuries among the 32 crew members
aboard the Alisher-Navoi, she said.
   Two Japanese crewmen, including skipper Takemitsu Masu, were
taken to a hospital in Osaka for treatment of unspecified injuries.
   At the time of the accident, the Soviet vessel was making a turn
in order to leave for Australia after unloading pig iron at an
Osaka pier, while the Ryusei-maru, carrying a load of limestone,
was heading toward the pier.
