<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 0057EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-America-InLights     02-22 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-America-In Lights,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lights Of Western Maryland Community Form Outline Of United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEB RIECHMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LaVALE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For more than 20 years, the lights of this
western Maryland community have shimmered with national pride.
   As the lights of LaVale flicker at dusk, a near-perfect outline
of the United States begins to shine brightly from this residential
community nestled in the foothills of the Alleghenies.
   ``It's an unusual happenstance. No one tried to make it,'' said
Carson Dowell, who has lived for 25 years atop Haystack Mountain
where the map is best viewed on a cold, clear winter night. ``I'm
not sure who discovered it. My wife mentioned it to me. She
couldn't believe it.''
   A shopping center forms the U.S.-Canadian border. A well-lighted
thoroughfare around LaVale is the West Coast. The East Coast is
about a mile of motels, fast food restaurants and stores along U.S.
40.
   ``It's beginning to get a litle busy and distorted because of
all the development in the LaVale area,'' said Cindy Snyder, who
also lives in the 124-home Sunset View development on the mountain.
``As you come down the East Coast, Florida is starting to get a
little out of proportion.''
   ``Back five, 10 years ago, it was probably a little better,''
she said. ``We're not knocking the development, but we're losing
our United States.''
   Maine is formed where U.S. 48 disappears behind a mountain
ridge. The southern edge of Lake Ontario is a bowling alley. A
disfigured Florida appears where U.S. 40 vanishes around Haystack
Mountain. And the Gulf Coast is a grouping of homes and other
establishments.
   ``It's the United States of America from Sunset View,'' said
David Dorsey, a planner with the Allegany County Planning and
Zoning Commission. ``I guess just about everyone has heard of it. I
don't know if everyone believes it.''
   The residential community of more than 7,200 has experienced a
rush of commercial and residential development, especially since
the 1960s, Dorsey said.
   ``We were worried about the mall when it opened up (in 1981),
but it's actually a big Hawaii,'' said Gary Ruddell, a businessman
who lives in the area. ``There's no Alaska. We have to do some more
development.''
   Ruddell, past chairman of the Sunset View Civic Association,
said the map is best seen in the winter when leaves have fallen
from trees on Haystack Mountain. About nine months ago, members of
the association thought about topping some trees to provide a
better view, but scrapped the idea in favor of more pressing needs,
he said.
   Some residents expressed concern that publicity would attract
sightseers to Sunset View and create traffic, but others said most
local residents either have already seen it, or have no interest in
getting a glimpse of America in lights.
   ``Sometimes at night people stop out in front and you wonder
what they're doing,'' Dowell said. ``But then you know what they're
doing. They're looking at the map.''
   ``I remember one time _ it's been years ago _ one of my
neighbors called and said, `There's someone down in your garden
with a tripod surveying,''' Dowell said. ``They weren't surveying.
They were down there taking pictures of the map.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880222-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 0108EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HotlineCrisis     02-22 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hotline Crisis,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Half Of Crisis Hotline Staff Walks Out in Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 30 years of handling people in crisis,
the Suicide Prevention Center has a crisis of its own. Half the
telephone hotline workers have walked out in a dispute over layoffs
and control of the center.
   The workers went out on Jan. 1 and it has been a sometimes noisy
dispute, with striking counselors picketing the center's offices
and chanting ``down with the board'' during a recent closed-door
meeting of directors.
   Despite the walkout, the crisis line handled more calls in
January than it did the same month a year earlier, Executive
Director Sheila Halfon said.
   In fact, the strike has prompted people to come forward to ask
if the center needed their help.
   ``We were deluged with calls from people who read about it and
(asked) how could they volunteer,'' Halfon said.
   In addition to the crisis line, the center operates a substance
abuse clinic, a halfway house, an AIDS research project, an art
therapy program and an annual curriculum for schools on substance
abuse and suicide.
   Before the layoffs, the center _ excluding crisis line workers _
had about 90 full- and part-time employees. The crisis line was
staffed by about 80 volunteers and consultants. The latter are
workers who started out as volunteers but have begun to receive
part-time, $6-an-hour shifts.
   The crisis line workers walked out when 27 of the non-crisis
line staffers were laid off and the hours of 15 others were cut
back late last year.
   The layoff was strictly a ``budgetary concern,'' Halfon
asserted, though she admitted, ``the timing was terrible, you know,
December.''
   The center's budget in 1985-86 was about $3 million, including
revenue from contracts, grants, clinic fees and donations, she said.
   But in the last year, some grants have ended and contracts that
provided government funding have not been renewed, she said,
estimating the current budget at about $1.5 million.
   ``We are concerned with fulfilling that,'' she said. ``The
cutbacks in just the layoffs will result in a savings of half a
million dollars.''
   The strikers, however, are particularly upset that among those
laid off was the center's first employee, social worker Sam Heilig,
who served as a clinical consultant.
   ``We can't function without a clinical person in control,''
Phyllis Meisler, a spokeswoman for the strikers, said recently.
   ``The dismissal of one of the most well known and most
experienced persons in the area of suicide prevention doesn't make
much sense,'' said Norman L. Farberow, a psychologist who
co-founded the center in 1958.
   Heilig did not return a telephone call for comment.
   In 1984, Farberow and the other founder, Dr. Robert E. Litman,
turned the center over to a board of directors composed of local
business people so that they could focus on research.
   But the founders, who have remained as clinicians, want to
regain control of the center.
   The board of directors met Feb. 7 to deal with the center's
problems.
   Halfon said the directors favored putting a member of the crisis
line staff on the board, but she would not reveal what moves the
board would take to resolve the overall problem of ``ultimate
administrative control'' of the organization.
   ``That's the part that's in question. What's the best way to
preserve the integrity and assets of the organization?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
