<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FBIDismissal Bjt   02-22 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FBI Dismissal, Bjt,0706</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fired FBI Agent Seeks Reinstatement; Changes Lifestyle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five months after the FBI fired him, former
agent John C. Ryan is grappling with a religious renewal that
caused him to question his past, challenge his supervisors and lose
his job.
   Wholesale changes are taking place in the life of a man who was
10 months away from settling into a quiet retirement when he was
dismissed Sept. 11.
   After carrying a gun every day during 21 years of loyal FBI
service, Ryan now is a pacifist who denounces the ``immoral
activities'' of the FBI and the United States' involvement in
Central America.
   Ryan, 49, is selling his Peoria home, where he and his wife,
Peggy, raised four children. And he's pondering a total change in
lifestyle while searching for a way to support his family the next
12 years until he can collect his federal pension.
   ``It would be inconsistent for me to continue being a heavy
consumer knowing how many victims the American lifestyle demands,''
Ryan said recently. ``There's war in Latin America so we can
continue to eat Big Macs, and I don't want to contribute to that.
We're scaling down our lifestyle to a more simplified life.''
   His only income comes from speaking engagements and from
teaching a sociology class at Bradley University. Legal fees to
fight his dismissal have eaten $13,000 out of the family savings _
perhaps part of the reason for the change in lifestyle.
   Clad in sneakers and jeans, Ryan hardly resembled the man who
spent two decades in foreign counterintelligence, investigating
organized crime in New York and hunting fugitives like anti-war
activist Daniel Berrigan.
   His work twice won him commendations, but something was missing
from his life. A devout Roman Catholic who once studied for the
priesthood, Ryan started taking religious study courses about 10
years ago.
   He earned his master's degree in 1985, and the transformation
from a follower of J. Edgar Hoover into a pacifist began to mature.
   It was then that Ryan knew his beliefs would conflict with his
role as chief counterintelligence operative in the FBI's five-man
office here. But he never really thought it would lead to his
dismissal.
   ``Refusing an order was something I'd never done before, and I
knew an act of insubordination would cost me some sort of
disciplinary action,'' Ryan said. ``I have religious beliefs they
are bound to accommodate. There are office jobs, places I could
work in the FBI. I wouldn't have to carry a gun.
   ``I think they overreacted in firing me. It was stupid. Look at
all the notoriety it has caused.''
   Ryan's life is in turmoil, but he seems content with his
decision to refuse an order to investigate an anti-nuclear group
suspected of vandalizing 11 Chicago-area military recruiting
offices.
   ``I really feel I did the right thing,'' Ryan said. ``I don't
know if I could have lived with myself had I done anything
differently.''
   His firing occurred 10 months before his 50th birthday in June,
when he would have been eligible for full retirement with 20 years
service.
   ``I could have simply ignored the order, but I chose not to. I
felt what we were doing was clearly investigating peace groups with
the obvious intention of intimidating and harassing them. I thought
the FBI was ill-advised to do this and I told them.''
   Despite his change of heart, the FBI negotiated with Ryan and
offered to reinstate him, with back pay, in December on the
condition he never speak of the case again. He said he signed an
agreement and mailed it to FBI headquarters but for some reason the
deal collapsed. The FBI has refused to say why.
   This month, an administrative judge in St. Louis ruled the FBI
was justified in firing Ryan.
   At a hearing, Ryan said he could not take a human life, even if
his or another person's life was endangered. He believes that was a
key reason his dismissal was upheld.
   Ryan still hopes to reclaim his job and his pension, and an
appeal is planned.
</TEXT>
