<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shootings-Mother     02-22 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shootings-Mother,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspect's Mother Wants To Send Sympathy Cards To Victims' Families</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of a man accused of bursting
into a defense company and shooting seven people to death said
she's saddened by the ``waste of life'' and wants to send sympathy
cards to the victims' families.
   ``I wish those people would know how badly we feel,'' Mina Belle
Farley said in an interview published Sunday. ``I don't know if it
would help (to send cards), but we could tell them how sad we are
about all of this.''
   Mrs. Farley, 70, also said she was shocked to learn that her
son, Richard Wade Farley, was charged with seven counts of murder
in Tuesday's shootings at ESL Inc. offices in nearby Sunnyvale.
   ``We'd never had any problems with Rick,'' she told the San Jose
Mercury News in a telephone interview Saturday from her home in
Henderson, Texas, about 100 miles east of Dallas.
   Mrs. Farley and her husband, Thomas, who is retired from a
career in the Air Force, learned of the shootings and their oldest
child's arrest the next day after they tried to contact him in San
Jose.
   Neither Farley's parents nor any of his five brothers and
sisters have heard from him since the attack, she said.
   ``We don't communicate much,'' said Mrs. Farley, who hasn't seen
her son since a trip to California 1{ years ago.
   She also said her son never mentioned 26-year-old Laura Black,
an ESL employee who authorities describe as the unwilling object of
Farley's romantic fantasies.
   Farley's four-year obsession with the electrical engineer is
believed by authorities to be the reason for the rampage. He was
fired in May 1986 for harassing Black, who went to court for a
restraining order to stop him from following, calling and writing
her, authorities said.
   Black was one of the three people who were shot during the
rampage, but she survived. She remained in stable condition at
Stanford University Medical Center, where she is expected to remain
for several more days.
   Farley remained under 24-hour surveillance at the Santa Clara
County Jail. Sheriff's Lt. Mike Fine said he was quiet and polite.
   Besides the seven murder counts, Farley is charged with three
counts of attempted murder. He could face execution if convicted.
</TEXT>
