<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Panama-Lobbyists Bjt   02-22 0888</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Lobbyists, Bjt,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big-Money Lobbying On Panama's Behalf Was Rule Until Recently</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama has spent hundreds of thousands of
dollars since 1985 hiring American lobbyists to champion the
country's cause in Congress and improve its image in the United
States, records show.
   Among those who have registered as agents of Panama are Stuart
Spencer, a long-time political adviser to President Reagan; M.B.
Oglesby Jr., former White House assistant for legislative affairs;
Francis Gomez, an executive with ties to Lt. Col. Oliver North's
network, and Jamie Whitten Jr., the son of Rep. Jamie Whitten,
D-Miss.
   The documents are filed at the Justice Department in compliance
with the Foreign Agents Registration Act. The law requires foreign
agents to report their activities every six months.
   Many foreign governments hire lobbyists to help learn about the
complicated U.S. bureaucracy. In recent years, the practice has
attracted congressional scrutiny, particularly when former
government officials sell their inside knowledge to foreigners.
   Raul St. Malo, a spokesman at Panama's embassy, said the
government no longer employs any American lobbyists, and the
records indicate that many contracts have lapsed.
   Relations between the two countries have deteriorated sharply
since Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the country's dominant figure,
was indicted on drug smuggling charges in Miami this month.
   One of the most recent filings _ covering the period through
December 1987 _ was made by Gomez, a former State Department
official and one-time business partner of Richard R. Miller, an
associate of North's.
   Gomez's company, Public Affairs Resources Inc., was paid nearly
$145,000 between July and December 1987 by a Panamanian business
group set up in August 1986 to ``promote tourism, exports,
investment and an improved image'' for Panama.
   The group, Impulso Turistico y Financiera de Panama, is headed
by Robert Cordovez. Gomez said Cordovez is a businessman with
``ties to people in the government.''
   Panamanian opposition figures, including Roberto Eisenmann, the
editor of the newspaper La Prensa, said Cordovez is close to
Noriega. Eisenmann lives in exile in Miami.
   For his money, Gomez worked extensively with the Panamanian
Embassy, the documents show. Among his duties: ``Edited articles
written by embassy officials,'' and, ``Made copies of newspaper
articles, speeches and letters as requested by the embassy.''
   The $21,000 a month contract with Impulso was first signed in
September 1986 by International Business Communications, a
now-defunct firm run by Miller and Gomez.
   Miller, who worked with North raising money for the Nicaraguan
Contras in 1985 and 1986, has pleaded guilty to tax violations in
soliciting contributions for the rebels. There is no indication
that Gomez worked with North.
   North, an ex-National Security Council aide, was fired in
November 1986 for his role in using money secured through the sale
of arms to Iran to help the Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   Gomez said his relationship with the Panamanian group has ended,
and he no longer works with Miller.
   Some major firms, such as Bill Hecht and Associates, which
employed Spencer and Oglesby, and Daniel J. Edelman Inc., lost
their contracts with Panama in 1986, a year in which Panama came
under increasing attack from U.S. officials.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz registered concern in June
1986 about allegations that Noriega engaged in drug-trafficking and
gun-running. And Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., called Noriega the
``head of the biggest drug trafficking operation in the Western
Hemisphere.'' U.S. aid to Panama ceased in late 1987.
   The law firm of Lipsen, Hamberger, Whitten and Hamberger, which
did lobbying work for Panama, last worked for the country in late
1985, according to Martin Hamberger.
   Spencer, one of Reagan's close friends, worked for the Hecht
firm, which signed a $25,000-a-month contract with the Panamanian
government in late 1985, shortly after Noriega installed President
Eric Arturo Delvalle.
   The Hecht firm's contract, which expired in November 1986,
called for discussions with members of Congress, their staffs and
the executive branch about the ``political, economic and social
situation'' in Panama.
   Spencer, whose home address is Newport Beach, Calif., flew to
Panama at least twice, staying at the El Panama Hilton or the
Marriott, records show.
   The documents do not explain exactly what Spencer did for
Panama. Spencer did not return two telephone calls, and Hecht said
it is against his policy to discuss relations with clients.
   But Rep. Mike Lowery, D-Wash., recalled a luncheon at the
Capitol Hill Club _ a Republican haunt _ that he went to in January
1986 at the invitation of the Hecht staff.
   The Hecht people wanted to explore arranging better contacts
between Panamanian legislators and members of Congress, he said.
They also discussed U.S. aid to Panama, he said. Washington shut
off all aid to the country in December 1987.
   Bud Moss, an aide to Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., said he couldn't
recall the topic of Panama coming up at a luncheon with Frank West,
a lobbyist from the Hecht firm. ``We talked about banking,'' Moss
said. The $36.10 meal was charged to Panama.
   Steve Cook, a representative of Edelman, said his firm did press
work for Panamanian officials roughly between November 1985 and May
1986. One project involved setting up interviews for Delvalle's
wife at an anti-drug conference in Atlanta, he said.
   Raymond Bender, a lawyer with Dow, Lohnes and Albertson, said he
has represented the Panamanian government on some legal matters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880222-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 0119EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MontanaFire     02-22 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Montana Fire,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wildfire Jumps River, Burns Homes Near Whitehall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITEHALL, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wildfire whipped by winds of up to 50
mph raced through a mountain valley south of here Sunday,
destroying at least three homes and burning hundreds of acres of
grassland, witnesses said.
   No injuries were reported.
   Firefighters from at least 10 volunteer fire departments in the
rural area northwest of Yellowstone National Park battled the
blaze, assisted by volunteers from the Forest Service, the
Department of State Lands and two mining companies.
   Gail Giono, a dispatcher for the Jefferson County Sheriff's
Department, said the fire was first reported in early afternoon and
had grown to 500 acres by early evening. It remained uncontrolled,
and those on the scene reported at least three homes destroyed, she
said.
   The fire was centered about five miles south of this town of
1,000 and was headed eastward, not toward the town, officials said.
The homes that burned were scattered rural residences.
   The wind ``is as bad as I've ever seen it,'' said Glen Hanson, a
trapper who lives on the south edge of town. ``The ... stuff was
going faster than you could run.''
   ``A lot of people lost their homes,'' Hanson said, but noted he
did not know exactly how many homes were destroyed.
   Authorities said it was believed that the fire was caused by a
downed power line, but that had not been confirmed.
   Strong winds raked much of Montana east of the Continental
Divide on Sunday. There were widespread reports of damaged roofs,
downed power lines, uprooted trees and toppled billboards and signs.
</TEXT>
