<1ST_LINE>r a PM-IcePatrol     02-22 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ice Patrol,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Meteorites From Moon Found in Antarctica</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 15-year search for meteorites in
Antarctica has turned up thousands of meteorites, including six
from the moon and one possible rock from Mars, scientists say.
   Those seven meteorites _ solid bodies that travel through space
and survive passage through the Earth's atmosphere _ have been the
focus of years of scrutiny by scientists looking for insight on the
composition of the two heavenly bodies.
   ``It has always been assumed that a lot of material should be
falling off the moon from meteoritic impact,'' said Ursula B.
Marvin, a geologist at the Smithsonian Institution's Center for
Astrophysics here. ``We suspected that some of our meteorites came
from the moon before the Apollo missions.''
   Marvin was part of the U.S. expedition that discovered the
plum-sized rock weighing about four grams in January 1982.
   Japanese scientists have located five lunar meteorites in
Antarctica. Scientists also are ``building a case'' for Martian
origin of the meteorite found in 1979.
   Comparing the 1982 find with lunar samples collected by American
astronauts, scientists found the meteorite closely matched highland
materials returned by the Apollo 15, 16 and 17 crews.
   Analysis indicated that the fragment was blasted away from the
moon by an asteroid impact about 100,000 years ago and hurled to
Earth.
   The 66-year-old Marvin, who also teaches part-time at Harvard
University, said the lunar meteorite probably was traveling in
space for between 1,900 and 2,500 years before crashing through the
atmosphere and landing on the Antarctic ice.
   The Antarctic rock believed to be from Mars spent about 10
million years in space.
   Some of the 1,000 moon rocks retrieved in the Apollo missions
have been dated at more than 4 billion years old _ a short time, by
geologic standards.
   X-rays and gamma-rays of the moon's surface taken by Apollo
orbiters have led scientists to believe the lunar meteorite may
come from a crater on the far-eastern rim of the moon or on the
unexplored dark side, Marvin said.
   ``We went to six places on the moon and the Russians sent
unmanned landers to three places,'' she said. ``We have no exact
location for this composition anywhere.''
   Annual U.S. meteorite expeditions to Antarctica occur in the six
weeks of the year when the continent is bathed in sunlight 24 hours
a day.
   The National Science Foundation, the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration and the Smithsonian provide equipment and
financing for research for the meteoritic expeditions, said Marvin,
who has has made three trips to the 5-million-square-mile continent
to search for meteorites.
   She said that since manned moon exploration stopped after the
Apollo 17 mission in 1972, meteorite searches are crucial.
   ``It's one of the most vital and productive aspects of the space
program,'' Marvin said. ``As a matter of fact, in planetary
exploration it's the only show in town. This all gives us more
information _ without actually going up there _ about the evolution
of the moon as a body.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880222-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 0140EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Pesticides Bjt   02-22 0850</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pesticides, Bjt,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pesticide Issue Flares Amid Growing Concern over Health Effects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A foul-smelling mist came rolling into
Atwater, Calif., on the night air, silently blanketing a row of
homes on the outskirts. Within an hour, townsfolk were staggering
into the emergency room.
   Environmentalists point to the June 1 incident, which they
contend was caused by pesticides sprayed on nearby peach orchards,
to fuel their arguments that the nation must do more to control the
poisons.
   The Senate Agriculture Committee is set to try once again to
overhaul the Federal Insecticide, Fungicide and Rodenticide Act
(FIFRA), the primary law providing for regulation of the compounds.
   Pesticides are now a $5 billion-a-year industry. Tomatoes, beef,
potatoes, apples, pork and many other foods arrive at the dinner
table laden with chemicals. In a number of states, pesticides have
been found in groundwater, often used for drinking.
   Chemical makers contend that the benefits of pesticides outweigh
the risks. They say drinking a glass of well water where
contamination has been measured poses less hazard than downing a
shot of vodka.
   However, there are some 113,000 cases of pesticide-related
illness and injury logged each year. A May 1987 National Academy of
Sciences report said cancer is caused in laboratory animals by 30
percent of the insecticides most likely to show up in food, 50
percent of the herbicides and 90 percent of the fungicides.
   Congress has moved fitfully at best to tighten regulation of the
1 billion pounds of pesticides sprayed on U.S. fields annually in
the war on bacteria, fungi, bugs, worms, mice and other forms of
crop blight.
   Critics ridicule FIFRA as hopelessly toothless. ``We call it a
no-law law because it doesn't do anything,'' consumer advocate
Ralph Nader says.
   A 1972 rewrite of FIFRA gave the Environmental Protection Agency
until 1975 to complete a ``reregistration'' process, including a
full-scale safety review, of some 700 pesticides. In 1975,
lawmakers approved a one-year extension. In 1978, the deadline was
junked altogether.
   The General Accounting Office, an investigative arm of Congress,
now estimates that at the present crawl, the job won't be completed
until the year 2024.
   Senate Agriculture Committee Chairman Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt.,
and Sen. Richard G. Lugar, R-Ind., have proposed a nine-year
deadline for the reregistration process, plus a possible two-year
extension.
   ``I think most Americans are willing to put up with a spot on
their lettuce or a blemish on their apple rather than risk
cancer,'' says Leahy.
   The National Agricultural Chemicals Association, champion of the
nation's pesticide makers, has no objection to a speedup in itself.
   More complex issues, however, are lying in the legislative weeds
and could rise up to scuttle the bill. Something similar happened
in 1986 when a seeming compromise came unglued just before Congress
adjourned.
   Chemical companies are willing to contribute to the costs of
reregistration by paying $150,000 per ingredient. But the
Leahy-Lugar bill calls for $750,000, which the NACA calls ``a money
grab, pure and simple.''
   Under current law, companies are entitled to indemnities from
EPA to compensate for the banning of their products. Already the
agency has paid $2.4 million to chemical makers for taking the
pesticide EDB off the market and $18 million for a chemical known
as 2,4,5-T, or Silex.
   And the agency estimates it will pay out between $60 million and
$155 million in indemnities and disposal costs to get rid of a
pesticide called Dinoseb, The annual budget of the entire EPA
pesticide program is $70 million.
   The Leahy-Lugar bill would bar such indemnities unless Congress
passed an individual money bill for each one. Such a measure is
guaranteed a rough time on Capitol Hill. The industry is firmly
opposed.
   Manufacturers have other objections as well, especially to an
amendment Leahy co-sponsored with Sen. David Durenberger, R-Minn.
NACA President Jack D. Early told the Agriculture Committee that
the Leahy-Durenberger amendment contains ``an unrealistic ground
water definition, unenforceable goals for water quality standards
and (an) unworkable state ground and surface water protection
program.''
   Of the main legislation, he said the plan to require separate
money bills for indemnities would ``ultimately be bad for
agriculture'' because ``there is no guarantee that agricultural
users will recoup their losses.''
   However, one incentive to action is a provision that would
extend patent rights for chemical manufacturers.
   The 1986 bill passed by the House also included provisions that
would preempt states from setting more stringent safety standards
than those of the federal government and exempt agricultural
producers from cleanup liability under the environmental laws. They
were rejected by the Senate when it fashioned its own version.
   In the House, the Agriculture and the Energy and Commerce
committees are fighting over jurisdiction of the bill.
   Some FIFRA critics, such as Rick Hind of the U.S. Public
Interest Research Group, declare in disgust that it ``will take a
disaster'' to get the House moving on pesticide legislation. But
House Agriculture Committee Chairman E. ``Kika'' de la Garza,
D-Texas, scoffs at that notion.
   ``We don't need a disaster,'' he says. ``We know what we have to
do.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
