<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TrainDerailment     02-22 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Train Derailment,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Train Derails, Spills Acid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAMINE, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven cars of a 133-car Union Pacific
Railroad freight train derailed and spilled an acid solution into a
creek, threatening the water supply for thousands of people,
authorities said.
   No one was injured in Sunday's derailment in which one car
spilled about 13,000 gallons of phosphatic fertilizer solution
containing phosphoric acid into the creek leading to the Lamine
River, said Walter Fussner, a Union Pacific spokesman.
   The Lamine River, which feeds into the Missouri River, is the
water source for nearby Boonville, a town of nearly 7,000
residents. Officials shut off the water intake valve to the
community as a precaution, and residents were asked to conserve
water, said Lt. Becky Loesing of the Cooper County Emergency
Operations office.
   The Jefferson City water department was monitoring its water
supply from the Missouri River.
   Phosphoric acid can irritate the skin and respiratory system,
said Larry Alderson, environmental emergency specialist with the
Missouri Department of Natural Resources.
   A 50-man cleanup crew worked into the night with backhoes and
bulldozers to clean up and neutralize the acid. Trace elements of
the acid were found in the Lamine River, but no fish were killed,
Fussner said.
   Fussner said the cause of the accident, which occurred shortly
before noon two miles from the Missouri River, was under
investigation.
   Union Pacific officials called a cleanup contractor, who built a
dam to try to prevent the fertilizer from further contaminating the
Lamine River. Lime was hauled in to neutralize the acid, Alderson
said.
   Fussner said the railroad encountered problems because the spill
was in a remote area. No roads lead to the area, and all supplies
were being brought in by train.
   The train was traveling from East St. Louis, Ill., to North
Platte, Neb., when the accident occurred near this central Missouri
town.
</TEXT>
