<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DanceMarathon     02-22 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dance Marathon,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Young Cancer Victims Aided By Dance Marathon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young cancer victims and their parents
gained emotional support and more than $300,000 in financial help
from college students who swayed and staggered through a 48-hour
dance marathon.
   ``I just like the fact that people are dancing not just to dance
for fun but to help kids,'' said 10-year-old Diane Brannon of
Etters, a leukemia patient who took a few turns around the dance
floor with Penn State University students Sunday.
   Billed as the largest student-run fund-raising event in the
country, the 16th annual Interfraternity Dance Marathon raised
$324,200 in pledges for the Four Diamonds Fund at Penn State's
Milton S. Hershey Medical Center, organizers said Sunday.
   Diane's mother, Teresa, said she and her husband, Jim, would
have been forced to sell their house without financial help from
the fund, which helps pay for treatment of children suffering from
cancer.
   Bob Sherfy, a social worker at Hershey Medical Center who works
with the young cancer victims, said the dance marathon offered the
parents and children more than money.
   ``They know there's someone out in the world who cares about
them,'' Sherfy said.
   Near then end of the marathon, participants complained of sore
feet, fatigue and boredom.
   ``It's torture,'' said Marc Baskin, a junior management major
from Glen Cove, N.Y.
   But Baskin and many other dancers said they gained resolve from
the children at the dance.
   ``When they brought the kids in Saturday, you said to yourself,
`You can do it,''' said Tammie Rutherford, a sophomore business
management major from White Plains, N.Y.
   Hundreds of volunteers, clad in yellow T-shirts, attended the
hobbled and weary dancers as they endured the final leg of the
marathon.
   Tom West, a sophomore sports medicine major from West Long
Branch, N.J., taped feet, iced ankles and treated blisters from a
trainer's table off the dance floor.
   ``Some people come in and their feet are just flat,'' said West,
explaining that fallen arches were the most frequent physical
malady.
   Carol Stelmach, a junior marketing major from Baltimore, said
she and other dancers had a tactic for keeping their minds off
their feet.
   ``You have to do something that makes you think of your hands,''
Ms. Stelmach said. She said she had played catch using a frisbee
and balls and even participated in a card game.
   A total of 272 couples _ 544 dancers _ entered the marathon this
year, said Pat Dugan, a senior accounting major from Pittsburgh and
head of the organizing committee. A total of 506 finished.
   They were allowed only three-minute breaks every eight hours and
three other three-minute breaks at some time during the marathon.
   Spectators filled the White Building Gymnasium to capacity for
the final hours of the marathon, clapping and cheering.
   Dugan said this year's marathon was the most financially
successful in the event's history.
   James H. Brucker, director of development for the medical
center, said the marathon is the single biggest source of income
for the Four Diamonds Fund.
   Last year, the dance marathon raised $297,000, Dugan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
