<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Israel     02-22 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Israel,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peres Worried About Soviet Role In Arranging Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres says he
is concerned about the Soviet role in setting up Arab-Israeli peace
talks even as the Soviets pledged to be more of a factor in
negotiations.
   Peres, who favors an international conference to quell the
violence in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, voiced doubts
about Soviet involvement in arranging such a conference.
   The deaths of two Arabs Sunday brought the number of
Palestinians killed by Israelis since the protests began Dec. 8 to
61, according to U.N. figures.
   ``What role the Russians will play depends on what role the
international conference will play,'' Peres said Sunday in an
interview from Jerusalem on ABC-TV's ``This Week With David
Brinkley.''
   ``I would never agree that any foreign country, Russia or other
country, will make decisions instead of us or will try to force us
to make a decision,'' Peres said. ``I don't accept the Russian
concept that an international conference should be an authoritative
conference. I think it should be an authorizing conference, namely
enabling the parties to negotiate among themselves freely.''
   Peres said he understood that Jordan, Egypt, Israel and the
United States share this view.
   The foreign minister said the conference ``should be like
somebody that opens the door to a new era, but not somebody who
replaces the residents in the house itself.''
   Peres also acknowledged Sunday that he sent a handwritten note
to Attorney General Edwin Meese III in 1985 about a proposed Iraqi
pipeline.
   Peres, who was Israel's prime minister at the time, previously
has denied writing to Meese that he supported the $1 billion,
540-mile pipeline project, which was never built.
   Meanwhile in Moscow, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze, prior to meeting with Secretary of State George P.
Shultz, said that his government wants ``to play a more active role
_ also in the negotiations.''
   Shultz, who travels to Israel later this week, met with Soviet
officials to discuss the next superpower summit meeting between
President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the
Iran-Iraq war and the conflict in the Middle East.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel has resisted Soviet
participation in the search for a Middle East settlement. In
addition to not having relations with Israel, the Soviets generally
support Arab positions.
   The Soviets broke relations with Israel after it defeated Egypt,
then a Soviet ally, in the 1967 Mideast war. However, a small group
of Soviet diplomats was sent to Israel last year to take care of
some consular matters.
   Peres emphasized the urgent need for negotiations.
   ``I'm convinced that the time has really come _ which shouldn't
be postponed _ to start to negotiate and find a solution which will
answer the expressions of the Palestinians on one hand, and the
security call of Israel on the other,'' he said.
   Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, interviewed on CBS-TV's
``Face the Nation,'' welcomed U.S. efforts to set up talks on
resolving the Mideast crisis and never was asked about a Soviet
role.
   ``I believe it's a very good idea to bring about a beginning of
a talking,'' Rabin said. ``After all, the problem that we face can
be solved only by political means. By military means, by force, we
can bring about tranquility but not a solution. ...
   ``We have a very great respect and trust to Secretary Shultz. We
believe that he is honest, decent human being and is trying his
best to bring about a beginning of a talk.''
   Former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger, who appeared on the
ABC program, said negotiations should be conducted under U.S.
auspices and not Soviet authority.
   ``I have the gravest doubts about an international conference,''
Kissinger said. ``I have grave doubts about a Soviet role, unless
the Soviets are willing to ask of their Arab friends what we are
going to propose to our Israeli friends. So, I think that American
mediation is the best course.''
</TEXT>
