<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua-Ortega     02-22 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Ortega,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan President Says More Contra Aid Means More War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega charged that
U.S. lawmakers who are seeking to secure additional aid for the
Contra rebels are egotistically toying with Nicaraguan lives.
   Ortega said in a two-hour speech to the National Assembly on
Sunday that, despite a Feb. 4 vote in the House of Representatives
against a Reagan administration request for more Contra aid, ``this
chapter has not closed.''
   President Reagan, he said, will look for a way to get more money
to the rebels by calling the assistance humanitarian aid.
   ``If the (U.S.) Congress approves that type of financing, it
would be erasing the word peace that it wrote when it voted against
the funds, and would be putting (in) the word `war,''' Ortega said
in the speech, broadcast over a government national radio network.
   ``That is the little game of Congress, a Congress where many
interests, particularly egotistical, are involved and which is
playing with life, hunger, security and the self-determination of
the Nicaraguan people,'' he said.
   The House voted against Reagan's plan to give the Contras a
$36.2 million aid package that included about $3.6 million for
weapons and ammunition to help them in their 6{-year-old fight
against the leftist Sandinista government.
   Democrats prevailed in the vote, 219-211, after the party's
leadership promised members there would be a later chance to vote
on a package of Contra aid for food, clothing, medicine and shelter
only.
   A group of Democrats, together with one or two Republicans who
voted against the president's plan, have been trying to draw up
such an alternative.
   One proposal for the alternative aid request would give the
Contras humanitarian aid at a rate of about $1.8 million a month.
   Ortega said 26,500 people have been killed since the war began
and 23,882 wounded. Other, unofficial sources, have put the death
toll at more than 40,000. The war, he said, has cost the country
$3.6 billion.
   Damage to the economy was estimated at $376 million last year,
exceeding the $270 million in export earnings, he said.
   Even so, he said, the economy advanced at an inflation-adjusted
rate of 1.7 percent in 1987. It contracted 0.4 percent in 1986.
   The inflation rate skyrocketed to 1,347 percent last year, well
ahead of the 657 percent of the previous year.
   The government last week unveiled a new program to try to
control runaway inflationm. It introduced a new cordoba currency,
boosted prices of basic goods, increased salaries and cracked down
on speculators.
</TEXT>
