<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Markets     02-22 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down Slightly Against Yen; Stocks Close Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell slightly against the Japanese yen
today, closing at 129.95 yen, while stock prices in Tokyo rose
moderately.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which posted a 98.05-point gain last Friday, added
another 73.30 points or 0.29 percent to close the day's trading at
24,846.71 points. Volume in the first section was 870 million
shares.
   The dollar opened trading Monday at 129.95 yen, down 0.58 yen
from last Friday's close of 130.53, and ranged between 129.87 and
130.05 yen. Trading totaled $2.526 billion.
   ``There's absolutely nothing going on'' in the foreign exchange
market, said a trader at Goldman Sachs who spoke on condition of
anonymity. ``The dollar's been moving in a 10-point range in
inactive trading. It's extremely, extremely quiet.''
   Traders said the dollar's relative stability against the yen was
behind the recent upswing of stock prices in Tokyo.
   Prospects of favorable trade and economic figures for fiscal
1987, which ends March 31, helped lift stock prices, said Kunihiro
Ono of Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   Other traders said share prices also were boosted by a report
published over the weekend that the Economic Planning Agency
foresees a 4 percent growth in Japan's gross national product in
1988.
   Dealers said buying interest faded and volume sagged after a
sharp rally in the morning session, as investors began to worry
about a correction following the market`s rally last week.
   Foods and retails, such as Seven-Eleven, had a fast speculative
run, along with securities companies and steels, which were
stronger earlier in the day but eased off in later trading,
according to Stephen Codrington of Jardine Fleming Ltd.
   Light electricals, constructions and pharmaceuticals also
firmed, while department stores and textiles fell back, other
traders said.
</TEXT>
