<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Portugal     02-22 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Portugal,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Looking for Agreement on Portuguese Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration is likely to find
out during a visit by Portuguese Prime Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva
this week if a proposed $46 million increase in military aid
satisfies Portugal's request for more compensation for U.S. use of
a major air base.
   Cavaco Silva's first trip to Washington since he took office
last August is expected to be dominated by discussion of the base
situation, which has injected a dose of sourness into an otherwise
sweet relationship between the two NATO nations.
   Portugal is getting $117 million in U.S. assistance this fiscal
year _ in NATO only Turkey and Greece got more _ but that was $30
million less than the fiscal 1987 payment.
   In the budget sent to Congress last week, Portugal would get
$163 million.
   Portugal wants $207 million a year, which U.S. negotiators
pledged in 1983 they would make their ``best efforts'' to provide
in return for a base-rights agreement that gives the United States
access to Lajes Air Base in the mid-Atlantic Azores islands.
   Besides being part of the NATO chain of bases, Lajes is viewed
by the Pentagon as an indispensable refueling point for mammoth
transports heading for the Middle East and Africa.
   The grumbling in Lisbon is similar to noises being heard in the
Philippines, Greece, Turkey and Spain _ allies seeking more
benefits from the United States in return for use of military
installations.
   ``Security cooperation is an important part of the relationship
between the United States and Portugal and obviously will be
discussed during the prime minister's visit,'' the Portuguese
embassy said in its announcement of Cavaco Silva's meetings, which
include talks with Reagan on Wednesday.
   ``There will be further discussions about promised economic
assistance,'' the embassy said.
   Under the terms of the base rights agreement, Portugal has the
right to demand a review of the pact at its mid-term, which occurs
this month. The form of the review is not spelled out, but U.S.
officials have said it could result in a demand by Portugal for
specific amounts of additional aid.
   After Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci visited Lisbon Feb.
3-4, the two countries announced an agreement under which Portugal
would hold off calls for a formal review of the pact and the United
States would supply surplus military equipment to compensate for
the aid cutback.
   Since then, however, the agreement has come under attack.
   Portuguese President Mario Soares said the surplus equipment
agreement is unsatisfactory.
   In a speech last Thursday, Portuguese Foreign Minister Joao de
Deus Pinheiro said he favored ``an update'' of the defense accord.
   Officials of both countries _ notably Pentagon and State
Department officers sympathetic to Portugal's requests and
frustrated by budget strictures _ have said the dispute is purely
financial.
   Unlike in Spain and Greece, where the voters support a reduced
U.S. military presence, there is widespread support for the
American bases in Portugal.
   ``The upcoming Portuguese-American negotiations shouldn't be
dramatized,'' Pinhero said. ``Our common interests and views far
exceed any possible bilateral difficulties.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
