<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NuclearMissiles 1stLd-Writethru a0444 02-22 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Missiles, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0444, 710</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Recasts 2nd graf and adds new 3rd graf clarifying Carlucci
agreeing to congressional request to keep Midgetman program alive.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new Pentagon budget has reopened the
bitter fight between Congress and the Reagan administration over
the MX nuclear missile and how to build America's future arsenal of
land-based atomic weapons.
   And in the latest round _ on a possible successor to the MX
missile _ past administration critics have gained grudging support
from an unusual quarter _ Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci.
   Although he personally doesn't think much of the Midgetman
missile, the congressionally designated heir apparent to the MX,
Carlucci has agreed to request enough funding to keep the project
alive until a new administration can make the final decision.
   The budget sent to the Democratic-controlled Congress last week
proposed $807 million to buy a dozen more of the 10-warhead MX
weapons, along with $793 million for a new method of basing the
giant missiles aboard trains.
   The current plan is to put 50 of the weapons into silos on
Warren Air Force Base in southeastern Wyoming. The Air Force also
wants to build 50 more and deploy two each aboard 25
specially-built trains.
   But Carlucci told the Senate Armed Services Committee last week
that if it were up to him, he would put all 100 MX weapons on the
trains.
   ``We badly need a survivable missile system,'' he explained.
   That statement echoed criticisms by MX opponents, who claimed
during a series of long fights in Reagan's first term that putting
the MX into land-based silos would make the missiles vulnerable to
a first strike by accurate Soviet missiles.
   Former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger strongly disagreed
and pushed hard for approval for 100 of the weapons. They were to
replace some of the aging Minuteman missiles which now make up the
heart of America's land-based nuclear missile force.
   After a series of long fights, Congress finally agreed to put 50
of the weapons in land-based silos and then approved the
single-warhead Midgetman weapon as a successor to the MX. The Air
Force agreed with that plan, but later Reagan decided to try to win
approval for the second 50 MX weapons.
   Even as the budget was unveiled Thursday, MX critics were lining
up to oppose the railroad-basing plan.
   ``The debate concerning survivability has been raging for years
and apparently will continue,'' said Rep. Nicholas Mavroules,
D-Mass., one of the chief opponents of the weapon in Reagan's first
term.
   ``Based on the available data, serious questions remain
regarding the safety and survivability of that type of deployment
system,'' said Mavroules. ``Because of these lingering questions,
Congress must be concerned about the rashness of this proposal.''
   Another critic, Rep. Les AuCoin, D-Ore., said ``rail garrison
would be vulnerable to more than Soviet missiles. Because
commercial rail lines would be used, the threat of terrorism and
sabotage must be considered serious.''
   ``Additionally, in light of the recent problems surrounding the
safety of our nation's rail system, it is not pleasant to
contemplate the thought of nuclear warheads being trundled around
through populated areas.''
   Both Mavroules and AuCoin promised to try to eliminate all money
for the rail-basing plan.
   Carlucci also said he wanted to kill the Midgetman program
because budgetary restraints made it necessary to choose between
Midgetman and the MX. But to meet a congressional request, he
included $200 million to keep the program alive until a new
president takes office next year.
   That met with the approval of Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of
the Senate Armed Services Committee and a Midgetman supporter.
   ``I felt it would be a mistake to zero the program and I wanted
it kept alive for the next administration. This money seems to me
to meet that request,'' said Nunn, who helped defeat an attempt to
kill the Midgetman program two months ago.
   Of the 50 MX weapons to be deployed, 33 are now in their silos,
but only 20 of those are operational because of problems in
delivering the guidance systems. But Carlucci said that all 50 will
be in the silos by the end of 1988.
</TEXT>
