<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 0434EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FlexibleFuel     02-22 0705</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Flexible Fuel,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dual-Fuel Cars Seen as Protection Against Price Hikes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cars and trucks capable of switching from one
fuel to another could discourage future oil price increases by
foreign producers, the Energy Department says.
   The department says dual-fuel motor vehicles, in sufficient
numbers on American highways, would offer that benefit even if the
foreign oil producers also supplied the second, non-petroleum fuel.
   In the first of a series of reports planned for this year on
alternate fuels, the department says enough twin-fuel vehicles
would have to be in use to switch away from about 1 million barrels
of oil a day.
   The United States uses almost 17 million barrels of oil per day,
a bit more than a third of it imported, and five-eighths of it
devoted to transportation.
   It would take a decade of spending several billion dollars a
year to build the plants and distribution system necessary for
significant switching ability to methanol or natural gas, the
report said.
   The department and many in the oil industry are worried that
imports will account for 60 percent of supplies by the middle of
the next decade. That would give the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries leverage it has been unable to exercise in the
surplus-sloshed soft markets of recent years, because OPEC will
then have the only spare production capacity available in the world.
   The department promised more detailed reports on the experience
of other countries, supply prospects, environmental effects and a
cost-benefit analysis later this year. The most recent report was
described as ``context and analytical framework.''
   ``Whatever strategy the country goes with has got to withstand
cyclical swings in oil prices,'' said Scott Campbell, director of
the office of policy, planning and analysis, whose staff did the
work.
   Though other approaches should be pursued, only methanol
``appears at this stage of the assessment to be a fuel with clear
potential for meeting a significant percentage of this country's
transportation fuel demand in the short run,'' the study said.
   The study director, Vito Stagliano, estimated that a dual-fuel
car would cost $50 to $350 more in volume production. Ford Motor
Co. already has produced several hundred.
   To cut oil demand by 1 million barrels a day, the report
estimated these needs:
   _Ten new methanol plants each year for a decade, costing a total
of $20 billion to $25 billion.
   _Development of 10,000 to 30,000 alternative-capable retail
outlets a year, with an eventual total of 150,000 stations costing
more than $5 billion in all. No cost estimate was given for
changing pipelines, barges and other distribution facilities to
methanol.
   _Methanol-compatible vehicles entering the motor vehicle fleet
at a rate of 1.5 million to 8 million a year. There are more than
170 million cars, trucks and buses on U.S. highways now.
   Except in emergencies, motorists would not use methanol unless
it were ``perceptibly less expensive'' _ more than two gallons of
methanol are needed to provide the mileage obtainable with a gallon
of gasoline.
   ``Nevertheless, it is conceivable that the very prospect of
seeing large volumes of the demand for oil translate into demand
for alternative fuels will in itself discourage future increases in
oil prices,'' the report said.
   Methanol is made most cheaply from natural gas. The report
observed that although the United States is the world's biggest
methanol producer, it has been a net importer since 1982, and
Middle Eastern countries can produce at half the U.S. cost.
   A future methanol market ``could be dominated by OPEC oil
suppliers, or it might be one in which those countries play a less
significant role,'' the report said.
   Middle Eastern countries could supply U.S. methanol needs
economically, but ``any increase in the total potential supply of
liquid fuels in the world should tend to enhance U.S. energy
security, because it would cause the world energy market to loosen
up,'' the report said.
   A methanol cartel that raised prices would call forth increased
supplies from elsewhere, just as oil output expanded elsewhere in
the 1970s after OPEC began steep price hikes, the report said.
   ``Because feedstocks of natural gas are more widely distributed,
even greater price competition would result in this case,'' it said.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
