<DOCNO> AP880222-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 0435EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseDollars     02-22 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Dollars,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Makes Most from Military Contracts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California continued to pace the nation last
year in the receipt of Pentagon contracts despite suffering a
significant drop in awards compared to the previous year, new
reports show.
   California also maintained its position as the state with the
largest Defense Department payroll, as well as the No. 1
destination for military retirees. Payroll and pension checks
combined pumped $12.7 billion into the California economy in fiscal
1987, the reports show.
   Nationally, the Pentagon awarded $147.12 billion in contracts
for work performed inside the United States during fiscal 1987 _ a
drop of $2.1 billion compared to fiscal 1986.
   It also paid out $84.5 billion in payroll and pensions during
the year to individuals retired or working inside the United
States, up $2.7 billion compared to the previous year.
   Of that $84.5 billion grand total, $26.3 billion went to pay
civilian employees in the 50 states; $34 billion went to pay
active-duty personnel in the 50 states; $5.5 billion went to pay
reservists and National Guard members, and $18.7 billion went to
retirees.
   The new figures are contained in two annual statistical reports
_ one known as the Defense Department ``Atlas'' and the other
entitled ``Prime Contract Awards by State'' _ that attempt to show
how Pentagon spending is affecting the 50 states.
   Those figures will be augmented in the coming months with
additional reports on such things as the nation's top defense
contractors; total contract actions, including work outside the
United States, and civilian and military employee comparisons.
   The state statistics for fiscal 1987 show that the 12 months
ending last Sept. 30 produced some unusually wide swings in
Pentagon spending patterns.
   For example, California easily paced the nation with military
contractors in that state winning $24.5 billion in awards. But that
total represented an 11.6 percent drop, or $3.2 billion less than
the $27.7 billion in contracts awarded in fiscal 1986.
   Similarly, Texas tumbled from second place to fourth in the
contract rankings because of 20.9 percent decline in awards, while
Virginia climbed from eighth to fifth thanks to a whopping 44.5
percent increase in awards.
   Texas finished the fiscal year with awards totaling $8.65
billion, while Virginia finished with $7.8 billion. Second place
went to New York with $9.6 billion, while third place went to
Massachusetts with $8.69 billion.
   The remainder of the top 10 included Missouri at sixth place
with $6 billion; Florida with $5.8 billion; Connecticut with $5
billion; Maryland with $4.75 billion, and Ohio with $4.5 billion.
   Even setting aside contracting, California benefited the most
from the Defense Department's presence, with $12.7 billion flowing
into the state in pension checks and salaries for civilian,
active-duty and reserve employees.
   Virginia, Texas, Florida and Georgia rounded out the top five,
retaining the same positions in fiscal 1987 they had the year
before. Virginia saw $8.8 billion flow into its borders in total
compensation, compared to $6.6 billion for Texas, $5.6 billion in
Florida and $3.2 billion in Georgia.
   The remainder of the top 10 included North Carolina with $3
billion in total compensation; Maryland with $2.74 billion;
Washington with $2.66 billion; Pennsylvania with $2.4 billion, and
South Carolina with $2.3 billion.
   Breaking down those figures to focus on retiree compensation,
the most money again flowed into California _ totaling $2.7
billion. Next was Texas with $1.9 billion, followed by Florida with
$1.88 billion; Virginia with $1.4 billion and Georgia with $682.5
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880222-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 0435EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DrugStudies     02-22 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Studies,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Effectiveness Of Anti-Drug Programs Needs Evaluating,
Investigators Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal watchdog says it is time to use a
few of the millions of dollars spent annually on anti-drug
education to answer a simple question: What works and what doesn't?
   That was the conclusion reached by Inspector General Richard
Kusserow after he was asked by the White House to evaluate a
variety of programs.
   In weeks of studying Nancy Reagan's ``Just Say No'' campaign and
two other antidrug efforts targeted at the very young,
investigators found more questions than answers.
   The main recommendation in a preliminary version of Kusserow's
report is that federal agencies ``should develop an evaluation
strategy to include long- and short-term evaluations of the
implementation and effectiveness of youth drug education programs.''
   Specifically, he said those strategies should be devised by the
Education Department and the Alcohol, Drug Abuse and Mental Health
Administration.
   Kusserow, charged with monitoring programs of the Department of
Health and Human Services, agreed to discuss the study after The
Associated Press obtained a draft copy.
   He acknowledged that the document lacks the precision typically
associated with IG reports, but said that should not be read as an
indictment of any of the programs surveyed. In fact, he said, ``It
looks like they're on the right track.''
   But the former FBI agent said his investigators' attempts to
determine whether the programs are ``just fluff and puffery or
real'' were hampered by lack of measurable data.
   ``There is no evidence that seems to be available to tell us how
successful these programs are,'' he said. ``I think we've put the
first layer in, but if you want to have an ongoing, effective
program we're going to get more sophisticated. You cannot get
sophisticated until you start developing some objective criteria
and some instruments to measure progress.
   ``Our concern is that if these programs satisfy themselves that
they can relax on their laurels and sort of coast on to ever
increasing success, I think they're deluding themselves. If we want
to increase the effectiveness of the programs we are going to have
some sort of measurement that would allow them to know what are
successful techniques versus the less successful techniques.''
   Kusserow added: ``You're not talking about hoards of money to do
that. You're just saying that somewhere along the line they're
going to have to set aside some resource to look at how they can go
about developing a model they can measure.''
   And developing such measurements, he said, are beyond the scope
of the IG's office.
   In addition to ``Just Say No,'' a loosely knit association of
local efforts operating under a private foundation, the IG study
looked at the Boys Clubs of America's ``Smart Moves'' and the
National Federation of Parents' ``Drug Free Youth.''
   ``These programs sort of spontaneously came into being,''
Kusserow said, noting that each is financed almost totally at the
community level.
   He said each of the three should consider developing its own
criteria for measuring success and that someone _ perhaps the
federal Alcohol, Drug Abuse and Mental Health Administration _
``might want to ask which one is best.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
