<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Higgins Pleads On Videotape For Washington's Help</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines previous, a0469-76.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kidnappers of a U.S. Marine officer
serving with the United Nations released on Monday a videotaped
message from the captive in which he pleaded with the U.S.
government to meet his captors' demands.
   Lt. Col. William R. Higgins appeared reading from a statement in
the 70-second tape that was released by the Organization of the
Oppressed on Earth to a Western news agency office in Beirut.
   He wore a dark green sweater and a newly grown beard.
   ``I, William Higgins, in order to get me released, these demands
have to be met,'' said the 43-year-old decorated Vietnam veteran
and one-time military assistant to former Defense Secretary Caspar
Weinberger.
   Higgins was abducted near south Lebanon's ancient port city of
Tyre on Wednesday. In the videotape, he looked gloomy, but
physically fit.
   Higgins said President Reagan ``has to take responsibility for
the crimes he has committed against the oppressed people in the
region.''
   He listed the same demands made by his captors when they first
claimed his abduction in a statement Friday that branded the Marine
colonel a spy for the ``satanic CIA.''
   The demands, as listed by Higgins, are:
   _Withdrawal of Israeli forces from all occupied territories in
Lebanon.
   _The release of all detained Lebanese and Palestinian
Mujahedeen, or Holy Warriors, from the Khiam detention camp, in
south Lebanon, and all jails of ``the Zionist regime in occupied
Palestine.''
   _An end to U.S. intervention in Lebanon and to U.S. diplomatic
missions to the Middle East.
