<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Celeste Predicts Presidential Nominations Will Hinge on Ohio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Richard Celeste says he believes the Ohio
primary election this May will determine the presidential nominees
for both the Democrats and the Republicans.
   Celeste said Sunday he thinks the state will play the pivotal
role because the May 3 primary will fall at a key time in the
nominating process and because of the nature of the state.
   ``I think that the Ohio primary will determine who the nominee
is for each of the parties,'' Celeste said in answer to a question
at a news conference. ``They (the winners) may not have all the
delegates, but I think ... it will be clear that they are going to
be the first-ballot choice.''
   ``Any nominee understands that to win the general election, they
must carry Ohio,'' said Celeste. ``Our state is kind of a fulcrum
in the political process, it seems to me.''
   Celeste said it is too early for him to try to influence the
nominating process by endorsing a candidate, but that he may do so
prior to the Ohio primary.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Republicans Vote To Ban Pre-Primary Endorsements</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The California Republican Party has
voted to prohibit any endorsement by either the statewide party or
any official Republican county central committee prior to the GOP
primary.
   In a three-day convention, noteworthy principally for the
absence of all of the party's presidential candidates who are
campaigning in states with ``Super Tuesday'' primaries on March 8,
the only other significant business was adoption of new rules for
naming members to the party's governing board.
   The ban on endorsements Sunday was in response to a 1986 court
ruling that a state law prohibiting such endorsements violated
constitutional free speech guarantees. However, that ruling left
the political parties free to adopt any rules they want restricting
themselves.
   Contrary to the GOP action Sunday, the California Democratic
party is expected to adopt rules permitting pre-primary
endorsements at its statewide convention next month.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>O'Neill Gives Primary Scorecard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The presidential primary scorecard, in the
view of former House Speaker Thomas P. ``Tip'' O'Neill, allows for
more than one ballot at the Democratic convention and division
among Republicans.
   In his first public appearance since surgery late last year for
rectal cancer and an enlarged prostate, O'Neill told a convention
crowd of 2,000 on Saturday that Missouri Congressman Dick Gephardt
doesn't have the financing to run a successful race and Tennessee
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. may have waited too late to join the fray.
   Jesse Jackson will control a sizable block of votes and make the
convention, which O'Neill believes ``is going to go more than one
ballot, and there are going to be a lot of smoke-filled rooms.''
   O'Neill backs a fellow Massachusetts politician, Gov. Michael
Dukakis.
   On the GOP side, O'Neill said Vice President George Bush got his
timing back with his win in New Hampshire, but Senate Minority
Leader Bob Dole ``has a Democratic style and can distance himself
from the administration.''
   But internal strife may hurt Republicans, he told members of the
National Electrical Manufacturers Representatives Association.
</TEXT>
