<HEAD>With PM-Robertson's Prospects Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some comments from political observers about Pat
Robertson in the Super Tuesday states:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   NORTH CAROLINA: Merle Black, political scientist at the
University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill: ``I think Bush's
biggest competition in the South will come from Robertson. He's a
big unknown. We don't know how strong he is, but he's likely much
stronger here than in New Hampshire.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MISSOURI: GOP Chairman Hillard Selck: ``It does not appear to be
in the cards for Pat Robertson to make a strong showing in
Missouri. He's probably going to pick up a few delegates. But you
can't go around the nation and pick up a few delegates here and a
few there and expect to win the nomination.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ARKANSAS: State Democratic Executive Director Kip Blakely,
assessing Robertson's support: ``Remember the Right to Life march a
couple of weekends ago? It was raining and it was a Saturday
morning and it was freezing. There were over 3,000 people who
turned out. That's Pat Robertson.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   TEXAS: GOP Chairman George Strake: ``I think he's going to be
present and accounted for. He's going to pick up some delegates.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   TENNESSEE: Republican Chairman Jim Henry: ``He's going to get
40,000 or 50,000 votes in Tennessee. That will probably give him a
solid third (behind Bush-Dole or Dole-Bush).''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MASSACHUSETTS: Paul Cellucci, coordinator for George Bush:
``We're not expecting any invisible army. We haven't seen any signs
of that, although there is (Robertson) support out there. I'm not
nervous at this point. New Hampshire makes me feel a lot better.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   OKLAHOMA: Republican chairman Tom Cole: ``I think Pat Robertson
causes us a lot fewer problems than Jesse Jackson causes
Democrats.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MARYLAND: Former GOP Chairman Allan Levey, a Bush supporter: ``I
think 10 percent would be the top that he (Robertson) would get.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON: Bruce Hawkins, Robertson's state director: ``New
Hampshire was actually a positive for our people. They look (at
Roberton's last place finish) and said, `We will not let that
happen here.'''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   RHODE ISLAND: GOP Chairman J. Michael Levesque, forecasting a
weak Robertson showing: ``I have not seen any kind of signal or
signs that there is a significantly large evangelical movement in
Rhode Island.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   GEORGIA: Former state GOP chairman Bob Bell: ``If those people
who are voting for Pat Robertson stay in the Republican column,
there's a whole lot of Democrats who are going to be out of
office.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LOUISIANA: Robertson state director Billy E. McCormack, citing a
6 percent jump in Republican registration since October: ``We feel
like we were responsible for 90 to 95 percent of them.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   FLORIDA: Rep. David Troxler, R-Fla., one of the few elected
officials supporting Robertson: ``I do believe that if he takes a
substantial number of Super Tuesday delegates _ 55 or 60 percent _
he will be the nominee.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ALABAMA: Al LaPierre, executive director of the state Democratic
Party, on Robertson's claim that the Russians have missiles in
Cuba: ``I don't think it hurts him with his voters. They think it's
true.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   KENTUCKY: Harold Rogers, state chairman for Bush, on Robertson's
support: ``Essentially it's still limited to the religious
conservatives. I don't see him breaking out beyond that very narrow
base, except in spotty cases, here and there.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MISSISSIPPI: Ed Cole, chairman of the Mississippi Dem Party,
says: ``I think he's obviously going to be a real strong factor in
the Republican primary. I think he will wreak havoc on the
Republican organization in Mississippi.''
</TEXT>
