<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Kidnap     02-22 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Kidnap,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Wants All US Hostages in Lebanon Freed Before He Leaves
Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan says nothing would make him
happier during his last year in office than to see all of the
American hostages in Lebanon freed.
   ``I'd like that better than anything else,'' Reagan told
reporters during a black-tie reception Sunday night for the
nation's governors. He said the administration is ``doing
everything we can and exploring every avenue'' to free Marine Lt.
Col. William R. Higgins, who was kidnapped Wednesday near the
ancient port city of Tyre, Lebanon.
   ``It's just so difficult,'' Reagan said. ``It is such a terrible
situation and you're afraid you'll do something that will harm them
(the hostages). We don't know who they (the captors) are or where
they are.''
   Higgins headed a 76-man observer group attached to a U.N.
peacekeeping force in south Lebanon. There are eight other
Americans as well as 14 other foreigners missing in Lebanon.
   ``I just feel anytime a citizen of this country is unjustly
denied their constitutional rights, it's the obligation of this
government to come to their aid,'' Reagan said.
   Then, looking at the reporters, he said, ``I wish you would stop
calling them terrorists and start calling them cowards.''
</TEXT>
