<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CalQuake     02-22 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cal Quake,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Central California Hit With Moderate Earthquake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAKERSFIELD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake shook central
California, jarring residents awake as it sent dishes rattling and
house beams creaking but caused no injuries or major damage,
officials said.
   The quake, measuring 3.9 on the Richter scale, hit at 11:43 p.m.
Sunday, and was centered about 40 miles west-northwest of
Bakersfield, said Robert Finn, spokesman for the California
Institute of Technology's seismology laboratory in Pasadena.
   Shaking was felt over a broad area in Kern and San Luis Obispo
counties, and as far north as Paso Robles, about 75 miles away.
   ``It rattled some dishes and caused some attic beams to creak,
but after the initial fright, most of our callers settled right
down,'' said San Luis Obispo County Sheriff's Sgt. Gary Hogan.
   ``We've had about a dozen calls, spread out over about 40
miles,'' Hogan said. ``It woke people up, but there weren't any
reports of injury or damage.''
   Residents in Bakersfield and nearby Taft felt the ground shake,
but Taft police officers said they barely noticed the temblor.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. An earthquake of 3.5 on the open-ended scale can
cause slight damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5
considerable damage, 6 severe damage.
</TEXT>
