<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Taiwain-Hijack     02-22 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwain-Hijack,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crew And Passengers Foil Attempted Hijacking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passengers and crew members on a China
Airlines flight today prevented a Taiwanese man from hijacking the
plane to Beijing by hitting him over the head and wrestling him to
the floor, the airline said.
   The Boeing 737 jetliner was carrying 114 people, including one
American, on a flight from Taipei to the southern port city of
Kaohsiung, 240 miles away, when the hijack attempt by the
29-year-old man occurred.
   The man, an employee at a knife grinding shop, was carrying two
fake grenades made of wood and a slip of paper from a fortuneteller
predicting a year of bad luck, the airline said at a news
conference.
   According to the airline, the would-be hijacker was subdued
after a crew member hit him on the head with a ``hard object.''
   No injuries were reported among the other 106 passengers and
seven crew members aboard the jetliner. The plane landed at
Kaohsiung and later returned to Taipei where members of the cabin
crew appeared at a press conference.
   Stewardess Lee Lin said she was passing out drinks to the
passengers about 20 minutes after takeoff when the would-be
hijacker, Chien Chu-yuan, handed her a slip of paper demanding the
plane be diverted to Beijing.
   ``He threatened on the slip of paper that he would kill all of
us with his two grenades if we didn't fly to Beijing,'' she said.
The man later said he wanted to go to Taipei, but crew members said
he was nervous and probably meant Beijing. The would-be hijacker
claimed to have two partners, but the airline has ruled out that
possibility.
   The stewardess asked four stewards for help as most passengers
remained unaware of the unfolding drama. The stewards and a few
passengers then pounced on the hijacker when he tried to show the
phony grenades to the passengers and subdued him after a 10-minute
scuffle.
   ``We asked the captain to fly in circles and told the hijacker
we would divert to Beijing,'' said steward Chi Hsi-an.
   Police said the would-be hijacker, a native Taiwanese who worked
in his brother's knife grinding shop, was in custody in Kaohsuing.
Attempted hijacking can carry the death sentence in Taiwan.
   Officials were unsure how many foreigners were aboard the plane
besides the one American. Among the passengers was Yu Chen
Yueh-ying, the Kaohsiung county magistrate who is an opposition
member.
   In 1985, an attempted hijacking occurred aboard a China
Airlines' Boeing 737 flying the same route with 107 passengers. In
that incident, a homesick army sergeant who wanted to see his
parents was overpowered by crew members after he seized a
stewardess.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880222-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 0614EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GromykoMemoirs     02-22 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gromyko Memoirs,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Leader: Mao Wanted to Lure U.S. Troops Into Nuclear Trap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Andrei Gromyko says he rebuffed
Mao Tse-tung's proposal that the Soviet Union help lure U.S. troops
into China where they would be attacked by nuclear weapons, a
newspaper reported today.
   Gromyko's two-volume memoir covers nearly 50 years of Soviet
diplomacy, including dealings with nine American presidents,
according to The New York Times, which said an advance copy was
made available to its Moscow bureau.
   In ``Memoir,'' expected to be distributed to bookstores in the
next few weeks by its Soviet publisher, Gromyko says Mao's proposal
came during a secret visit to Beijing in August 1958.
   Gromyko, Soviet foreign minister from 1957 to 1985, said he was
surprised by the audacity of the plan, according to the Times.
   ``The scenario of war described by you cannot meet a positive
response by us,'' Gromyko said he told Mao. ``I can say this with
certainty.''
   Gromyko, 78, wrote that Mao was anticipating an American attack
on China because of tensions over the islands of Quemoy and Matsu,
off mainland China.
   Mao said Chinese forces would retreat to the heartland of China,
luring American soldiers after them. Then, Mao proposed, ``the
Soviet Union should catch them with all its means,'' Gromyko wrote.
   At the time, China was expecting to receive nuclear weapons from
the Soviet Union, but Moscow withdrew their offer in 1959. Soviet
officials later accused Mao of recklessness. China exploded its own
nuclear bomb in 1964.
   Gromyko denies reports that he misled President Kennedy about
the presence of Soviet missiles in Cuba during the 1962 missile
crisis.
   ``In spite of several allegations circulating in the West, not
once in the whole course of the conversation did Kennedy raise the
question of the presence of Soviet missiles in Cuba,'' he wrote.
   ``Consequently, I did not have to answer whether or not there
were such weapons in Cuba.''
   Gromyko, who dealt with every U.S. president from Franklin D.
Roosevelt to Ronald Reagan reserved special praise for Roosevelt.
   He describes Roosevelt as someone ``who knew how to conduct
conversation freely, without any tension,'' and a leader who knew
how to make and carry out policy.
   He also described meetings with American stars such as Marilyn
Monroe, whom he met during a Hollywood reception for Soviet
officials in 1959. He said they exchanged a few words, and he
recalled her ``special and indescribable attractiveness.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
