<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     02-22 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every year the Chamber of Commerce manages
to find volunteers to taste more than 100 bottles of homemade wine
for the Newport Wine and Seafood Festival.
   It's hard work, some of the 27 volunteer judges tapped this year
said over the weekend.
   ``We taste a lot of different wines and try to decide, try to be
objective,'' Opal White said. ``We don't want to say anything bad
about them, but some of them ....'' She trailed off, perhaps not
wishing to leave a bitter aftertaste.
   Since wine can be made from nearly anything organic, some of the
entries are, well, unusual. Garlic, dried kiwi fruit, rose petals,
zucchini and even sauerkraut have found their way into bottles
during past competitions.
   ``A little sauerkraut wine is good on a cold night,'' judge
Joseph Swafford said dryly.
   Stomach aches are unlikely, since the rules say the judges are
supposed to sniff, swirl, taste and spit. Still, the volunteer
judges must sign a waiver releasing the chamber from any blame
should they be struck with a sudden illness, and nobody else is
allowed the taste the amateur wines that are displayed at the
festival.
   The festival, which opened Friday and runs through Feb. 28,
allows the public to taste commercial wines, and compare their
choices with results from a panel of professional judges.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whales are coming to Lake Michigan.
   The Shedd Aquarium says its Oceanarium, a $43 million expansion
project that should be completed by 1990, will exhibit six whales,
four dolphins, several sea otters and a rookery of penguins.
   The Oceanarium design calls for huge rocks, cliffs and 35-foot
trees on 1.8 acres of what was Lake Michigan before 30 million
gallons of water was siphoned so construction could begin below
lake level in August.
   To give the illusion the whales are in the ocean, a
600-foot-long 35-foot-high picture window will overlook the lake
from behind their tanks.
   ``I've got a gut feeling that we might even have to turn people
away,'' aquarium director William P. Braker said recently as cranes
pounded 75-foot-long steel pilings for the foundation. ``We had 1.1
million visitors in 1987, and with the Oceanarium, I think we may
hit 2 million.''
   Three milk-white, 15-foot beluga whales will be airlifted from
Churchill, Manitoba on the Hudson Bay, aquarium officials said. As
whales go, Manitobas are small, but the largest animal now at Shedd
is a 7-foot nurse shark.
   Three more Pacific black whales, about the size of Manitobas,
will be brought from Japan, the aquarium staff said.
   Braker said Shedd, which opened in 1929 and is the world's
largest indoor aquarium at 230,000 square feet, ``needed a good
shot in the arm to bring it out of many years of being static.''
   Money for the Oceanarium includes $5 million each from the state
and the Chicago Park District. The aquarium has spent $8 million
and hopes to raise the remainder of the $25 million price tag
through donations.
</TEXT>
