<1ST_LINE>u i PM-NewCaledonia-Clash     02-22 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Caledonia-Clash,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstrators Injure Police, Take Hostages In New Caledonia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police clashed with about 100
separatist demonstrators today at a hospital construction site, and
authorities said 10 officers were injured and a dozen were taken
hostage in the melee.
   Philippe Berges, chief of staff at the High Commission, said the
protesters at Poindimie on the east side of the South Pacific
island were demanding a halt to work on the site. The work began
Friday.
   ``There will be no negotiations until the gendarmes have been
freed,'' Berges said.
   He said the team of gendarmes, a police force under military
direction, showed great restraint by not firing their weapons when
they were attacked with stones and sticks.
   The gendarmes fired tear gas grenades to get free of the
demonstrators, but some of the officers were captured and disarmed.
   Berges said reinforcements were being sent to the scene, where
Melanesian supporters of the Kanak Socialist National Liberation
Front, known by its French initials FLNKS, are opposed to building
of the hospital on what they say is land belonging to the Tieti
tribe.
   New Caledonia, a French overseas territory of 145,000 people
about 1,100 miles east of Australia, voted against independence in
a referendum last September.
   The indigenous Melanesians make up 42.6 percent of the
population, Europeans 37.1 percent and other nationalites the rest.
</TEXT>
