<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 0755EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0508 02-22 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0508,0600</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds Bishop obit. SUBS first graf of Woods obit to include
dropped word `was.' No PMs separates moved.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Mildred Seydell</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mildred Seydell, a globe-trotting journalist who
interviewed Benito Mussolini and covered the Scopes ``monkey
trial,'' died Saturday. She was 98.
   Ms. Seydell, a resident of suburban Roswell, once said she
``much preferred to set the stage for adventure rather than the
table for dinner.''
   Her work as a writer and columnist for Hearst publications,
including the now-defunct Atlanta Georgian newspaper, took her
around the world.
   She wrote ``Talks With Celebrities,'' including an interview
with the Italian dictator Mussolini, for Universal News Service and
27 Hearst papers.
   She also covered for Hearst the 1925 Tennessee trial of John
Scopes, a teacher indicted for illegally teaching the theory of
evolution.
   Ms. Seydell was a columnist for the Atlanta Georgian from 1926
to 1939, the year the paper closed.
   She was born Mildred Woolley and in 1910 married Paul Seydel, a
chemist she met while studying at the Sorbonne in Paris. She added
an ``l'' to Seydel and used the name professionally.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>William Claiborne Hayes Jr.</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WATERFORD, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Claiborne ``Red'' Hayes Jr., the
NASA official who greeted astronaut John Glenn after his
history-making flight in 1962, died Saturday. He was 63.
   Hayes, who spent 27 years with the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration, directed the at-sea recovery efforts that
plucked astronauts from the ocean after their space capsules had
returned to Earth.
   When Glenn was brought aboard an aircraft carrier after
America's first manned orbital flight, Hayes was the first to shake
his hand.
   Hayes joined the National Advisory Committee on Aeronautics in
1952 and was there when NASA was organized a few years later.
   Hayes directed the recovery of astronauts Glenn, Scott
Carpenter, Walter Schirra and Gus Grissom. He retired in 1979.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Makoto Miike</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Makoto Miike, the eldest member of Japan's House of
Councilors, died Saturday. He was 87.
   Miike had been a member of the upper house of the governing
Liberal Democratic Party since 1986.
   He was first elected to the House of Representatives, the lower
house, in 1949 and was postal and telecommunciations minister in
1972 in the government of Prime Minister Kakuei Tanaka.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Jim Woods</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALTAMONTE SPRINGS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Woods, a major-league
baseball announcer for six clubs during a 26-year career, died
Saturday. He was 71.
   He began his big-league career with the New York Yankees in 1953
as Mel Allen's partner. He also worked with the old New York
Giants, Pittsburgh Pirates, St. Louis Cardinals, Oakland A's and
Boston Red Sox.
   Woods left the Red Sox after the 1978 season and worked for the
USA Network on cable television before retiring.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Isabel Bishop</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Artist Isabel Bishop, a painter and printmaker,
has died of Parkinson's disease at age 85.
   Bishop, who died Friday at her home in the Riverdale section of
the Bronx, was known for her work depicting the everyday activities
of American women and for showing life as it existed around Union
Square in 1930.
   Miss Bishop studied at the Arts Students League, and began her
long series of Union Square paintings shortly after leaving the
League in 1924. She joined Manhattan's Midtown Gallery in 1932, and
remained affiliated with it for the rest of her life.
   Miss Bishop is survived by a son, Remsen Wolff, and two
granddaughters.
</TEXT>
