<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Convict'sResentencing     02-22 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Convict's Resentencing,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Resentencing Jury Recommends Death Sentence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors have recommended that a man whose
death sentence was overturned should be resentenced to die, in
spite of character witness testimony by other death row inmates who
described him as generous and caring.
   James Ernest Hitchcock, 31, was convicted and sentenced to death
in 1977 for the rape-murder of his 13-year-old stepniece. The U.S.
Supreme Court overturned his sentence last April.
   After a three-day resentencing trial, jurors voted 7-5 Saturday
to recommend that Hitchcock be executed for the crime.
   Circuit Judge Gary Formet Sr. is not required to follow the
jury's recommendation in his decision, which will be announced
Wednesday.
   Although Hitchcock confessed to the slaying shortly after his
arrest in July 1976, he later recanted and blamed the killing on
his older brother, Richard, who James said had become enraged when
he caught the defendant and victim having sex.
   Hitchcock testified Saturday he confessed to the slaying because
``I thought I was doing the right thing for my brother. ... I loved
him. I covered it up.''
   Richard Hitchcock, 38, denied the accusation last week as he did
11 years ago, when Cynthia Driggers died. He was not charged in his
stepdaughter's death.
   The resentencing jury also heard testimony Friday from eight
convicted killers, who portrayed Hitchcock as a model prisoner, a
peacemaker, teacher and generous person who should be spared from
the electric chair.
   They said Hitchcock taught them to read and write, broke up
fights and loaned them money for tennis shoes and cigarettes.
   ``Ernie doesn't belong there,'' said death row inmate James
Chandler. ``He's trying to help people ... He doesn't need to die.''
</TEXT>
