<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Stewart,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jimmy Stewart Honored At Monterey Film Festival</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTEREY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veteran actor Jimmy Stewart was honored
with a lifetime achievement award by the Monterey Film Festival at
a dinner that drew a galaxy of stars and a letter from President
Reagan.
   Actor Clint Eastwood, the mayor of nearby Carmel, presented
Stewart with the award Sunday night at the $150-a-plate, black-tie
affair that ended the three-day festival.
   Several of his leading ladies, among them Doris Day and Joan
Fontaine, were on hand as a tribute to Stewart, who turns 80 on May
20.
   Also attending were actresses Katherine Ross and Sue Ann
Langdon, actor Tab Hunter and last year's Film Festival honoree
Cliff Robertson.
   Letters were read from Reagan, a former actor, who said that
Stewart's name on a marquee was ``an iron-clad guarantee of
quality,'' and Gov. George Deukmejian, who said that Stewart
``lifted the spirits of young and old alike.''
   Stewart looked fit during his visit to the Monterey Peninsula,
though he admitted at a news conference Sunday afternoon that he is
having a hard time hearing.
   ``You'd all better speak up,'' he said with a smile.
   Of his career, Stewart said he is grateful he was able to play
so many different roles. ``I had all sorts of parts,'' he said.
``Comedy, westerns, the serious and thought-provoking.''
   Stewart, the star of such classics as ``It's a Wonderful Life''
and ``Mr. Smith Goes to Washington,'' was asked what he thought of
computer colorization of his old black and white films.
   ``Colorization is one of the most disgraceful things that ever
happened in any endeavor in this country,'' he said. ``I hope the
people who perpetrate this on others go flat broke someday soon.
   ``The actors end up with orange faces. The cameraman took all
this time, all this time to create depth and to cast the right
shadows. With colorization, people just walk around, just walk
around like painted Easter eggs.''
</TEXT>
