<2ND_LINE>PM-Death Denied,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Find Body In Trailer, Relatives Say `God Dealing With
Him'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REFORM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of a man whose decomposed body was
found about three weeks after his death apparently were convinced
that he was still alive, officials said.
   ``I understand they were seeing a voodoo man,'' Pickens County
Coroner Herbert Latham said of the deceased man and his relatives.
   Pickens County Sheriff David Abston identified the dead man as
Jessie James Latham, 42, not related to the coroner.
   The body was discovered in a bedroom in a mobile home Wednesday
by county health workers, authorities said. The coroner said the
man had been dead about three weeks.
   ``He was pretty well decomposed at the time and the odor all
around the trailer was pretty strong,'' Abston said. ``Some of the
kids playing in the yard were wearing face masks, like in an
operating room.''
   The coroner said the dead man's relatives ``tried to convince me
that he was still alive, that God was dealing with him, that he was
fine.''
   ``This was a weird case,'' he said Sunday, a day after the body
was buried.
   The coroner said that although no foul play was suspected, he
was awaiting hospital records from New York, where Latham had
received some treatment, before announcing the cause of death.
   The coroner said Latham apparently was aware he was suffering
from a fatal disease. The autopsy did not reveal the exact disease,
he said.
   Abston said Latham returned to Alabama recently from New York,
and was picked up at the Tuscaloosa Airport by his sister,
Catherine Latham, who took him to a motel in Reform. The two stayed
there for two weeks.
   Dilip Bhakta, the motel manager, said he never saw Latham, but
asked Latham's sister to leave the motel Feb. 2 ``because of the
smell.''
   ``She never would let anyone come in the room and would meet our
maids at the door to get materials,'' Bhakta said.
   Bhakta said the odor ``was very strong, very offensive'' and
that there were several complaints from other guests.
   Ms. Latham said she took her brother to a man in Hale County who
told him to drink goat's milk with some pills he gave him. She said
she took her brother to the mobile home on Feb. 2.
   The nine occupants of the trailer included two infants and
several teen-agers, the coroner said.
   Ms. Latham dismissed the claim that her brother was treated by a
``voodoo doctor.''
   Abston said she told him that her brother was alive when he was
moved and did not die until the day authorities found his body.
   L.C. Keasler, director of the Pickens County Department of Human
Resources, said agency workers went to the trailer Feb. 14 after an
anonymous tip, but were refused entrance. The agency workers
returned Wednesday with police.
   Asked if any supernatural elements or voodoo were involved in
Latham's treatment, his sister told The Tuscaloosa News on
Saturday: ``I don't like to use that word. I'm not working for the
devil _ I work for God.
   ``All I could do was minister to him. He's in God's hands now.''
</TEXT>
