<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Boitano-GoldMedal 1stLd-Writethru a0535 02-22 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boitano-Gold Medal, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0535,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boitano Talks About Winning the Gold Medal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, ``This time ...,' to CORRECT silver medal to
1,500 meter speed skating, sted 5,000 meter. A longer version moved
on the sports wire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER PARMELEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CALGARY, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He didn't win the 6.0 scores that signal
an absolutely flawless program. But to figure skater Brian Boitano,
his gold medal-winning performance at the Olympics was the ultimate
``10.''
   ``This time, it was perfect,'' the 24-year-old Californian said
one day after he defeated friend and rival Brian Orser of Canada to
become the only U.S. Olympic gold medalist. The United States' only
other medals have been a bronze in the figure skating pairs and a
silver in 1,500 meter speed skating.
   ``For the first time in my life it looked better than it felt,''
Boitano told a news conference Sunday, after watching a video of
his triumphant performance. ``I'm usually so critical of myself
that I thought I'd see things I'd done wrong.
   ``Instead ... it was the first time I could say the jumps were
the best I've done and I could say, `Hey, what a good program.'
It's something you build for for years and when it happens ... it's
the ultimate.''
   Saturday night's dramatic ``Battle of the Brians'' capped 10
years of skating rivalry that saw Boitano lose the last two
meetings, at Skate Canada last fall and at the 1987 World
Championships. Each man selected his own military music and battle
colors _ blue for Boitano, red for Orser.
   Boitano, from the solemn opening notes from Carmine Coppola's
``Napoleon'' to the final seconds when he thrust his fist in the
air and wiped away a tear of elation, shone throughout.
   The four-time American titlist was first with five of the nine
judges, to Orser's four. Although they tied in points, the judges
gave Boitano the victory on better technical marks.
   Writing about his future for USA Today newspaper, Boitano said:
``It's kind of scary because you know your life is going to change,
and you don't know if you're ready for it or if you want it to
change.''
   Money, from commercial endorsements or other appearances, was
not the reason behind his drive to win the gold, he wrote for
today's edition. ``I'm sure I'll do some things with it, but it's
not why I treasure it.''
   ``It's going to be different when I go home. It's kind of scary
thinking about what it's going to be like when I get back to San
Francisco, wondering if I'll be able to slip in and out everywhere
without being recognized. I worry about privacy, about always being
on show. `Brain Boitano seen drinking a wine,''' he said.
</TEXT>
