<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Castro-Missiles     02-22 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Castro-Missiles,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talk of Soviet Missiles `Insane' _ Castro</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fidel Castro, in an interview published today,
flatly denied presidential aspirant Pat Robertson's charge that the
Soviet Union has nuclear missiles in Cuba.
   In the interview, published in USA Today, Castro told the
newspaper's chairman, Allen H. Neuharth, that there ``is not even a
semblance of a Soviet missile in Cuba. Not one. I repeat, not one.''
   He also said in the weekend interview, conducted in Havana, that
talk of such missiles is ``insane.''
   Castro was asked about Robertson's recent assertions that 25
intermediate-range Soviet SS-4 and SS-5 missiles, armed with
nuclear warheads, have been stationed in Cuba. The White House
subsequently said it had ``no indication'' of any nuclear weapons
being in Cuba.
   Indeed, Castro said in the interview, ``With your sophisticated
satellite spying, you know when a cat is walking on the roof of a
house in Cuba.''
   Talk of Cuba's posing a military threat to the United States, he
said, is a ``Walt Disney fantasy.''
</TEXT>
