<DOCNO> AP880222-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 1003EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-EthiopiaAbduction     02-22 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ethiopia Abduction,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six European Relief Workers Released After Being Abducted In
Ethiopia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six European relief workers who were
abducted by rebels in Ethiopia have been released, a medical aid
official said today.
   Three Irishwomen, two Belgians and a Dutchman were set free
after being kidnapped by the Popular Front for the Liberation of
the Tigre last Thursday, said an official of the medical relief
group Medicins Sans Frontieres-Belgium.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said no
details were available and did not specify when the relief workers
were freed.
   Earlier today, Seyoum Musse, head of foreign relations for the
London office of the rebel group said the six were in good
condition.
   ``The whole aim of taking them with us was to show there are
millions of people who are beyond the reach of ... isolated
symbolic (government) food distribution centers like the one they
were stationed at,'' Musse said in a telephone interview.
   ``The aim is to dispel the government's misinformation that
millions are being reached with aid,'' he said, denying that the
group's action was an abduction.
   ``The government will not allow these workers to go outside the
place they work. For this reason we have taken them a few hours
away,'' he said. ``They are the guests of millions of starved
people.''
   The rebels abducted two Belgian doctors and a Dutch nurse of the
international aid group along with two Irish nuns and an Irish
doctor from their base in Idaga Hamous in Tigre, about 340 miles
north of the capital Addis Ababa, the medical group reported Sunday.
   Medicins San Frontieres is an international non-governmental
organization that has medical aid projects in 15 countries in
Central America, Africa, the Middle East and Asia.
   A spokesman for the doctors group initially said the relief
workers may have been abducted to treat rebel wounded. Fighting in
the northern province has been intense between the secessionist
rebels and the government of Lt. Col. Mengistu Haile Mariam.
   Musse denied that the workers had been taken to treat wounded.
   ``We have our own doctors,'' he said.
</TEXT>
