<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru   02-22 0832</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0530,0848</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Warship Fires Warning Shots At Fishing Boats</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with eight grafs to UPDATE with U.S. statement on
warning shots; picks up 7th graf pvs: U.S. officials...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. warship making its maiden voyage
on the Persian Gulf fired warning shots today at a pair of fishing
boats that crew members initially believed were attack vessels.
   A U.S. military official, asking not to be identified, said the
landing-dock ship Trenton took the action ``after it observed two
apparent Boghammar-type boats coming toward it,'' about 30 miles
off the coast of Dubai.
   He said the Trenton issued two verbal warnings, which were
ignored, and as the boats approached to within 3,300 yards ``it
fired a flare and bursts of .50-caliber machine-gun fire, at which
time the craft stopped, then veered off toward the northeast.
   ``A helicopter sent up from the frigate John A. Moore later
confirmed through observation that both were fishing boats and
neither was hit or damaged,'' the official added.
   He said the boats at first appeared to resemble the fast,
Swedish-built Boghammar Marin boats frequently used by Iran's
Revolutionary Guards to attack commercial ships in the Gulf.
   U.S. warships in the past have fired warning shots to keep
unidentified small boats and Iraqi aircraft from approaching too
close to convoys escorted by the navy.
   The 17,000-ton Trenton had just arrived in the gulf hours
earlier carrying about 400 U.S. Marines and a contingent of Marine
attack helicopters.
   It was accompanied by the missile frigate John A. Moore and the
Gus W. Darnell, a 39,000-ton oiler chartered by the U.S. Military
Sealift Command. The Darnell makes periodic trips into the Gulf to
pick up fuel oil for U.S. warships.
   U.S. officials said that because the group included no Kuwaiti
tankers or other commercial vessels under the U.S. flag, it would
not be counted as a gulf ``transit.'' The Navy has conducted 35
escorted convoys since last July and the next one is expected to
leave Kuwait in the next few days.
   Meanwhile, the U.S. gulf operation will get a new commander this
week, a 50-year-old career aviator who once headed the Blue Angels,
the Navy's elite acrobatic jet team.
   Rear Adm. Anthony A. Less, will become commanding officer of the
Navy's Middle East Force in ceremonies Saturday aboard a new
flagship, USS Coronado. The Salem, Ohio, native replaces Rear Adm.
Harold J. Bernsen.
   As commander of the force since July 1986, Bernsen oversaw last
year's buildup that followed President Reagan's decision to
re-register 11 Kuwaiti oil tankers under the American flag to
protect them from attacks by Iran.
   Under Bernsen, the force nearly tripled in size, from about six
to 17 warships. It was recently cut back to 16.
   The United States has been escorting Kuwaiti vessels since last
summer. The only mishap occurred during the first convoy when the
supertanker Bridgeton struck a mine, believed laid by Iran, on July
24. Since then, the Navy has escorted 34 other convoys without a
hitch.
   Iranian ships frequently stop and search vessels they suspect of
carrying cargo for Iraq. Iran also attacks neutral ships in
retaliation for Iraqi air raids on Iran's oil shipping in the gulf.
The two nations have been at war for 7{ years.
   The last such raid claimed by Iraq was last Tuesday, and no ship
attacks by Iran have been reported since Feb. 11.
   Less takes over a command being drastically reshaped for the
second time in the past several months.
   On Feb. 3 he relieved Rear Adm. Dennis Brooks as commander of
the Joint Task Force Middle East, a shipboard headquarters created
last year to improve coordination between the gulf-based ships and
two supporting battle groups in the Arabian Sea.
   Well-informed Navy officers, speaking on condition of anonymity,
say the system failed because of operational conflicts between the
gulf and task force commanders.
   Although the Middle East Force is a surface unit, U.S. law
requires any ship with extensive air capability, such as the
16,912-ton Coronado and the 15,000-ton La Salle, which it replaces,
to be commanded by an aviator.
   Less flew A-7 Corsair attack bombers from the carrier Kitty Hawk
during the Vietnam War and in 1973 became the first commanding
officer of the Blue Angels when the flight demonstration team was
formally made a squadron. He served as its commander and flight
leader for three years.
   Less later commanded the oil tanker Wichita and the attack
carrier Ranger, operating in the western Pacific and the Indian
Ocean with the U.S. Seventh Fleet. Since last August, he had
commanded a carrier group and battle group.
   Bernsen, a Boston native, and specialist in aerial electronic
surveillance, served five tours aboard the carrier Forrestal in the
Mediterranean. He was commanding officer of the La Salle _ later
his own flagship _ during the 1979 U.S. hostage crisis in Iran and
the start of the Iraq-Iran war in 1980.
</TEXT>
