<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Explosions, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0514,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blasts Hit Morgue, Nursery School</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATE thruout with school being empty but family in morgue
and with trial beginning.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Explosions apparently caused by firebombs rocked a
nursery school and a morgue early today in Paris, causing extensive
damage but no injuries, firefighters reported.
   A previously unknown group called Committee of International
Revolutionary Solidarity claimed responsibility for the morgue
explosion, radio station RTL reported. The explosions came on the
day that a trial of seven alleged French terrorists began.
   Police said the explosion at the morgue, called Medical-Legal
Institute, occurred at about 5:30 a.m. A guardian and his family
who live at the institute were awakened by the blast but not hurt.
   About half an hour later and a mile to the northeast, a second
blast hit the ground floor of the Wake-up School, a private nursery
school in the lower middle-class Charonne district east of the
Bastille.
   No one was at the school.
   Fires at both locations were rapidly brought under control by
firefighters.
   There was no immediate report of a claim of responsibility for
the second explosion, and no indication why the nursery school or
the morgue might have been chosen as targets.
   Police refused to confirm that leaflets, claiming responsibility
for the blast, had been found at the morgue.
   The radio station quoted the leaflets as saying ``although we
are not sympathizers of Direct Action, we are against the state as
arms dealer and a society that profits from death.''
   Direct Action, the best-known extreme left terrorist group in
France, was effectively dismantled by a series of arrests last year.
   The fourth trial this month of Direct Action members opened this
afternoon, with seven people charged in the 1983 robberies of a
jewelry store and a bank.
   Jean-Marc Rouillan, one of four leaders of the group who have
been on a hunger strike for 84 days but kept alive with
transfusions, is among the seven defendants.
</TEXT>
