<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru   02-22 0859</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0529,0882</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinians Observe `Martyrs' Day'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 20 grafs to UPDATE with Justice Ministry
confirming protester punishment edict, details of second memorial
troops looking for agitators prior to Shultz visit, additional
injury in Ramallah; picks up 15th graf pvs: ``A Molotov...'' Pls
note keyword line was incorrectly given as Israel-Violence in 1st
Ld-Writethru, a0529.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians held memorial services today for
the 61 Arabs killed by Israelis troops, and Israel's attorney
general ruled soldiers could not use force to punish or humiliate
protesters.
   Two Palestinians were wounded in clashes with soldiers in the
West Bank city of Ramallah and the Gaza Strip refugee camp
Jabaliya, hospital officials said.
   In the Gaza Strip city Khan Yunis, an Israeli civilian fired in
the air after his car was stoned by protesters, an Arab reporter
said.
   The army said it was checking both reports. It also said an Arab
was arrested after trying to stab an Israeli soldier in Ramallah,
the third such attack in four days.
   Leaflets distributed in the occupied territories declared a
``Martyrs' Day'' today and called for demonstrations and a strike
this week to protest the visit to Israel by U.S. Secretary of State
George Shultz.
   Army officials said the five-day Shultz visit, scheduled to
begin Thursday, might prompt an escalation of violence.
   ``It's not organized or systematic, but outside events like the
Shultz visit do affect the situation,'' an army spokeswoman said on
condition of anonymity.
   Jerusalem Police spokesman Rafi Levy said 1,500 additional
officers brought in from other areas had been deployed in the holy
city to curb Arab violence.
   Israeli troops entered the Arab neighborhood of Silwan at the
foot of the Mount of Olives and cleared away makeshit barricades,
while national police went door-to-door checking identifications
and looking for agitators.
   Attorney General Yosef Harish sent a letter to Defense Minister
Yitzhak Rabin saying soldiers may not use force as a means of
punishment or humiliation, said Justice Ministry spokeswoman Etty
Eshed.
   Orders that call for such use of force are illegal, ruled
Harish, who demanded Rabin issue appropriate instructions to the
troops.
   Ms. Eshed said Harish decided to take action after many
Palestinians complained to him about abuse by soldiers.
   In an army survey, 65 percent of soldiers questioned said they
had witnessed rough treatment of Palestinians by troops, said the
army's chief psychologist, Col. Shlomo Dover, on Israel radio.
   ``We don't have problems with the motivation of soliders ... not
that they rejoice to do it, but it's an assignment that has been
given to the army and that's how it is seen by the soldiers,'' he
said.
   Since the wave of protests began Dec. 8 in the territories
Israel seized in the 1967 Middle East War, Israelis have killed 61
Palestinians. The latest fatalities were two men shot and killed by
soldiers Sunday.
   The government has spent $330 million, or 1 percent of the
government's 1988 budget, in an attempt to quell the violence.
   Palestinians held memorial services Monday to mark Arabs killed
by Israeli soldiers.
   About 1,500 Arabs marched through Kfar Naama in the West Bank to
mourn the loss of the second village to die in the violence that
began Dec. 8. Marchers listened to a series of defiant speeches
condemning Israel's occupation and renamed one of the roads, The
Street of the Martyrs of the Uprising.
   No soldiers appeared, and no violence was reported.
   In another memorial service today, women marched to a cemetery
in the West Bank village of Anabta to honor three residents who
died in clashes with the army earlier this month.
   A Molotov cocktail was thrown at an Israeli car in the West Bank
town of Ramallah, but no one was injured, the army said.
   In the Gaza Strip refugee camp of Jabaliya, soldiers clashed
with protesters, and a 14-year-old boy was shot in the thigh,
doctors at Gaza City's Shifa Hospital said.
   In Gaza City, anti-American slogans painted in red on closed
store shutters read: ``No to the Shultz visit. Yes to the
Palestinian government. Yes to the PLO.''
   The Palestine Liberation Organization has ordered Palestinians
in the West Bank and Gaza Strip not to meet with Shultz, saying he
is pro-Israeli and has rejected minimal Palestinian demands.
   But local Palestinian leaders said today that they were trying
to persuade PLO chief Yasser Arafat to lift the ban. U.S. officials
met with several Palestinian representatives over the weekend to
discuss the Shultz visit.
   During his visit, Shultz will present to Israeli leaders a U.S.
peace initiative calling for an international forum for direct
talks on Palestinian self-rule and negotiations on a final
settlement by December.
   But Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir told European Jewish leaders
Sunday night he objected to the hurried pace: ``Any attempt to
force the pace and shorten the period (of self-rule) would be a
detriment to the very essence of the agreement.''
   He also indicated he would not give in to pressure to accept the
American plan: ``When the time comes for decisions, we shall decide
on the basis of what is in our national interests.''
</TEXT>
