<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Scotus-Set-Aside     02-22 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Set-Aside,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court To Decide Affirmative Action Issue From Virginia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to study a key
affirmative action issue _ the power of local governments to
require minority participation in public works projects.
   The justices said they will hear an appeal by Richmond, Va.,
officials seeking to revive a so-called set-aside program for
construction industry businesses owned by minorities.
   The court previously expressed interest in examining the issue
when on Jan. 19 it asked the Justice Department to comment on a
construction company's challenge to a set-aside program in the
Miami area.
   But the justices stopped short of announcing whether they will
hear arguments in the Miami dispute.
   In the Richmond case, the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
ruled last September that the city's preferential treatment for
minority businesses approved in 1983 is an unconstitutional form of
reverse discrimination.
   The Richmond plan would require the prime contractor on any city
building contract to subcontract at least 30 percent of the value
of the project to firms that are at least one-half minority owned.
   The minorities covered by the plan were blacks, Hispanics,
Orientals, Indians, Eskimos and Aleuts.
   The appeals court, in its 2-1 decision, relied heavily on a 1986
Supreme Court ruling that struck down an affirmative action plan in
Michigan designed to protect from lay-offs minority teachers with
less seniority than whites.
   The Supreme Court in that case said preferential treatment of
minorities must be narrowly tailored to avoid hurting whites. The
court restricted the power of employers to adopt affirmative action
programs when there has not been proof those employers practiced
past discrimination.
   Supporters of local set-aside programs, on the other hand, point
to a 1980 Supreme Court ruling that Congress may require 10 percent
of federal public works contracts be earmarked for
minority-controlled businesses.
   An eventual Supreme Court ruling on local set-aside programs
would have far-reaching impact.
   Most states and some 160 local governments have such programs,
according to a study by the Minority Business Enterprise Legal
Defense Education Fund.
   The 4th Circuit court, in striking down the Richmond plan, said
the city's program was adopted on scant evidence of past
discrimination.
   The appeals court noted that minorities comprise about half of
Richmond's population and that minority-owned businesses had
received less than 1 percent of the value of the city's public
building contracts.
   But the appeals court said there are few minority-owned
businesses in the city area, and there was no evidence they had
been victims of past discrimination.
   ``General population statistics suggest, if anything, more of a
political than a remedial basis for the racial preference'' quota
in the set-aside program, the 4th Circuit court said. ``There has
been no showing that qualified minority contractors who submitted
low bids were passed over.''
   The appeals court also said the 30 percent quota ``was chosen
arbitrarily. The figure simply emerged from the mists.''
   ``The Richmond ordinance reflects the most casual deployment of
race in the dispensation of public benefits. It prefers some, and
in so doing diminishes the rights of all,'' the appeals court said.
   A coalition of groups representing local and state governments
urged the Supreme Court to reinstate the Richmond plan.
   The coalition said it would reopen old wounds and discourage
affirmative action if governments must first show past
discrimination before adopting remedial programs.
   The coalition groups are the National League of Cities, the U.S.
Conference of Mayors, the National Association of Counties and the
International City Management Association.
   Richmond's plan was challenged by the J.A. Croson Co. after its
bid _ the only one submitted _ to install stainless steel urinals
and water closets at the city jail was rejected.
   City officials refused to award the contract after Croson said
there was only one unqualified minority contractor that could help
on the project. The company said the cost of the project would rise
by $7,663 if the minority contractor were used. The city then
called for new bids.
   The case is Richmond vs. Croson, 87-998.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
