<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 1036EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Helicopter     02-22 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Helicopter,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to Decide Search Warrant Issue in Florida Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide when
police need court warrants before searching from helicopters for
marijuana growing in fenced-in yards.
   The justices said they will study a Florida Supreme Court ruling
that a helicopter search by sheriff's deputies in Pasco County four
years ago violated the right of privacy.
   The nation's highest court in 1986 ruled that a warrantless
search by Santa Clara, Calif., police in an airplane had not
violated privacy rights.
   In that case, police spotted marijana plants growing in a
fenced-in yard while flying at a lawful altitude of 1,000 feet.
   Voting 5-4 then, the justices said the Constitution's Fourth
Amendment, which bans unreasonable government searches, ``simply
does not require the police traveling in public airways at this
altitude (1,000 feet) to obtain a warrant in order to observe what
is visible to the naked eye.''
   In the Florida case, Pasco County deputies received an anonymous
tip that Michael A. Riley was growing marijuana in his yard.
   Unable to tell what plants were growing in a greenhouse in the
yard, the deputies flew over the yard in a helicopter, at an
altitude of about 400 feet. From there, they could look into
missing panels in the greenhouse roof.
   Based on what they saw, the deputies obtained a search warrant
and entered Riley's yard, seizing 44 marijuana plants.
   Riley challenged the helicopter search, seeking to block
prosecutors from using the marijuana plants as evidence against him.
   The Florida Supreme Court last July 9 ruled for Riley, stating
that the helicopter search violated Riley's reasonable expectation
of privacy under the Fourth Amendment.
   The state court said the 1986 decision did not authorize ``an
unlimited right to any type of examination of residential property
from the air.''
   The state court added, ``Surveillance by helicopter is
particularly likely to unreasonably intrude upon private activities
... because of a helicopter's virtually unlimited maneuverability
and observational capabilities.''
   It noted that fixed-wing airplanes are not authorized to fly
lower than 500 feet in the area where the search occurred.
   Florida prosecutors filed the appeal acted on today.
   The case is Florida vs. Riley, 87-764.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880222-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 1042EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Offshore     02-22 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Offshore,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Will Decide Iowa Case on Taxing Oil and Natural Gas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether states may tax any income from oil and natural gas
extracted from the Outer Continental Shelf.
   The court said it will hear an appeal by Shell Oil Co.
challenging an Iowa tax.
   The state tax is designed to be imposed on that portion of a
company's income derived from doing business in Iowa.
   Shell Oil said it was improper for state officials to include
any revenue from offshore gas and oil in determining the company's
taxable income.
   Shell said the state tax violates a 1953 federal law authorizing
exploration and production of Outer Continental Shelf oil and gas.
   The shelf is underwater land more than three miles off the shore
of any state. The land is owned by the federal government and
leased to private companies.
   The Iowa Supreme Court upheld the state tax last October. It
said the levy ``is in no way dependent upon the exercise of
legislative jursidiction on Outer Continental Shelf lands'' that
the 1953 federal law was intended to prohibit.
   Including revenue from OCS oil and gas ``apparently aids in
obtaining an accurate measure of the tax to be imposed as a result
of Shell's Iowa activities,'' the state court said.
   The Reagan administration agreed with the ruling of the Iowa
court but urged the U.S. Supreme Court to use Shell's appeal to
settle the dispute.
   Justice Department lawyers noted that the Iowa case would be a
good one for the high court to use in examining state tax authority
because the Iowa tax takes into account sales both on and off the
Outer Continental Shelf.
   The case is Shell Oil vs. Iowa, 87-984.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
