<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Abortion     02-22 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Abortion,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Won't Reconsider Decision in Illinois Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to reconsider
its 4-4 decision last December striking down an Illinois law that
could have made abortions more difficult to obtain for some
teen-agers.
   The justices, without comment, rejected a request by Illinois
Attorney General Neil F. Hartigan that they restudy the law ``after
the appointment of a ninth justice.''
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy joined the court last Thursday,
filling an eight-month vacancy. He did not participate in today's
order denying reconsideration.
   Despite his 12-year tenure as a federal appeals court judge,
Kennedy's legal views on abortion are unknown.
   The high court's decision in December was not accompanied by a
written opinion, but merely upheld a ruling that the challenged
Illinois law impermissibly interfered with abortion rights.
   Such even splits among the justices automatically uphold lower
court decisions in the particular cases but set no national
precedent.
   In seeking reconsideration, Hartigan emphasized the importance
of ``a decision by a full court'' in the case.
   The Illinois law required that girls under 18 and still
financially dependent on their parents notify both parents 24 hours
before having an abortion.
   The law allowed a girl to avoid notifying her parents if she
could prove to a state judge that she was mature enough and
well-informed enough to make the decision on her own and that
notifying her parents would not be in her best interest.
   Doctors who failed to comply with the law's requirement faced
criminal prosecution.
   A federal appeals court ruled that the 24-hour waiting period is
an impermissible infringement on the right to have an abortion,
established by a landmark 1973 Supreme Court decision.
   The appeals court also said the Illinois law provision for
parental notification or judicial permission could not be enforced
because it did not ensure confidentiality and anonymity for girls
who appeal when a judge denies permission for an abortion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
