<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador-Strike     02-22 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador-Strike,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transport Strike Called By Guerillas Halts Bus Traffic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 24-hour transport strike
called by leftist guerrillas virtually halted bus and truck traffic
today and drastically curtailed use of automobiles.
   The strike was called by members of the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front to protest legislative and municipal elections
scheduled for March 20. The rebels say the elections are a farce.
   No buses circulated in this capital of 1 million people.
Thousands of people walked to work, although some pickup trucks
jammed with passengers were on the roads.
   The army said it doubled motorized patrols to provide security
for people who defied the strike.
   The private radio station YSU said truck and bus traffic
nationwide was about 5 percent of normal. From the western
provincial capital of Santa Ana, the radio reported that the
stoppage of buses was total.
   It said two buses of 50 that normally would have been dispatched
left the eastern provincial capital of San Miguel for other cities.
   The leftist guerrillas have been fighting the U.S.-backed
government since 1979 with a campaign that includes economic
sabotage.
   There were seven guerrilla-imposed transport strikes last year.
Three strike violators were killed, about 30 were wounded and some
160 vehicles were destroyed or damaged.
</TEXT>
