<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Floods     02-22 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Floods,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flash Floods Kill 12 In South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flash floods roared through
central South Africa today, killing at least 12 people and leaving
hundreds of others without homes.
   Up to 12 inches of rain soaked parts of Orange Free State
province during the weekend, washing out roads, bursting dams and
flooding huge stretches of farmland, authorities said.
   Military helicopters plucked 200 people from houses, trees, cars
and areas inaccessible by road, the air force reported.
   Telephone lines were down in many areas, and the city of
Bloemfontein, the capital of the Orange Free State, only could be
reached by air, officials said.
   Rivers in the region have overflowed their banks and many small
towns have been evacuated, officials added. Heavy rains were
predicted to continue through Tuesday, forecasters said.
   Officials said the storm killed 12 people and forced several
hundred others to flee their homes.
   Lulu de Jager, spokesman for the Orange Free State Agricultural
Union, said farm damage from the flooding would run into millions
of dollars.
   ``We will start a survey when the weather clears up, but we may
take if for granted that crop and livestock losses have been
astronomical,'' de Jager said.
   Heavy flooding last September in the southeastern part of the
country left more than 300 people dead and 500,000 homeless.
</TEXT>
