<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AmtrakFire 1stLd-Writethru a0572 02-22 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amtrak Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0572,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amtrak Defends Crew's Actions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of name from Sary to Sara in 8th graf,
`Passenger Sary ....'
^By JOE RUFF</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Amtrak official defended the actions of
crew members aboard a train that caught fire over the weekend,
saying that despite passenger complaints, several lives may have
been saved.
   Passengers aboard Amtrak's California Zephyr said they received
no warnings or instructions from crew members after the fire broke
out early Saturday, killing a chef and injuring 19 other people.
   ``I think our on-board crew's initial instinct was to make sure
passengers weren't in any danger from the fire. Then they had to
get employees out of the car,'' said Amtrak spokesman John Jacobsen
in a telephone interview from Washington.
   ``We could have easily had four or five employees killed in that
dormitory car yesterday,'' Jacobsen said.
   However, the actions of a conductor and his assistant may have
saved several lives, Jacobsen said.
   Conductor J.P. Jones, of Arvada, Colo., and assistant conductor
Todd M. Witaker of Denver separated the crew car from the train's
baggage car and engine to reach people endangered by the smoke,
Jacobsen said.
   The fire aboard the 14-car westbound train carrying 294
passengers and a crew of 18 was reported about 3 a.m. as the train
was pulling into Hastings for a scheduled stop. Hastings Fire Chief
Jim Mitera said the blaze was under control about 90 minutes later.
   Passenger Sara Bentley of Fremont said later it was a miracle no
one panicked.
   ``I think the worse thing was that they didn't let anyone in our
car know whether we were in danger,'' Ms. Bentley said. ``We
couldn't find out if our car was safe.''
   Jacobsen said an Amtrak investigation was continuing, and that
no disciplinary action had been taken against any crew members. The
National Transportation Safety Board also was investigating.
   Jacobsen said the fire may have been caused by luggage or some
other flammable material placed near a heater in a crew car,
contrary to earlier findings by the Nebraska State Fire Marshal's
office that pointed to an electrical short in the heater.
   Amtrak investigators didn't find evidence of a short, Jacobsen
said. State Fire Marshal Wally Barnett said he would stand by the
state report.
   ``We're fire investigators, and we think we're right,'' Barnett
said Sunday.
   The victim, identified as chef Cesar Arguelles, 70, of Chicago,
was one of seven crew members on the car, Jacobsen said. County
Attorney Gary Anderberg said an autopsy showed the chef died of
smoke inhalation.
   Nine crew members and three passengers were treated for smoke
inhalation at Mary Lanning Hospital. All but two had been released
by this morning, nursing supervisor Mona Mueller said. Those two
were in satisfactory condition and were expected to be released
today.
   Jacobsen said the fire probably would prompt Amtrak officials to
renew their search for an effective smoke alarm for their trains.
But no models work now because they are often set off by the
constant vibrations of trains, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
