<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 1120EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Bookstore     02-22 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Bookstore,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Moves Michigan Adult Bookstore Dispute to Federal
Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand a ruling
that forces Ann Arbor, Mich., city officials to justify in federal
court a zoning ordinance limiting where adult bookstores may be
opened for business.
   The court, without comment, refused to hear arguments aimed at
squelching a lawsuit challenging the ordinance.
   The ordinance limits the area where adult bookstores may locate
to a portion of downtown Ann Arbor representing less than 1 percent
of the land within the city's 25.3 square miles.
   Adult bookstores are defined by the ordinance as those where
sexually explicit materials comprise more than 20 percent of the
stock in trade. So any business establishment, anywhere in the
city, may have up to 20 percent of its trade in adult materials.
   Karen Christy, who sought to operate an adult bookstore in an
area not zoned for adult entertainment, sued the city. She sought
to block enforcement of the zoning ordinance.
   U.S. District Judge Charles Joiner refused to block enforcement,
ruling that the ordinance is not impermissibly restrictive.
   ``The 20 percent requirement provides a beneficial way for
decentralization of the adult book business,'' he said. ``By
sanctioning the selling of adult books and other books together,
the city has eliminated most of the well-known problems of urban
blight that result from concentrations of these bookstores without
sacrificing its citizens' First Amendment freedoms,'' Joiner said.
   But the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last July 23
that Joiner was wrong.
   ``A city cannot arbitrarily limit the exercise of First
Amendment rights,'' the appeals court said. ``A limitation of adult
materials to 20 percent of a bookseller's wares conditions the
constitutional right to speak in one way on the bookseller's
willingness to speak in a different way 80 percent of the time.''
   The appeals court sent the case back to Joiner for further study
after saying it found no evidence ``of a legitimate government
objective for the passage of this zoning ordinance.''
   In the appeal acted on today, city officials argued, among other
things, that the Constitution's First Amendment does not guarantee
the existence of adult bookstores if ``the right of access to such
materials may be accommodated in other ways.''
   The case is Ann Arbor vs. Christy, 87-649.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
