<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Angola 1stLd-Writethru a0516 02-22 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Angola, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0516,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Says Pilot Missing Following Angolan Air Raid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd graf, `The plane ...,' to UPDATE
with report that two planes shot down. PICKS up 3rd graf pvs,
`South Africa ...' INSERTS 3 grafs after 6th graf, `During the .
..,' with details of report. PICKS up 7th graf, `South Africa .. .'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military today said a
South African pilot was missing after his plane was shot down in
southeast Angola during a weekend air raid.
   The plane was struck by ground fire while attacking Cuban and
Angolan government troops during a battle Saturday, the military
said. It was the second time during South Africa's five-month
intervention in Angola that it acknowledged losing one of its
warplanes inside the country.
   The Angolan news agency ANGOP reported today that Angolan
government troops shot down two South African jetfighters over the
weekend and have scored significant gains in recent battles against
South African units and the Angolan rebel movement UNITA.
   South Africa launched two other air attacks Saturday in southern
Angola against bases of the South-West African People's
Organization, known as SWAPO, in retaliation for the bombing Friday
of a bank in South-West Africa. The death toll in the bombing
reached 20, South-West African police said today.
   South Africa also announced that it followed up the air attacks
with long-range mortar bombardments Saturday and Sunday on SWAPO
positions. The military said the mortar attacks were
``successful,'' but did not disclose any details.
   South Africa occupies South-West Africa, also known as Namibia,
in violation of a United Nations resolution. Its forces regularly
enter Angola to raid SWAPO bases.
   During the Saturday afternoon attack, a plane piloted by Maj.
Edward Every was downed by ground fire, the military said, adding
that the air raid was staged because the Angolan-Cuban forces
``posed a potential threat'' to South African troops.
   The ANGOP report, monitored in Lisbon, Portugal, identified one
of the downed South African pilots as Maj. Every, and said Angolan
officials had recovered his personal effects.
   The report did not specify whether Every was in Angolan custody,
and did not identify the pilot of the other plane, both of which
were French-made Mirage fighter bombers.
   In a separate dispatch, ANGOP reported that South African
bombing raids caused ``countless deaths'' over the weekend.
   South Africa announced in November that its troops were fighting
in Angola to support the National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola, or UNITA, rebel movement. However, it is widely believed
that South African troops began fighting in Angola one month
earlier, in October.
   UNITA has been fighting a 12-year bush war for a power-sharing
agreement with Angola's Marxist government, which is backed by
Cuban and Soviet forces.
   President Eduardo dos Santos of Angola said Sunday that 9,000
South African soldiers are deployed in southern Angola. He also
said South Africa has staged 16 air raids so far this year, and
that six South African planes have been shot down and 140 of that
nation's soldiers have been killed.
   South Africa has repeatedly refused in recent months to disclose
the extent of its military involvement in Angola. However, it has
announced the deaths of more than 30 soldiers since November.
   The military said in November that one of its warplanes had
crashed in Angola while participating in an attack on SWAPO forces
and that another plane had been hit but managed to return to a base
in Namibia before crash-landing.
</TEXT>
