<HEAD>Numerous Calls On Colorado Springs Kidnapped Baby</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to update with calls to police, quote
from mother.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police are getting numerous calls
from people who say they have seen a 4-week-old girl kidnapped from
her mother's home, but so far officers have turned up no suspects.
   Rachael Ann White was taken Friday when her grandmother left the
room while interviewing a woman for a babysitting job.
   The phone has been ringing steadily at the Colorado Springs
Police Department with reports from area residents who say they
have been the infant with the woman who kidnapped her, but so far
police have been unable to trace the infant or her abducter,
officer Mike Stewart said today.
   Cora Abbott, mother of the missing baby, said authorities won't
tell her specifically ``what they're working on for fear I'll get
my hopes up and then it'll turn out to be nothing.''
   ``The most important thing we have is the composite (drawing) of
the female suspect. That person has to stop somewhere for gas,
groceries. There's got to be someone out there who has information
on that person,'' police Lt. Joe Vernier said Sunday.
   No ransom has been sought, police said late Sunday.
   Abbott, 27, was working when the abduction occurred. Her mother,
Evelyn Reed of Canon City, told police she was interviewing a woman
for a babysitting job at her daughter's home when the telephone
rang.
   Reed said she handed the baby to the woman and went into another
room to answer the phone. When she returned the woman was gone.
   The woman was described as Hispanic with reddish-tinted black
hair, 5-feet-6 tall, 150 pounds, and 40 to 45 years old.
