<HEAD>With PM-Lebanon-Kidnap</HEAD>
<HEAD>Higgins Under Duress in Tape: White House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A videotape by Lt. Col. William R. Higgins on
behalf of demands by his captors was ``obviously ... made under
duress,'' the White House said today.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the tape had been
viewed by members of the National Security Council and White House
staff but he did not believe President Reagan had seen it.
   ``Obviously it was made under duress,'' Fitzwater said. ``We
continue to call for the immediate and safe release of Colonel
Higgins as well as other hostages in Lebanon. We are not going to
give in to the demands of terrorists. We will continue to pursue
all avenues for his release.''
   When asked if Reagan had any reaction, the spokesman said, ``You
know the president's deep convictions about Colonel Higgins and all
the hostages, but we want to avoid saying anything that could
exacerbate the situation.''
