<2ND_LINE>PM-Fires-Wind, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0574,0768</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fierce Winds Fan Blazes In Rockies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs the 3rd graf and the 16th, beginning ``Colorado
Highway,'' to update with highways reopened.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN STEINBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A forest fire sparked by a hiker's campfire and fanned by 90 mph
gusts slowed today after threatening up to 100 houses near Boulder,
Colo., and a wind-whipped 2,400-acre blaze in Montana destroyed at
least four houses.
   No injuries were reported.
   Roads in Colorado's Sunshine Canyon area were closed late Sunday
and occupants of one apartment building near the blaze voluntarily
left the building, as did residents of five homes. But no
evacuations were ordered and the roads were reopened today.
   The fire grew to more than 200 acres of grass and light timber
by early today, the Boulder County Sheriff's Department said.
   The area was under a high wind warning with 90 mph gusts
reported. Wind had been expected to reach 100 mph today, but at 3
a.m. it subsided to gusts of no more than 30 mph and there was an
early morning calm of 6 mph, the National Weather Service said.
   ``The fire has laid down considerably since last night,'' said
firefighter John Gregg. ``It's not contained in the sense that
there is no fire line around the fire completely, but it's not
spreading out of control as it was last night when the winds were
high.''
   Strong wind blew through much of the Rockies on Sunday.
Afternoon and evening wind gusted to 65 mph in Cody, Wyo., and near
Calgary, Alberta, chinook wind forced postponement of the final
heats of the men's two-man bobsled competition at the Winter
Olympics.
   The Colorado fire started on Boulder's Mountain Park land in
Sunshine Canyon and threatened 80 to 100 homes, said sheriff's
spokesman Brian Leach.
   ``I don't know of one that has threatened as many structures as
this one,'' he said.
   Warm, dry and windy conditions existed just before the fire was
reported about 5 p.m. Sunday. No buildings had burned by early
today, as the fire burned about one-half mile southwest of Boulder
Memorial Hospital.
   About 100 firefighters battled the blaze.
   Residents of suburban Sunshine Canyon were asked to be ready to
leave their homes in case the fire crossed a ridge into their area,
the sheriff's department said.
   One family evacuated that subdivision Sunday night, and four
families in Boulder did so by today, according to reports from the
scene.
   As flames topped a ridge above one neighborhood, homeowners
hooked up garden hoses to spray their roofs and started packing.
   ``I'm scared to death,'' said ne resident Patricia Grant.
   Colorado Highway 119 through the fire area was closed overnight
between Boulder and Nederland, as were two other roads, but they
were reopened today.
   Sheriff's Sgt. Ernst L. Little said a 30-year-old hiker told
police he had started a campfire that apparently caused the blaze.
   In southwestern Montana, a grass fire whipped by gusts up to 50
and 70 mph raced across 2,400 acres south of Whitehall and
destroyed four houses before being brought under control early
today, said Dan Fisher, assistant chief of the Whitehall Volunteer
Fire Department.
   Firefighters from at least 10 volunteer fire departments in the
rural area northwest of Yellowstone National Park battled the
blaze, assisted by volunteers from the Forest Service, the
Department of State Lands and two mining companies.
   About two dozen families endangered by the fire were evacuated,
but might be able to return to their homes later today, Fisher
said. Emergency kitchens were set up in two Whitehall churches to
feed homeless and firefighters, and emergency sleeping space was
provided at the high school gymnasium and in private homes.
   The houses that burned were scattered rural residences.
   The wind ``is as bad as I've ever seen it,'' said Glen Hanson, a
trapper who lives on the south edge of town. ``The ... stuff was
going faster than you could run.''
   Whitehall Fire Chief Dale Davis said the blaze started Sunday
when a cottonwood tree was blown over and severed a Montana Power
Co. line two miles south of Whitehall.
   Flames estimated at 20 to 30 feet high licked the tops of trees
along the Jefferson River, and Jefferson County Fire Warden Doug
Schmitz said the fire jumped the river.
   The fire charred an area three miles wide and two miles long,
and firefighters said some ranchers cut barbed wire fences to set
their cattle, horses and sheep free ahead of the racing flames.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
