<HEAD>Hotel Fire Kills Six In Bulgaria</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with six reported dead. Edits to conform.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire raced through a ski resort hotel in
Bulgaria before dawn today, killing six people and injuring 36
others, Bulgaria's official news agency reported.
   The news agency BTA said the fire in Borovets, a ski resort 22
miles southeast of Sofia, began at 3 a.m.
   ``Measures were taken to put out the blaze but the building was
quickly engulfed in flames,'' said the BTA report received in
Vienna. ``In the panic that followed, six people died.''
   The agency said two of the dead were Dutch, one was Bulgarian
and three had not been identified.
   Of the 36 injured, BTA said 17 were British, four Soviet, five
West German, seven Greek, two Danish and one Dutch, according to
BTA. Their names were not released.
   ``The causes of the fire are still not known,'' the news agency
said, adding a commission was appointed to investigate ``the tragic
accident.''
   BTA identified the dead Dutch visitors as ``Ms. Ever
Vanderberg'' and ``Mr. Peter Zekelenburg.'' Their home towns were
not made public. The name of the dead Bulgarian was not reported.
   An unidentified man who answered the telephone at the Bulgarian
state tourist office in Borovets said the 170-bed hotel was
destroyed in the blaze. He refused to give further details about
the fire.
   Initial reports from Western diplomats in Sofia said Britons,
West Germans and Dutch tourists were injured when they jumped out
hotel windows to escape the blaze at the Moussala hotel. The
diplomats, contacted by telephone from Vienna, spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   Several Western embassies said they had sent diplomats to
Borovets to try and learn more about the fire.
   Bulgaria has recently made great efforts to encourage Western
tourists to visit its mountain resorts on comparatively cheap ski
vacations.
   Carol Thatcher, daughter of British prime minister Margaret
Thatcher, was a recent visitor to Borovets, a picturesque village
in the Rila Mountains. It is close to Mount Moussala, the highest
peak in Bulgaria at 9,652 feet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
