<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 1221EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NRC     02-22 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NRC,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Overhaul of Nuclear Regulatory Commission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation to replace the five-member Nuclear
Regulatory Commission with a Nuclear Safety Agency headed by a
single administrator was approved Monday by a Senate subcommittee.
   Sponsors of the package said the change is needed to end
internal battling at the NRC, help restore public confidence in
nuclear power and provide better inspection and regulation of
commercial generators.
   The bill, worked out by Sens. John Breaux, D-La., and Alan
Simpson, R-Wy., also would create a Nuclear Reactor Safety
Investigations Board to conduct independent reviews of major
accidents and safety problems at nuclear facilities.
   The package also sets up an inspector general to monitor
internal operations of the nuclear licensing agency and create an
Office of Investigations to look for wrongdoing by nuclear
licensees.
   Breaux said ``it is only through a program of more effective
regulation that the confidence of the American people in the
benefits of this technology will be restored. ...
   ``The record amply demonstrates that the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission is a collegial body that rarely makes its most important
decisions collegially,'' Breaux said.
   Discussing the commissioners, Simpson said ``they don't
communicate with each other.'' He said the NRC suffers from a
``pernicious diffusion of accountability and responsibility'' that
produces ``indecisive, ineffective, inefficient regulation of the
commercial nuclear industry.''
   Frank Ingram, a spokesman for the NRC, said the agency had no
immediate comment on the details of the legislation but added that
``a majority of the commission supports a single administrator
concept.''
   The bill was approved by voice vote of the Environment and
Public Works subcommittee on nuclear regulation.
</TEXT>
