<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain-Communists     02-22 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Communists,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communists Elect New Secretary-General</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Spanish Communist Party elected Julio
Anguita as its new secretary-general Monday, ending at least
temporarily the leadership crisis that has threatened the survival
of the once influential party.
   Anguita, leader of the Communists of the southern Andalusia
region and former mayor of Cordoba, was elected by the 100-member
Central Committee at the end of the party's three-day 12th congress.
   In accepting the post, the 46-year-old son of an army officer
called on the workers and intellectuals who have left the party to
return.
   The congress took place amidst struggles with problems of
direction and membership, which has fallen to 62,300 from a high of
more than 150,000 during the 1979 general elections.
   Under outgoing Secretary-General Gerardo Iglesias, the party
tried to broaden its appeal to include ecological and pacifist
groups and to reach out to the middle class.
   The United Left coalition, which includes the Communists, now
holds seven of the 350 seats in the Spanish lower house of
Parliament, down from a peak of 20 seats held by the Communists
alone after the 1979 elections.
</TEXT>
