<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Angola     02-22 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Angola,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South African Warplane Downed In Angola, Heavy Combat Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military said Monday a
South African pilot was missing after his plane was shot down in
southeast Angola during a raid on Angolan and Cuban forces.
   Angola's Marxist government reported ``violent combat'' in the
area and said two of South Africa's French-built Mirage fighters
were downed during low-altitude bombing runs Saturday near the
garrison town of Cuito Cuanavale.
   The announcement by South Africa marked the second time during
its five-month intervention in Angola that it acknowledged losing
one of its warplanes inside the country. It has been fighting in
support of the UNITA rebel movement.
   Military headquarters said a plane piloted by Maj. Edward Every,
31, was downed by ground fire during a raid staged because
Angolan-Cuban forces ``posed a potential threat'' to South African
troops.
   Angola also identified Every by name but did not say whether he
was dead or captured. It gave no details about the pilot of the
other plane it claimed to have downed.
   South Africa said it launched two other air attacks earlier
Saturday in southwest Angola against guerrilla bases of the
South-West African People's Organization, known as SWAPO, in
retaliation for the bombing Friday of a bank in South-West Africa.
The death toll in the bombing rose by two to 20 Monday, South-West
African police said.
   South Africa said it followed up the retaliatory air raids with
mortar bombardments Saturday and Sunday on SWAPO positions. A
military statement said the mortar attacks were ``successful,'' but
gave no details.
   SWAPO has denied responsibility for the bank bombing. It said
Monday that South Africa's retaliatory raids ``hit innocent
civilians'' but not SWAPO bases.
   South Africa occupies South-West Africa, also known as Namibia,
in violation of a United Nations resolution. Its forces regularly
enter Angola to raid bases of SWAPO, which has been fighting since
1966 for Namibia's independence.
   South Africa announced Nov. 11 that its troops had intervened in
Angola's civil war. It is widely believed that South African troops
entered Angola weeks earlier.
   UNITA _ the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
_ has been fighting a 12-year bush war for a power-sharing
agreement with Angola's government, which is backed by Soviet
advisers and 40,000 Cuban troops.
   Angola's president, Eduardo dos Santos, said Sunday that 9,000
South African soldiers are deployed in Angola. He said six South
African planes have been shot down and 140 South African soldiers
killed this year.
   South Africa has refused to disclose the extent of its
involvement in Angola. It has reported the deaths of more than 30
soldiers since November, and says all its combat fatalities are
announced.
   The military said in November that one of its warplanes crashed
in Angola while engaged in an attack on SWAPO forces. It said
another plane was hit but returned to a base in Namibia before
crash-landing.
   Angola's news agency, ANGOP, quoted defense officials Monday as
saying South African forces renewed their attack on Cuito Cuanavale
on Saturday, two days after Angola announced its forces had
repelled a drive to take the strategic town. Now reportedly
deserted, Cuito Cuanavale had been the forwardmost staging point
for government attacks on UNITA strongholds in Angola's southeast
corner.
   Anolga's Defense Ministry said ``countless deaths'' had resulted
from South African air raids on the southwestern towns of N'Giva
and Lubango. Those were the raids which South Africa said were
aimed at SWAPO bases.
   ANGOP reported heavy fighting in central Angola along the
east-west Benguela railway, and said 200 UNITA guerrillas were
killed.
</TEXT>
