<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Conn-Senate     02-22 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Conn-Senate,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conn. Attorney General Says He'll Challenge Weicker for Senate
Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Joseph I. Lieberman
today officially announced his challenge of maverick Republican
Sen. Lowell P. Weicker Jr. in this year's Senate race.
   Weicker, 56, who announced his candidacy for a fourth term
earlier this month, has made a name for himself as a liberal
Republican, frequently at odds with his party and president. He has
championed constitutional issues and civil rights and worked
against school prayer and balanced budget amendments.
   He squeaked into office for a third term in 1982, but says he
expects this to be the biggest win of his career. Early polls give
him the lead but show Lieberman in a good position for a challenger.
   Lieberman, 45, a Democratic former state senator who ran
unsuccessfully for Congress in 1980, said he'll focus on a single
theme between now and November: What has Weicker done for
Connecticut?
   The populist attorney general attacked Weicker for using the
Senate as ``a debating society'' for his own agenda, issues that
don't do much for the average person.
   As attorney general, Lieberman has seized on non-partisan
consumer and environmental issues, such as grocery store coupon
rip-offs, increased electric rates and dumping sewage into the
Connecticut River.
   The candidates will be determined at state party conventions
this summer. So far, Weicker is unopposed and Lieberman has only
token opposition from Gary Johnson, who describes himself as a
veterans' rights advocate.
</TEXT>
