<1ST_LINE>r i AM_BRF_Australia-Koalas     02-22 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM_BRF_Australia-Koalas,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koalas Face Extinction, Expert Warns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The koala, Australia's national
symbol, could become extinct unless long-term plans are devised to
protect its habitat, an expert on the cuddly marsupials warned
Monday.
   ``I am positive that if we don't take immediate action the
koala, our famous `animal ambassador,' will slowly but surely slide
down the inevitable path toward extinction,'' said Don Burnett,
president of the Koala Preservation Society.
   He told a three-day koala symposium at Melbourne University
extinction was only a matter of time as urban development erodes
the creature's natural habitat.
   Koalas are found only on the eastern coast of Australia. They
survive on a species of gum leaf and in recent years a venereal
infection has devastated koala colonies.
   It is generally acknowleged that koalas were more prevalent
prior to European settlement of Australia in 1788, but no figures
are available on their number today.
</TEXT>
