<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Mecham     02-22 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham's Criminal Trial Postponed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today ordered that the start of
Gov. Evan Mecham's trial on criminal charges of concealing a
$350,000 campaign loan be delayed until March 22.
   Judge Michael Ryan of Maricopa County Superior Court ordered the
delay from the original March 9 trial date to allow both sides time
for handling pretrial motions and answers.
   Mecham is charged with six counts of fraud, perjury and filing
false documents in connection with the $350,000 campaign loan made
in October 1986 by Tempe developer and attorney Barry Wolfson.
Willard Mecham, his brother's 1986 campaign treasurer, faces three
similar counts.
   Mecham also faces a Feb. 29 impeachment trial by the State
Senate and a May 17 recall election.
   Assistant Attorney General Michael Cudahy said he needed more
time to reply to defense motions in the criminal case. Cudahy also
complained that attorneys for the Mechams had not yet made required
pretrial disclosures, including lists of witnesses and exhibits.
   The governor's lawyers were given until March 7 to file a motion
seeking return of the charges to the grand jury for a new finding
that enough evidence existed to support the charges.
   Ryan today also scheduled a March 2 hearing on several motions
that were filed last week by Willard Mecham's lawyer, Michael
Scott, and joined today by defense attorney Murray Miller on behalf
of the governor.
   Those motions would remand the charges, dismiss some of the
counts and require grand jurors and the prosecutor to submit to
questioning.
</TEXT>
