<DOCNO> AP880222-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 1346EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Robertson'sProspects     02-22 0849</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robertson's Prospects,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson, Super Tuesday's Unknown Factor, Seen Winning Some
States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders in both political parties, trying to assay the
hard-to-measure strength of Pat Robertson, say they expect he'll
win some Southern Republican presidential primaries on Super
Tuesday, come in second in others and pick up a substantial share
of the 700 delegates up for grabs that day.
   Interviews by Associated Press reporters in the 16 states
holding Republican primaries or caucuses on March 8 underscore that
the former television evangelist is a wild card, his strength
unfathomable but clearly formidable.
   ``We've got seven phone lines and they're jammed with calls
these days,'' says North Carolina GOP chairman Jack Hawke. ``People
are asking questions you just don't hear a lot _ how is a precinct
organized, how is a person registered. It leads me to believe they
(Robertson supporters) are active across the state.''
   Says Hawke's Democratic counterpart, Jim Van Hecke: ``I think
he's scared the established Republican Party to death.''
   Because many evangelical Christians, the core of Robertson's
support, have not participated in the nominating process in the
past, his strength in competition with George Bush, Bob Dole and
Jack Kemp is hard to gauge.
   A new question mark is whether the weekend confession of moral
waywardness of another television evangelist, Jimmy Swaggart, could
have any fallout on Robertson, who made his fame preaching before
the TV cameras.
   ``I think Bush's biggest competition in the South will come from
Robertson,'' says political scientist Merle Black at the University
of North Carolina. ``It's not inconceivable that he could beat Bush
in some of these states.''
   Political observers report that Robertson appears weak in the
three non-Southern Republican primaries _ Massachusetts, Rhode
Island and Missouri. But Jennifer Dunn, Republican chairman in
Washington state, which holds caucuses March 8, says Bush, Dole and
Robertson are so closely clumped that a prediction is impossible.
   ``I wouldn't be a bit surprised to see a 30 percent Robertson
turnout in the delegate selection, with the other candidates
splitting the rest,'' Mrs. Dunn says. Says Robertson state chairman
Bruce Hawkins: ``We're not just going to take it, we're going to
sweep it.''
   South Carolina, which holds its primary on March 5, three days
before Super Tuesday, could be an early indicator of Robertson's
strength. Observers say a strong Robertson showing there could give
him a big boost throughout the South. Robertson claims he is ready
to pull a stunner in South Carolina.
   Republican primaries or caucuses will be held on Super Tuesday
in 12 Southern states _ Alabama, Arkansas, Florida, Georgia,
Kentucky, Louisiana, Maryland, Mississippi, North Carolina,
Oklahoma, Tennessee and Texas. Nearly a third of the GOP's 2,277
convention delegates will be selected on Super Tuesday.
   ``I think Robertson in Tennessee is going to do pretty well,''
said Tommy Harper, Tennessee campaign manager for Bush. A worker at
Bush headquarters, speaking on condition she not be quoted by name,
goes further: ``Robertson is the one we are really worried about.''
   Arkansas State Democratic Executive Director Kip Blakely, trying
to assess Robertson's support, says: ``Remember the Right to Life
march a couple of weekends ago? It was raining and it was a
Saturday morning and it was freezing. There were over 3,000 people
who turned out. That's Pat Robertson.''
   Blakely predicts Robertson will win the Arkansas primary: ``I
think its his.''
   ``Robertson will probably come in second in Georgia _ if he
doesn't come in first,'' says Georgia GOP chairman emeritus Bob
Bell. ``You don't know how many people are out there in the
invisible army and how many will come out to vote. But they're
committed with a burning zeal.''
   In precinct meetings 16 days ago, Robertson won a plurality of
delegates to the county conventions which will be held in the 10
largest counties in Georgia. Only counties with populations over
80,000 held the meetings. Robertson chairman Brant Frost said
Robertson's support ranged from a low of 35 percent in Fulton
County (Atlanta) to a high of 96 percent in Bibb County.
   Next door in Alabama, Steve French, political director of the
state GOP, sees no prospect of a Robertson win.
   ``Texas is shaping up to be a Bush vs. Robertson race,'' Bush's
son, George Walker Bush, said last week in Texas.
   Robertson is seen as a factor behind Republican registration
jumps in many states.
   In Louisiana, Robertson state director Billy E. McCormack,
citing a 6 percent jump in Republican registration since October,
says, ``We feel like we were responsible for 90 to 95 percent of
them.''
   ``You take Hopkins County, a very conservative, Bible-Belt area
which had a 16 percent increase in (Republican) registration from
May to October,'' observes Stan B. Smith, political director for
the Kentucky GOP. ``You got to feel, if you put two and two
together, that a lot of that is Robertson.''
   But Bush's state chairman in Kentucky, Harold Rogers, says of
the Robertson strength: ``Essentially it's still limited to the
religious conservatives. I don't see him breaking out beyond that
very narrow base, except in spotty cases, here and there.''
</TEXT>
