<1ST_LINE>r w PM-UPI 3rdLd-Writethru a0622 02-22 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UPI, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0622,0654</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to include background, quotes from Brian;
picks up 9th graf, `To finance...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new managers of United Press International
plan no hirings, firings or changes in service for at least two
months while they study the company's future, the wire service's
new president said today.
   ``Everything is frozen'' during the study period, Paul Steinle
said in a news conference. The new management team has not decided
on what course to follow with the financially ailing company.
   While Steinle would not deal in specifics, he said he believes
that America's news executives ``want two wire services'' but he
said he still needs to talk with people in the news industry
because he and others want UPI to become ``a market-driven
company.''
   The management and a team of 15 experts will interview the staff
and media executives, assess the company's financial situation and
look at options for the next four to six weeks. At that time they
hope to have a business plan detailing the company's future.
   Steinle works for WNW Group Inc., a media investment group whose
chairman is Dr. Earl W. Brian. Brian recently formed WNW, a holding
company, to take control of UPI from Mexican publisher Mario
Vazquez Rana.
   Brian said WNW purchased control of Vazquez Rana's stock for 10
years in UPI for a ``substantial cash payment,'' but he would not
say how much. The announcement was made late Friday.
   Brian, 45, is chairman of Infotechnology Corp., a New York firm
with at least partial interest in 22 companies, including Financial
News Network, a cable TV service. The companies are mostly in the
area of information or venture capital.
   Brian served as secretary of California's Health and Welfare
Agency when Ronald Reagan was governor and went to the 1976
Republican National Convention as a delegate in Reagan's
unsuccessful bid to defeat Gerald Ford. In 1974, he unsuccessfully
sought the Republican nomination for Senate.
   He told The Los Angeles Times on Sunday that revitalizing UPI
under American ownership was an important personal goal. He added,
however, that his conservative views would not influence news
coverage.
   ``This thing to me is just a little deeper than an issue of
turning another company around,'' Brian said. ``As a conservative
Republican, as far as I'm concerned, UPI is an extremely important
asset to American people.''
   Giving the wire service new emphasis in such areas as financial
news and sports scores, using new technologies for delivery, are
being considered, he said. Referring to his business interests in
those areas, Brian said, ``We believe that a lot of this stuff can
be done directly by UPI itself.''
   To finance continuing losses at UPI, Brian said he will ask
private investors to put up money.
   Vazquez Rana, who paid $41 million to acquire UPI from Chapter
11 proceedings in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in June 1986, reportedly
lost a million dollars a month on UPI.
   Brian and Steinle said they hoped to improve UPI's marketing
capabilities, and that Brian's presence would help.
   The new managers will be ``doing it all in English,'' Brian
said, a reference to Vazquez Rana's inability to speak English.
   Meantime, Al Rossiter, UPI's executive editor, said that
``morale is soaring'' at UPI since the new managers took over.
   One of the reasons Brian could not purchase UPI outright was an
agreement that Vazquez Rana signed with the Wire Service Guild
giving the union the right of first refusal to buy UPI.
   The new UPI managers plan to meet later today with the Wire
Service Guild.
   Earlier, guild negotiator and spokesman Dan Carmichael said the
union ``wants to see UPI remain an integrated, quality, competitive
general international news service.''
   A proxy represents a transfer of voting power represented by the
ownership shares, but not the shares themselves.
</TEXT>
