<HEAD>Book-Lovers Protest Library Closure</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS typo to make it St. Pancras in 3rd graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty book-lovers spent their third straight day
holed up inside a London public library Monday to protest the
library's planned closure. They passed the time reading and talking.
   ``Libraries are vital to civilized life,'' said protest
organizer Roy Charterton, 62, a marketing consultant.
   Supporters in the street below the St. Pancras Reference Library
used a rope to hoist food supplies up to the protesters.
   ``We are sleeping on the floor and bringing food up through a
window ... as we have been told if we leave we cannot get back
in,'' Charterton said.
   The sit-in began Saturday and is scheduled to continue until
Tuesday, when Camden borough councilors are due to meet.
   The borough blames government-demanded budget cuts for the
library's closure.
