<1ST_LINE>r a AM-YaleWomen     02-22 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yale Women,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposing Groups In Uneasy Truce At Yale Women's Center </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN OKULA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women students on both sides of the
abortion issue are uneasily sharing the Yale Women's Center this
semester after the university overrode the center's decision to
exclude opponents of abortion.
   ``We've been meeting there once a week,'' said senior Kelly
Askew, president of Yale Students for Life. ``It's not entirely
welcoming, but it's getting much better. ... There was lots of
anger, bitter feelings.''
   Askew's group, which has about 10 members, asked the student
coordinating committee of the Women's Center for permission to meet
there last semester. The committee said no, largely because of
differences over abortion.
   The Women's Center, in the basement of a campus building,
provides meeting space for several organizations including the
staff of the student feminist magazine Aurora, the Women's Action
Coalition and a lesbian group.
   ``The pro-life stand made people uncomfortable,'' said Cory
Margenau, a Yale senior and a coordinating committee member. ``It
was a very unique situation with the Women's Center. We've never
had any groups who were supportive of pro-life opinions try to come
in.''
   When the coordinating committee rejected Askew's group, she said
she viewed it as discrimination.
   ``We asked if they were violating the Yale freedom of expression
policy,'' Askew said. ``The center is called the Yale Women's
Center and there's no denying the fact that we were all Yale women.
I would have no argument if they called themselves the Yale
pro-abortion center.''
   She added, ``There is a whole pressure here to be `PC,' to be
politically correct. ... Part of being PC is being pro-abortion.''
   The anti-abortion group took the matter to Yale's
administration, and both sides met with Patricia Pierce, associate
dean of Yale College.
   Sidney Altman, the dean of Yale College, made the final
decision, Askew and Margenau said.
   An assistant to Altman referred questions to Pierce, who said
the dispute ``had to do with freedom of expression and not with
one's personal political views.''
   Pierce said that as a result of the dispute, the dean's office
decided to spell out who was eligible to use the women's center:
groups primarily composed of undergraduate women and concerned with
women's issues.
   Margenau said she now agrees with Altman's decision that the
center is Yale property and should therefore be neutral, but the
Womens' Center coordinating committee saw another issue take shape
with his decision.
   ``We, the five coordinators, learned how little power we really
have when it comes to a man's decision. ... The main problem was
realizing who really had the power, and it was Dean Altman, and it
was kind of a blow,'' Margenau said.
   Countered Pierce: ``All the associate deans are women, and we
were all in on the decision, and we thought it an excellent one.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
