<HEAD>US Dismisses Video As Made Under Duress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon-Kidnap Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration said Monday a
videotape by Marine Lt. Col. William Higgins in which he repeated
the demands of his captors in Lebanon has no validity because it
was made under duress.
   ``All statements made by hostages are made under duress,'' said
State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley, echoing a similar
comment by White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   Mrs. Oakley noted that the demands, including an Israeli
withdrawal from its border security zone in south Lebanon, are the
same as those announced last Friday by the Organization of the
Opporessed on Earth, one of two groups which claim to have kidnaped
Higgins.
   She also disputed a statement by Peggy Say, sister of the
longest-held American hostage in Lebanon, that the administration
is displaying a double standard by working hardest to free captives
seized most recently.
   ``We all can understand and sympathize with her anguish and her
frustration and her sorrow over her brother's continuing
captivity,'' Mrs. Oakley said.
   ``We're making our efforts on behalf of all the hostages. Our
goal is not the release of this one or that one but rather the safe
return of all the hostages.''
   Mrs. Say's brother, Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, was kidnapped on March 16,
1985.
   Mrs. Say contended that the U.S. government has been less
vigorous in seeking out her brother than Higgins, a onetime top
aide to former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger.
   At the White House, Fitzwater said the Higgins videotape had
been viewed by members of the National Security Council and White
House staff but he did not believe President Reagan had seen it.
   ``We continue to call for the immediate and safe release of
Colonel Higgins as well as other hostages in Lebanon,'' Fitzwater
said. ``We are not going to give in to the demands of terrorists.
We will continue to pursue all avenues for his release.''
   Asked if Reagan had any reaction, the spokesman said, ``You know
the president's deep convictions about Colonel Higgins and all the
hostages, but we want to avoid saying anything that could
exacerbate the situation.''
</TEXT>
