<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ShuttleTest     02-22 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle Test,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shuttle Booster Joint Due Wednesday Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morton Thiokol Inc. will conduct the
fourth in a series of six firing tests for the space shuttle's
redesigned booster rocket's nozzle-to-case joint Wednesday, company
officials say.
   The objective of the test is to evaluate performance of the
joint between sections of the solid fuel booster with deliberately
flawed insulation adhesive and a damaged O-ring gasket, said Morton
Thiokol spokesman Rocky Raab.
   ``The test will allow engineers to evaluate the fail-safe
performance of the redesigned joint,'' he said.
   The test, to be held at the aerospace company's Wasatch
Operations plant 25 miles west of Brigham City, is one of hundreds
undertaken by Morton Thiokol as part of its booster redesign
efforts in the wake of the Jan. 28, 1986, explosion of the shuttle
Challenger and deaths of its seven crew members.
   A presidential commission blamed a leaking booster rocket seal
for igniting the shuttle's huge external tank for its liquid fuel
main engines.
   The new case-to-nozzle joint includes 100 added bolts,
adhesively bonded insulation surfaces and the added O-ring.
</TEXT>
