<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 1503EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Allegro     02-22 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Allegro,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scholar Who Helped Unravel Dead Sea Scrolls Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. John Allegro, renowned for his work in
deciphering the Dead Sea Scrolls but ridiculed for his theories
that Western religions were based on the worship of mushrooms, has
died. He was 65.
   Allegro died at his home on Feb. 17, his birthday, according to
death notices and obituaries published Monday. No cause of death
was given. He is to be cremated Tuesday.
   Allegro was a brilliant student of Semitic languages at
Manchester University and went on to study Hebrew dialects at
Oxford University.
   In 1953, he was named to an international team formed to
decipher the Dead Sea Scrolls, which were discovered in caves at
Qumran on the shores of the Dead Sea six years earlier.
   The scrolls, which spanned from about 100 B.C. to 70 A.D.,
included the oldest known manuscripts of books from the Old
Testament. Allegro's gift for deciphering minute texts was crucial.
His book, ``The Dead Sea Scrolls,'' was published in 1956 and
became a bestseller.
   Allegro's subsequent notoriety caused derision in the scientific
community but developed a cult following in the early 1970s.
Allegro, in his 1970 book ``The Sacred Mushroom and the Cross,''
contended that Judaism and Christianity were in fact products of an
ancient sex-and-mushroom cult.
   He theorized that Jesus's last words on the cross were not a
lament to God but ``a paean of praise to the god of the mushroom.''
   Although trained for the Methodist ministry, he became a fervent
anti-Christian devoted to debunking the story of Jesus.
   Allegro also published a 1966 book, ``Search in the Desert,''
about an unsuccessful search for lost scrolls in the Judean Desert.
   He is survived by a son and a daughter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880222-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 1514EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-CableTV 1stLd-Writethru a0561 02-22 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Cable TV, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0561,450</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 3rd graf, The court's action, to show new appeal
possible</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand a ruling
that drastically limits the power of communities to regulate cable
television and raises doubts about the constitutionality of a key
federal law governing cable operations.
   The court, citing a lack of jurisdiction, turned away an appeal
by two California cities barred from enforcing public access and
other rules challenged by a cable operator.
   The court's action, which appears to have been based on narrow
procedural grounds, leaves open the possibility of a subsequent
appeal.
   The dispute was between officials of Palo Alto and Atherton,
Calif., and Century Federal Inc., the cable operator.
   U.S. District Judge Eugene F. Lynch ruled last September that
cable regulations adopted by the cities unconstitutionally violated
Century Federal's free-speech rights.
   He threw out regulations that required Century Federal:
   _To provide public access channels for those not connected with
the cable company.
   _To wire the entire community to make service available to all
residents.
   _To use a ``state-of-the-art'' system to keep pace with the
latest technological advances.
   The judge, who previously had ordered city officials to award an
operating license to Century Federal, called for further hearings
to study franchise fee requirements adopted by the cities.
   Palo Alto and Atherton officials said the ruling appears to
declare unconstitutional a 1984 federal law regulating cable TV,
even though the judge did not say in so many words he was
invalidating the law.
   Although Lynch ``purported not to decide the constitutionality
of any provision of the act, (his) decision in fact holds that
numerous sections of that statute are unconstitutional,'' lawyers
for the cities said.
   The Reagan administration, in a ``friend-of-the-court'' legal
brief filed by Justice Department lawyers, urged the court to deny
the cities' appeal.
   The Supreme Court, in a 1986 ruling that has some bearing on the
case acted on today, raised the possibility that communities may be
barred from granting exclusive cable TV franchises.
   The court said cable franchise activities ``plainly implicate
First Amendment interests.'' But the justices stopped short of a
definitive ruling on the constitutional rights of cable operators.
   The ruling was in contrast to earlier decisions denying a
constitutional right to operate over-the-air television or radio
stations.
   Many cities award exclusive cable franchises city-wide or for
various regions within the city. They also impose rules similar to
those adopted by Palo Alto and Atherton.
   The case is Palo Alto vs. Century Federal, 87-946.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880222-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 1514EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SchoolShootout     02-22 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Shootout,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parents Say Students Should Wear Identification Badges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some parents of students at a school
where three faculty members were shot want students to wear
identification badges and be subject to random searches with
hand-held metal detectors.
   ``We're feeling as though some of (the school's) rules and
regulations need to be looked at,'' said Ivy Villafana, whose
daughter attends Pinellas Park High School. ``If we cannot have
these metal detectors, then we can have doors that lock from the
outside.''
   About 50 parents met Sunday night to discuss ways to prevent
further violence at the school.
   They plan to submit their ideas to the Pinellas County School
Board during its regular meeting Wednesday.
   School officials were not invited to Sunday's meeting, but
representatives from the school's Parent-Teacher-Student
Association were on hand.
   On Feb. 11 two administrators and one student teacher were
wounded in an altercation with two students. Assistant Principal
Richard W. Allen died of his injuries Wednesday.
   At the meeting, one woman favored providing the school resource
officer _ a Pinellas Park police officer assigned to the school _
with a hand-held metal detector. The officer should make random
searches, she said.
   ``Doesn't have to be a reason. Just stop them and run them up
and down,'' she said.
   Principal Marilyn Heminger declined to comment specifically on
any of the group's suggestions.
   She said she was glad to hear the meeting was positive, ``and I
hope that from (the meeting) come some good things that we can work
with.''
   One of the two students accused in the shootings had recently
been suspended for cursing a teacher.
   Linda Leotti, organizer of Sunday night's meeting, told parents
that other school systems she surveyed around the country send
students to counselors before suspending them. She will suggest
Wednesday that Pinellas County institute a similar policy.
   ``We want suspensions, but we want counseling,'' Ms. Villafana
said. ``And we don't mean guidance counselors, we mean
psychologists.''
   If a student uses profanity when expressing frustration to a
teacher, he shouldn't be suspended, she said.
   Among the other suggestions: providing counseling for teachers
and students; having a substitute resource officer when the regular
officer is out; providing new carpeting to replace one with
bloodstains; having a crisis-intervention team; and having a parent
volunteer force patrolling hallways.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
