<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Debo     02-22 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Debo,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Lady Of Oklahoma History Angie Debo Dies At 98</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARSHALL, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angie Debo, who came to Oklahoma by
covered wagon and became known as ``The First Lady of Oklahoma
History,'' has died at age 98.
   Ms. Debo, of Marshall, died Sunday at an Enid hospital, said
Steve Lindholm, owner of Abernathy Funeral Home in Crescent.
   The nationally esteemed historian wrote 13 books and hundreds of
articles about Indian and Oklahoma history. Last month, Gov. Henry
Bellmon presented her with the 1987 Award for Scholarly Distinction
from the American Historical Association.
   In a new forward she wrote at age 91 for her 1949 book
``Oklahoma, Foot-Loose and Fancy-Free,'' Ms. Debo called her home
``more than just another state.''
   ``It is a lens in which the long rays of time are focused into
the brightest of light,'' she wrote. ``In its magnifying clarity,
dim facets of the American character stand more clearly revealed.
For in Oklahoma all the experiences that went into the making of
the nation have been speeded up. Here all the American traits have
been intensified. The one who can interpret Oklahoma can grasp the
meaning of America in the modern world.''
   Her books include ``The Rise and Fall of the Choctaw Republic,''
``And Still The Waters Run,'' ``Geronimo: The Man, His Time, His
Place'' and ``Prairie City.''
   In 1985, her portrait was hung permanently in the rotunda of the
state Capitol, near portraits Will Rogers, Jim Thorpe, and Sequoyah.
   She earned the John H. Dunning Prize of the American Historical
Society and the Alfred A. Knopf Fellowship in history.
   A one-hour documentary on her life and work is scheduled to be
broadcast next fall as part of Public Broadcasting's ``The American
Experience'' series.
   A funeral was scheduled for Wednesday, Lindholm said, adding
that she had no surviving relatives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
