<HEAD>Duffey Rejects 2-Day Moratorium</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Massachusetts chancellor
on Monday rejected calls to excuse students from classes or work so
they could take part in a moratorium to consider racial tensions at
the 25,000-student university.
   ``The university administration joins the Undergraduate Student
Senate, which represents the wide majority of students on the
campus, in standing against the moratorium on classes planned by
members of the Graduate Student Senate this week,'' Joseph Duffey
said in a statement.
   Duffey said the school considered gaining social awareness part
of education, but, ``We expect students to attend class and to gain
social awareness through class.''
   ``Participating in the boycott will not excuse students from
responsibility for meeting their academic obligations,'' Duffey
said.
   The moratorium, scheduled for Tuesday and Wednesday, was urged
by students last week following settlement of a six-day occupation
of a university building by minority students seeking harsher
treatment of people involved in racist behavior on campus.
   About 300 students marched to Duffey's office on Friday to urge
him to sanction the moratorium.
   The Graduate Student Senate and the Minority Graduate Student
Association called for all faculty and graduate instructors to
cancel their classes, ``but still hold students responsible for the
material that would have been taught.''
