<DATELINE>EULESS, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cancer patient who has been reading Zane
Grey books since his childhood had a dream fulfilled when columnist
Bob Greene delivered a rare book that completes an 89-book
collection of the Western author.
   ``I've got something for you,'' said Greene, of the Chicago
Tribune, when he handed a small green book to 73-year-old Mack
Landers.
   The book Greene delivered Sunday in this Fort Worth suburb,
``Don, The Story Of A Lion Dog,'' was published 60 years ago and
only about 100 copies exist in this country. It was the last of 89
books Landers needed to complete his collection.
   Landers was diagnosed with colon cancer in 1982 and has been
told by doctors he has less than three months to live.
   Greene wrote of Landers' search for the book in his nationally
syndicated column, and said five or six people from across the
nation called offering copies. Greene accepted one from Dr. James
H. Vickers, president of the National Zane Grey's West Society and
director of the pathobiology and primatology laboratory at the
National Institutes of Health in Bethesda, Md.
   Another copy was offered by Zane Grey's son, Loren.
