<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bulgaria-Fire     02-22 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bulgaria-Fire,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Kills 6 in Bulgarian Ski Resort</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pre-dawn fire Monday destroyed a
Bulgarian ski-resort hotel that caters to foreign tourists, killing
six people and injuring 36, Bulgaria's official news agency BTA
reported.
   A Western diplomat said a Dutch woman was killed when she jumped
from a window to escape the flames.
   BTA said those injured in the fire at Borovets, 22 miles
southeast of Sofia, were from Britain, the Soviet Union, West
Germany, the Netherlands, Greece and Denmark.
   It said two of the dead were Dutch, one was Bulgarian and three
had not been identified.
   Bulgaria has made great efforts recently to attract Western
tourists to its modern mountain resorts for relatively inexpensive
ski vacations. Borovets is bidding for the 1989 Alpine skiing world
championships.
   Throughout the day, most information on the blaze at the
Moussala Hotel came from Western diplomats in Sofia, the capital,
and two British tour companies. BTA did not issue its first full
report until nearly 15 hours after the fire started.
   ``Measures were taken to put out the blaze but the building was
quickly engulfed in flames,'' the BTA report said. ``In the panic
that followed, six people died.''
   ``The causes of the fire are still not known,'' it said, and a
``special commission has been appointed to investigate.'' BTA
added: ``The necessary medical aid has been provided to the injured
and the rest of the tourists have been accommodated in other
hotels.''
   A man who answered the telephone at the state tourist office in
Borovets, and would not give his name, said the 193-bed
Alpine-style hotel was completely destroyed.
   Reports said most victims were being treated in local clinics,
but a Dutch diplomat said two injured citizens of the Netherlands
were taken to Sofia because there was no more room at the clinics.
   The Global Ski tour organization in London had 32 customers
booked at the hotel, and said a representative in Bulgaria acted as
interpreter to help police interview the injured and others.
   Several Western embassies said they sent diplomats to Borovets
seeking more information about the fire and the victims.
   Carol Thatcher, daughter of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of
Britain, was a recent visitor to Borovets. The picturesque village
in the Rila Mountains is near Mount Moussala, at 9,652 feet the
highest peak in Bulgaria.
</TEXT>
