<HEAD>US Says Sandinista Delay in Talks ``Extremely Unfortunate''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Monday it was
``extremely unfortunate'' that Nicaraguan government cease-fire
negotiators did not respond quickly enough to a new truce proposal
to prevent the talks from breaking down.
   Spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley also welcomed what she said was the
unconditional acceptance of the proposal by the U.S.-backed Contra
rebels. The plan had been outlined by the chief mediator, Cardinal
Miguel Obando y Bravo, during talks last week in Guatemala City.
   The positive attitude of the Contras ``further indication of the
resistance's willingness to negotiate in good faith and of their
desire to achieve a cease-fire,'' Mrs. Oakley said.
   She added that the Sandinista government's delay in responding
to the proposal apparantly led to Obando y Bravo's decision to
break off the talks a day early.
   The cleric's proposal called for the Sandinistas to free all
political prisoners, allow complete freedom of expression and
resume a dialogue with opposition parties, among other measures.
   Nicaragua's leftist government has said the cease-fire
discussions should be limited to the technical aspects of achieving
a truce and that political questions should be dealt with
separately.
   Obando y Bravo's decision to suspend the talks caught the
Sandinista negotiators by surprise. They said they had been ready
to accept his plan in principle and to continue the discussions.
