<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     02-22 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Warship Fires Warning Shots At Approaching Speedboats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. warship, arriving in the Persian
Gulf on Monday as the newest addition to the Navy's escort
squadron, fired machine-gun warning shots to chase away two fishing
boats that ventured too close.
   Although the craft proved to be harmless, a U.S. official said,
the boats at first appeared to be Boston Whaler-type vessels, often
used by Iran's Revolutionary Guards to attack commercial shipping.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
Trenton fired after the boats approached within 3,300 yards of a
U.S. convoy, 30 miles off the coast of Dubai, at about 3 p.m.
   He said, ``Trenton ... issued two verbal warnings which were not
heeded, and when the boats came within 3,000 meters, it fired a
flare and bursts of .50-caliber machine-gun fire, at which time the
craft stopped and then moved off to the northeast.''
   A helicopter sent up by the missile frigate John A. Moore,
accompanying the Trenton, ``confirmed through observation that both
were fishing boats, and neither was hit or damaged,'' he added.
   While no U.S. warship has been directly attacked by Iran,
several have fired warning shots when unidentified small boats
approached too close or ignored verbal cautions.
   In one such incident last year, an Indian fisherman was killed
by gunfire from a Navy frigate.
   American ships also have fired warning shots or come close to
firing missiles at Iraqi warplanes flying too close during attack
sorties against Iranian coastal oil shipping.
   A delegation of U.S. officials is visiting Baghdad to discuss
the problem with Iraqi military leaders.
   The 17,000-ton Trenton sailed through the Strait of Hormuz hours
earlier to join the Middle East Force, the Navy's flotilla in the
gulf. It carried a 400-man U.S. Marine combat unit and a contingent
of Marine attack helicopters.
   U.S. officials said the group was not considered one of the
Navy's gulf ``transits'' as it did not include any of the Kuwaiti
tankers reflagged by Washington last year for protection from
Iranian attack.
   The Trenton, one of the ships involved in a current realignment
of navy units in the region, is a replacement.
   When the reshuffling is completed, probably within a week, it
will leave the gulf-based force at 16 ships, including six mine
sweepers, down one from its maximum strength of 17.
   Next Saturday, Rear Adm. Anthony A. Less will take over command
of the gulf force from Rear Adm. Harold J. Bernsen.
   U.S. officials said the Marines aboard the Trenton would provide
security for naval operations in the gulf, where the 7{-year-old
Iraq-Iran war has seriously affected commercial shipping.
   Iran's official news agency said a prototype of the ``first
Iranian-made airplane'' made a successful test flight Monday and
would soon go into mass production.
   It said the ``multiple-purpose'' aircraft can be adapted for
military use, and all parts were made in Iran by experts affiliated
with the Revolutionary Guards corps. Each plane will ``save
$500,000 in foreign exchange,'' said the Islamic Republic News
Agency.
   Iran also announced that at the orders of Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, 1,139 prisoners have been released as part of an amnesty
to mark the ninth anniversary of the Islamic revolution.
   IRNA said the detainees released in various cities in Iran were
``repentant'' and had been pardoned.
   It did not say what they were jailed for or on what day they
were released.
   Iran has already reported freeing more than 1,000 other
prisoners following the anniversary of the Islamic seizure of power
on Feb. 11, 1979.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
