<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mecham     02-22 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham's Criminal Trial Postponed Two Weeks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Evan Mecham's criminal trial on
charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan was delayed by a
judge Monday until March 22.
   The delay from the original March 9 trial date gives both sides
time to handle pretrial motions and answers, said Judge Michael
Ryan of Maricopa County Superior Court.
   Mecham also faces a May 17 recall election and a Feb. 29
impeachment trial by the state Senate.
   He is charged with six counts of fraud, perjury and filing false
documents in connection with a $350,000 campaign loan made in
October 1986 by Tempe develper and attorney Barry Wolfson. Willard
Mecham, his brother's 1986 campaign treasurer, faces three similar
counts.
   The governor and brother did not answer reporters' questions
when they entered and left the courtroom.
   Assistant Attorney General Michael Cudahy told Ryan he needed
more time to reply to defense motions. Cudahy also complained that
attorneys for the Mechams had not yet made required pretrial
disclosures, including lists of witnesses and exhibits.
   Cudahy said the Mechams' lawyers made ``more or less a
grandstand play'' by saying in court Monday that they were ready to
go to trial when they had not made the disclosures.
   The governor's lawyer, Murray Miller, said those disclosures
would be made this week.
   Ryan said he would schedule a hearing later on several defense
motions to remand the charges to the state grand jury, dismiss some
of the counts and require grand jurors and the prosecutor to submit
to questioning.
   Willard Mecham's lawyer, Michael Scott, has claimed in court
papers that Attorney General Bob Corbin's office manipulated the
grand jury process by having most testimony presented to a state
grand jury that met last fall, but holding the matter over for a
new grand jury which indicted the Mechams on Jan. 5.
   Corbin's office has contended, however, that the matter was
given to a new grand jury to avoid possible bias because three
members of the previous grand jury had signed petitions to recall
Mecham.
   Miller told Ryan that he was prepared to have both the criminal
and impeachment trials simultaneously although he indicated he may
ask a court to delay the Senate's impeachment trial. However, he
did not say when or where he would file such a motion.
</TEXT>
