<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Raffin     02-22 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Raffin,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Actress Deborah Raffin, Star of NBC's ``Noble House,'' Loves China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deborah Raffin had hoped for an anonymous
vacation in the People's Republic of China, but on her first day
there, throngs of Chinese ran up to her shouting, ``nightmare,
nightmare.''
   ``It's funny now, but it wasn't funny then,'' the actress said
recently. ``At first I thought it was because of my blonde hair and
obvious Western looks. Then I started to think that maybe I was
somebody's idea of a nightmare.''
   What actually caused the commotion was the Chinese people
recognizing her from the 1976 film, ``Nightmare in Badham County,''
in which she played a hitchhiker hounded by a lecherous sheriff. It
was a major box office hit in China.
   That visit six years ago began a love affair between Miss Raffin
and China, and she continued to return, recently to film the $20
million miniseries, ``Noble House,'' airing this week on NBC. She
plays a tough corporate officer who falls for the head of a trading
house, played by Pierce Brosnan.
   ``I had been to Hong Kong about a dozen times before the filming
and took the role as an excuse to go back,'' Miss Raffin said. ``I
feel very comfortable there. It's like the Manhattan of Asia, so
colorful and romantic with a tremendous energy level. It's a world
few of us in the United States know anything about.''
</TEXT>
