<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Biaggi     02-22 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biaggi,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Expulsion is Only Appropriate Sanction for Biaggi, Committee Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Mario Biaggi's violation of House ethics
constituted ``criminal conduct of a most serious nature going to
the heart of his representational responsibilities'' and warranted
expulsion, the House Committee on Standards of Official Conduct
said in a report released Monday.
   The committee, which recommended Thursday that Biaggi, D-N.Y.,
be expelled from the seat he has held for 20 years, explained why
it had elected to exercise its most serious punishment.
   ``The facts and circumstances giving rise to the violations,
being of the most serious nature, warrant the imposition of the
most stringent sanction available to the House of
Representatives,'' the 148-page report said.
   ``Accordingly, the committee submits that expulsion is the only
sanction appropriate to the violations committed by Representative
Biaggi.''
   Biaggi was not in his office Monday, but he said Thursday that
he intended to vigorously fight the expulsion recommendation.
   Biaggi, 70, was convicted in September of illegally accepting a
paid Florida vacation from Meade Esposito, the former Brooklyn,
N.Y., Democratic leader. Esposito was seeking government help for
Coastal Dry Dock and Repair Co., a financially troubled Brooklyn
shipyard that owed $280,000 in premiums to Esposito's insurance
brokerage firm.
   Biaggi was also convicted of illegally crossing state lines to
accept the gratuity and obstructing justice by trying to influence
how Esposito answered the FBI's questions. He was sentenced to 2{
years in prison and a $500,000 fine, and is free pending appeal.
   The ethics committee concluded that Biaggi violated rules
against discrediting the House; accepting impermissible gifts from
a person or organization with a direct or indirect interest in
legislation; failing to report a gift worth $250 or more on his
financial disclosure form; and accepting a favor or benefit that
might be construed as influencing the performance of government
duties.
   After reviewing evidence from Biaggi's trial, the committee
``found that the offenses for which Representative Biaggi was
convicted involved criminal conduct of a most serious nature going
to the heart of his representational responsibilities.''
   The committee's resolution to expel Biaggi must be approved by
two-thirds of the 435-member House to take effect. The matter may
be taken up on the floor at any time, now that the committee report
has been released.
   If the resolution passes, Biaggi would be the second congressman
expelled from the House since the Civil War. Rep. Michael ``Ozzie''
Myers, D-Pa., was ousted in 1980 after his conviction in the Abscam
bribery scheme.
   The committee report also includes a transcript of its closed
Dec. 17, 1987, meeting, at which Biaggi pleaded for leniency and
declared, ``I am incorruptible.''
   Biaggi argued that the vacation he took, at a Florida health
spa, was ``hospitality'' from Esposito, a friend of 40 years, not a
gratuity.
   Placing the value of the vacation at about $3,000, Biaggi asked
rhetorically, ``Mario Biaggi is going to compromise himself for
$3,000? I wouldn't compromise myself for $100,000.''
   Biaggi also said he did not know that Esposito had business with
Coastal until a bugged telephone conversation on June 2, 1986, more
than a year after the Florida vacation.
</TEXT>
