<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--WarCriminal     02-22 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--War Criminal,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Convicted Of Nazi Atrocities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet citizen was convicted of Nazi war crimes
Monday and sentenced to 15 years in jail, the official news agency
reported.
   Tass said Dmitri Maslo was found guilty of high treason and
other charges after a trial in the mining town of Selidovo in the
Ukrainian republic.
   During World War II, Maslo joined the police force in the
Ukrainian city of Krasnoarmeisk and ``voluntarily went over to the
side of Nazi invaders,'' Tass said. It said he arrested and
tortured Ukrainians and Jews and ``on many occasions he took part
in the shooting of peaceful civilians.''
   Maslo, who went on trial Feb. 9, also was accused of helping
kill prisoners in the Krasnoarmeisk jail in 1943 as Soviet forces
began liberating the area.
   He fled when the Nazis withdrew and settled in Khristinovka,
near the Ukrainian capital of Kiev, Tass said.
</TEXT>
