<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GangViolence     02-22 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gang Violence,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Die, Five Injured As Gang Violence Continues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five people were killed and five others were
injured in a flurry of weekend gang-related shootings despite a
police sweep aimed at curbing street violence.
   Sixty officers swept through gang-infested south-central Los
Angeles during a special 16-hour campaign against gang members and
drug dealers Saturday and Sunday. They arrested more than 50 people
for crimes ranging from narcotics sales to concealed weapons to
grand theft auto, said Lt. Mark Leap.
   Despite the show of force, the violence was unrelenting.
   In one of the weekend killings, a man was shot by three
teen-agers on bicycles, said Sheriff's Deputy Gabriel Ramirez.
   In one especially flagrant gang shooting, four men in a car
shouted gang slogans and opened fire on about 50 people gathered in
front of a Taco Bell restaurant Sunday, police said. Four
teen-agers were wounded.
   The escalating street gang problem in Los Angeles became evident
last month when it stretched out of crime-ridden south-central Los
Angeles and reached into upscale Westwood Village, where a
27-year-old woman died when she got caught in gang crossfire.
   The strong police response to that shooting sparked an outcry in
less-affluent communities such as the south-central area, where
more than 100 people were killed in gang violence last year.
   Mayor Tom Bradley last week signed an ordinance giving the city
150 more officers, many of which will be used to battle gangs. The
City Council also approved an anti-gang project that will result in
up to 100 gang members in jail on drug charges each month, said
Deputy Police Chief Glenn Levant, 45, the department's
newly-appointed ``gang czar.''
</TEXT>
