<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SoldierofFortune     02-22 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soldier of Fortune,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Son Fears Father, Convicted in Killing of Mother</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-age boy whose father hired a hit man
through Soldier of Fortune magazine to kill his mother fought back
tears Monday as he testified he feared a similar fate.
   Gary Wayne Black, 18, took the stand in the second week of a
federal court trial of a lawsuit filed by him and his maternal
grandmother, Marjorie Einmann.
   They are seeking $22.5 million from the Boulder, Colo.-based
magazine, accusing the self-proclaimed ``Journal for Professional
Adventurers'' of negligence for running an ad that led to the
slaying of Sandra Black.
   The ad, placed by John Wayne Hearn, brought him into contact
with Robert Black.
   Black is on Texas' death row for paying Hearn $10,000 to carry
out the killing of his wife. Hearn is serving three life terms in
Florida for that and two other slayings.
   Gary Black, a high school senior who found his mother shot to
death in their Bryan home three years ago Sunday, described her as
understanding and kind.
   ``She just was the worst person I could lose,'' he said.
   Mrs. Einmann, who also testified Monday as plaintiffs completed
their case against the magazine, said her grandson was so
devastated by the killing he not sleep alone or enter his house
alone for a year and a half afterward.
   He constantly twitched, and suffered from severe headaches, she
said.
   During treatment by state mental health counselors, the boy told
how much he feared his father, she said.
   ``They said his mind was so damaged. ... He feared if someone
could get into his own home to kill his own mother, someone could
get into my house to kill him.''
   ``If he could hire someone out of Soldier of Fortune magazine to
kill my mother, he could hire someone out of Soldier of Fortune
magazine to kill me, too,'' Gary Black said of his father.
   Hearn's ad appeared in four issues of the magazine in late 1984,
offering services of former Marine and Vietnam veterans and weapons
specialists with jungle warfare expertise for ``high-risk
assignments'' in the United States or overseas.
   A criminologist, Park Dietz, testified last week the reference
to ``high-risk'' meant the person placing the ad was willing to
commit a crime.
   Attorneys for the magazine do not deny the ad brought Hearn and
Black together, but insist publisher Robert Brown had no way of
knowing the ad was for illegal activity.
   Brown has testified he would have halted the classified ads for
personal services if he had known they were linked to crimes.
   Defense attorneys planned to call several witnesses to testify
for the magazine's value as a defense journal.
   Among them would be Col. Charles Beckwith, who led the Army's
Delta Force in the unsuccessful attempt in 1980 to rescue the
American hostages in Iran.
</TEXT>
