<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ArmoneSentencing     02-22 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Armone Sentencing,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reputed Mob Figure Gets 15-Year Sentence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 70-year-old reputed underboss of the Gambino
crime family was sentenced Monday to 15 years in prison and fined
$820,000 for a racketeering conviction.
   Joseph Armone, of Brooklyn, was convicted Dec. 22 of
racketeering conspiracy involving extortion, bribery and illegal
interstate travel to commit bribery.
   U.S. District Judge Jack B. Weinstein said he sentenced Armone
to prison despite his advanced age because he was convinced Armone
was a high-ranking member of the crime family.
   Weinstein also cited Armone's lengthy criminal record, which he
said began when the defendant was 15 years old.
   Armone had faced a maximum sentence of 20 years for the most
serious charge, racketeering.
   According to the prosecution, Armone was elevated from capo to
underboss after he was indicted in 1986. It was also alleged that
Armone was observed meeting with reputed Gambino boss John Gotti
during the trial.
   Armone was jailed at the time of his conviction after he refused
to renounce any organized crime ties as a condition for his release
from detention. On Monday, Armone made a brief statement to
Weinstein in which he said he had not meant any disrespect to the
court in refusing the offer but that he turned it down because he
was worried about ``his rights''
   Prior to sentencing, defense attorney Mark Krasnow said Armone
had ``paid his dues to society'' for his previous convictions and
charged that his client had been entrapped by the government.
   Prosecutor Douglas Grover, a special attorney with the Justice
Department's Organized Crime Strike Force, said Armone had been
convicted of ``serious and compelling'' crimes and of being a
leader in the Gambino family. his life,'' Grover said.
   One of the bribery charges accused Armone and one of his
co-defendants, Joseph N. Gallo, of unsuccessfully plotting to give
a $20,000 bribe so that Gallo's son would be transferred from a
state prison, where he was then being held, to a federal prison,
where presumably he would receive better treatment.
</TEXT>
