<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NorthernIreland     02-22 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Priest Says Shooting Victim Was Harassed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former parish priest of an
Irish nationalist who was shot dead from a British army observation
tower said Monday the victim was harassed by police and soldiers
for at least five years.
   The Rev. Brendan McHugh said Aidan McAnespie, 23, had to cross
into the Irish Republic every day to his job and was harassed
constantly at the army checkpoint.
   ``We complained time out of number to the police and military,
but no action was ever taken. Life for the poor man had just become
unbearable,'' McHugh told reporters.
   The army said it ``deeply regrets'' the shooting Sunday. A
spokesman said McAnespie was hit by a bullet fired from an
observation post about half a mile from the frontier in County
Tyrone.
   Police said the soldier involved was in military custody and an
investigation was being conducted. The soldier was not identified
and police would not comment on the priest's allegations.
   Relatives said McAnespie was walking to a regular weekly Gaelic
football game in Aughnacloy, the County Tyrone village where he
lives.
   Francis Molloy, a local councilman, said McAnespie was an
election worker for Sinn Fein, legal political arm of the outlawed
Irish Republican Army. The IRA denied he was among its members and
McHugh, the priest, said he was not involved in paramilitary
activity.
   ``He was never abused physically, just verbally, and his car was
often taken apart,'' he said. ``I don't know why he was singled out
for such treatment.
   ``The campaign against him must have been going on for at least
five years. Other young lads were also stopped, but Aidan appeared
to be getting special treatment.''
   Shootings of civilians by security forces have become rare
compared with the early 1970s, when Protestant-Catholic strife in
the British province was at its height.
   McAnespie's death came at a time of severe strain in Anglo-Irish
relations over other incidents involving police and the province's
Roman Catholic minority. The government in Dublin demanded a speedy
report.
   Britain provoked Irish outrage last month by saying it would not
prosecute policemen accused of perverting justice in the aftermath
of the killings of six unarmed Catholics in three incidents in late
1982.
   The strain was compounded by a British appeals court's refusal
to overturn the conviction of six Irishmen for two bombings that
killed 21 people in 1974. Irish officials believe the six are
victims of a miscarriage of justice.
</TEXT>
