<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugParachutist     02-22 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Parachutist,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Charges Dismissed Against Drug Parachutist's Alleged Conspirator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SHARP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Monday dismissed
drug-related charges against a woman whose boyfriend fell to his
death from a plane in 1985 with 77 pounds of cocaine and a
defective parachute strapped to his body.
   U.S. District Judge James H. Jarvis dropped the counts at the
request of Assistant U.S. Attorney James R. Dedrick, who last week
lost a bid to use statements mad by Rebecca Sharp to undercover
agents as evidence against her.
   Ms. Sharp, 32, a paralegal in Lexington, Ky., had been set to go
on trial March 1 on charges of conspiring with her boyfriend,
former Lexington narcotics officer Andrew Thornton II, to import
cocaine and of distributing the drug.
   Under the terms of the dismissal, Dedrick can seek another
indictment against Ms. Sharp. Meanwhile, her attorney said Ms.
Sharp was pleased at the movie and hopeful the case was over.
   Thornton's body was found on a Knoxville driveway Sept. 11,
1985. Bags of cocaine were tied to his waist, and federal
authorities have linked him to about 200 pounds of the drug found
in duffel bags scattered across northern Georgia for apparent later
retrieval. The empty plane was found crashed.
   A few days later, Drug Enforcement Agency special agent Kieran
Kobell, posing as an associate or representative of ``the
Colombians'' who supposedly provided Thornton the cocaine, went to
Lexington with a government informant, Bertram Gordon.
   Kobel said the two met with Ms. Sharp and she revealed an
intimate knowledge of the cocaine smuggling operation.
   Dedrick's motion did not specify why he wanted the charges
dismissed, but it seems likely the suppression of Ms. Sharp's
statements was a direct cause.
   U.S. Magistrate Robert P. Murrian ruled Feb. 12 that those
statements were made in fear.
   Kobell ``was playing the part of a Colombian or representative
of a Colombian or Colombians who had lost $12,000,000 worth of
cocaine,'' he wrote in upholding the motion to keep Ms. Sharp's
statements out of evidence.
   ``I believe that under the circumstances of this case, the
defendant (Ms. Sharp) had to have been in great personal fear for
her safety when she made the statements. ...,'' Murrian wrote. ``It
would have been smart from her point of view to promise that the
deal would go through, that the Colombians would not be `ripped
off' and that she would kill if necessary to see that happen.''
   Murrian also said Kobell threatened both Ms. Sharp and Fred
Partin, her attorney in Kentucky, according to Partin's testimony
at the suppression hearing. Partin is a former assistant U.S.
attorney.
   Kobell has denied threatening Ms. Sharp.
</TEXT>
