<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 1633EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Gore     02-22 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heflin Supports Gore's Presidential Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Albert Gore Jr. won the support
Monday of Sen. Howell Heflin, a Southern conservative who said he
wanted to ``educate'' the presidential candidate to more
conservative or moderate views.
   ``He's not too far to the left, but I've got to try to bring him
to the middle a little bit,'' said Heflin, of Alabama. ``I'm going
to work on him.''
   Heflin appeared with his Senate colleague from neighboring
Tennessee at a news conference scheduled by the Gore campaign to
trumpet what they regarded as an endorsement by an influential and
respected Southern conservative lawmaker.
   Gore also used the news conference to renew attacks on
Democratic rivals Richard Gephardt, a Missouri congressman, for
inconsistency and Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis for foreign
policy inexperience.
   Heflin's remarks, however, highlighted the difference between
the Alabama senator's conservative voting record in Congress and
that of Gore. Gore has positioned himself to the right of his
rivals on defense and foreign policy issues, but has a voting
record that critics say is more liberal than his rhetoric suggests.
   Heflin said Gore has common sense and a ``down-home centralist
philosophy.''
   But he acknowledged Gore was to the left of himself when he was
asked about how they have differed on such issues as military aid
to the Nicaraguan Contras and money for President Reagan's nuclear
defense shield program.
   ``I have a hope that I can educate him a little bit, and bring
him over a little bit more,'' Heflin said.
   Gore opposes military aid to the Contras, while saying he would
support some humanitarian aid, and has opposed money for Star Wars,
although he has said he would support some research consistent with
existing treaties.
   Gore had a rating of 70 in 1986 from the liberal Americans for
Democratic Action, meaning his votes on selected issues agreed with
that group's position 70 percent of the time. He had a rating of 9
from the conservative American Conservative Union. Heflin, by
contrast, had ratings of 25 from the ADA and 65 from the ACU.
   Heflin said he regarded Gore as the most electable of the
Democratic candidates and ``strong on national defense.''
   ``Al Gore is the only Democratic candidate in this race who can
carry the South in November,'' he said.
   ``His roots run deep in Southern soil, and he has never
forgotten rural America from whence he came,'' Heflin said.
   Gore renewed the criticism of his rivals, accusing Dukakis of
suggesting it was ``fine with him if the Soviet Union established a
client state in Central America, so long as they did not put Soviet
offensive weapons in that client state.'' Dukakis has sharply
denied making such a statement.
   ``It is another example of his total lack of experience in
foreign policy,'' Gore said.
   Gore repeated criticism of Gephardt for changing positions on
issues such as abortion, the minimum wage and taxes. But Gore
acknowledged he had voted in 1984 for legislation that had
mandatory production control provisions similar to the farm
proposals Gephardt now backs and Gore denounces as disastrous for
the economy.
   ``There is a difference between changing your mind on one or two
issues over a 12-year period, and having a wholesale change in
dozens and dozens of key positions,'' he said, referring to
Gephardt.
   He also said Gephardt's ``whole approach to the electorate is in
contrast to the approach during his career in the Congress.''
   Gore also campaigned in Maryland, one of the 20 states holding
Democratic primaries or caucuses March 8, where he said stopping
the flow of illegal drugs into the country would be a top priority
for his administration. He stopped at the Coast Guard's Curtis Bay
shipyard, which the Reagan administration has scheduled to close
and which he pledged to keep open.
</TEXT>
