<DOCNO> AP880222-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 2054EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpringBreak     02-22 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spring Break,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florida Officials Gird For Spring Break; Daytona The Reigning
Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This seaside town is girding for
another successful spring break, while former mecca Fort Lauderdale
faces defections to exotic resorts and uncertainty at home over
whether it should keep encouraging college students.
   The 1960 film ``Where The Boys Are'' established Fort Lauderdale
as the nation's spring break center, but Daytona Beach has taken
the lead in Florida recently.
   Daytona Beach will play host this year to about 500,000 young
vacationers between Feb. 28 and April 1, while Fort Lauderdale may
be lucky to attract the 200,000 that came last year, officials say.
   Not all of the defectors are going to Daytona Beach.
   In recent years, the Bahamas, Florida's Panhandle, Texas' South
Padre Island and the Mexican resorts in Cancun and Acapulco have
cultivated the free-spending students.
   ``I doubt if I have 100 reservations to Fort Lauderdale, but
probably 8,000 for Cancun,'' Rob Brown, president of Travel Turf
Tours in Bethlehem, Pa. told the Wall Street Journal last week.
   ``There's some talk about how Mexico's coming into prominence,''
Florida tourism division spokesman Raul Marcucci said Monday. ``It
started happening last year.''
   But with 16,000 hotel rooms along 23 miles of beach, Daytona
Beach is expecting a strong turnout.
   ``We know that, on an average, each student visiting Daytona
Beach spends between $325 and $400 here,'' said Evelyn Fine,
executive director of the Mid-Florida Research and Business Center
of Daytona Beach Community College. ``Assuming each dollar is spent
seven times in the local economy, my guess is we're looking at
about $130 million this year.''
   MTV and National College Television networks will broadcast live
from Daytona Beach over the peak March 20 weekend.
   Two breweries are sponsoring free concerts, a soft drink maker
is sending a portable dance club to motel parking lots, and
countless other national distributors will promote everything from
suntan lotion to peppermint schnapps, including tennis shoes and
do-it-yourself pregnancy tests.
   Tour promoters say Daytona Beach has become the spring break
mecca partly because Fort Lauderdale officials, weary of the
trouble that came with the collegians, have been cracking down.
   ``In the past five years, I've seen a gradual increase to
Daytona, just because of the strictness of the enforcement in
Lauderdale,'' said Ron Good, president of Campus Marketing Inc. in
Glen Ellyn, Ill. ``You can really kind of let loose in Daytona;
it's a little bit wilder.''
   Daytona Beach police jailed 270 people when an all-night,
rock-throwing melee broke out on the strip in 1975. But Fort
Lauderdale ran into even more trouble. A crackdown two years ago
resulted in 2,500 arrests.
   Across Florida, state officials this year are urging bar owners
to obey the law on the drinking age of 21.
   The Division of Alcoholic Beverages and Tobacco is presenting
workshops in traditional spring break cities to educate bar owners
and employees about Florida's drinking laws.
   Meanwhile, ``For sale'' signs have been sprouting in Fort
Lauderdale.
   ``Last year was a devastating year for a lot of the small
hotels, and some of these mom-and-pop hotels already are being
listed for sale,'' said real estate broker Max Sebastiani.
   While city officials emphasize family vacations, some merchants
are still rooting for the college students.
   ``There's only a small group that doesn't want the college
students,'' said ``Crazy Gregg'' Newell, former bar owner and
director of the Fort Lauderdale '88 Committee promoting spring
break. ``And they don't seem to be directly involved with beach
business.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
