he couldn't be relied on to block tax increases, but Brock said the
vice president really distorted the record. He said Dole has said
he would veto any attempt to increase income tax rates, but was not
averse to closing certain loopholes that allow corporations to
reduce their tax bills.
   He said it was time to ``start pointing out how many times
George Bush has changed his position on taxes. Back in October he
said he was against any tax increase, a few days later he came out
and said well maybe. In November again he said, well I really don't
want to and then four days after that he said maybe we'll have to.''
   ``I don't think we're going to be on the defensive on this one.
I think we're going to be on the offensive,'' he said.
   Brock did not elaborate on the comments he said Bush had made.
