<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia-Violence     02-22 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Violence,0759</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>27 People Killed In Two Days Despite State of Siege Emergency
Measures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers, guerrillas and a communist
leader were killed Monday despite emergency measures to curb one of
the bloodiest spates of violence the country has seen in three
decades.
   Ten peasants were singled out at a cockfight Sunday and shot by
men wearing black hoods, official reports said. In all, 27 people
have been killed in ambushes and assassinations over two days.
   President Virgilio Barco last month ordered a state of emergency
in an attempt to halt a wave of violence that has taken the lives
of more than 1,700 people in the last year. More than 120 people
have been killed this year.
   Most of those deaths came after Barco ordered army troops to
reinforce the police and increased jail terms for many violent
crimes, especially those committed by drug traffickers, leftist
guerrillas and paid assassins.
   Leftist guerrillas on Monday released seven mayors and two
reporters kidnapped earlier this month, the radio stations RCN and
Caracol said.
   Last week the rebels freed four mayors and a reporter they had
abducted. The guerrillas warned the mayors to budget more money to
help the poor and said they planned to blow up the country's main
oil pipeline again to keep oil from being exported.
   All 11 mayors and three reporters kidnapped were from towns in
northeast Colombia and all had been held for about a week.
   The kidnappings were by the National Liberation Army, known as
the ELN, which follows the political ideology of Cuba's Fidel
Castro. The rebel group has blown up the country's main oil
pipeline 13 times since Jan. 12.
   The latest victim of an apparent right wing death squad was
Carlos Gonima, a communist leader and assistant city attorney in
the northwest city of Medellin.
   A man riding on a motorcycle Monday shot and killed Gonima and
wounded his driver as Gonima headed for work at city hall, the
national police said in a news release.
   Gonima was a member of the leftist Patriotic Union party, which
has seen more than 500 of its members killed since it was organized
by former guerrillas in 1985.
   Leftist guerrillas ambushed an army patrol Monday, killing four
soldiers, the press office for the government of the state of
Antioquia said in a news release.
   In southwest Colombia guerrillas attacked the towns of Trujillo
and Caloto on Sunday and killed seven policemen, the army's 8th
Brigade said in a communique.
   Near Vistahermosa, in a jungled area in the southeast state of
Meta, 20 men wearing black hoods and carrying submachine guns
surrounded dozens of men attending a cockfight on Sunday, the
police said.
   Ten peasants were separated from the group and and shot as they
pleaded for their lives, the policer said. The police report did
not say who was suspected in the massacre. Drug traffickers have
long dominated large areas of the vast jungles in eastern Colombia.
   The traffickers kill people they suspect of being informers or
for refusing to let traffickers use their land for growing coca
trees, the source for cocaine.
   A broadcast reporter and a mother and her 15-month-old girl were
killed Sunday when gunmen opened fire on the reporter's car as the
three traveled along a highway near the western city of Cali, the
national police there said in a news release.
   The reporter, Belisario Zambrano, of the Cali station RCN, was
the 30th reporter to be slain in Colombia in 11 years. Zambrano
reported frequently on the government's efforts against narcotics.
   An Indian running for mayor in a small town in northwest
Colombia was assassinated Sunday.
   The victim, Jose Gilberto Motato, was the leading candidate for
mayor in the town of Riosucio, the mayor there, Alberto Diaz, said
in a broadcast report over the radio chain Caracol.
   Motato was the leader of an Indian movement for land reform and
other programs to help poor people in the area in the state of
Caldas.
   A city councilman, Rafael Ballesteros, was also killed Sunday in
Chicogorodo in the northwest state of Antioquia, the Bogota daily
El Tiempo quoted national police there as saying.
   The councilman was a member of the ruling Liberal party. About
100 members of Colombia's two dominate parties, the Liberal and the
Conservative, have been killed in the last year, with the army and
police blaming guerrillas for most of the killings.
</TEXT>
