<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BronxAssault     02-22 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bronx Assault,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mental Patient Assaults Two Relatives With Hatchet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 24-year-old mental patient who was not
considered dangerous walked away from a psychiatric center and
assaulted two relatives with a hatchet Monday, critically injuring
one of them, police said.
   The patient, Donald Rattray, was arrested at his home in the
city's Bronx section after he allegedly assaulted his
brother-in-law and an uncle at 5 a.m., said Sgt. Maurice Howard, a
police spokesman.
   Rattray was not considered dangerous by officials at Bronx
Psychiatric Center, to which he had been voluntarily admitted, said
Steven Osborne, a spokesman for the State Office of Mental Health.
   The brother-in-law, James Selvin, 30, was struck twice in the
head by the hatchet. He underwent surgery for his wounds and was
listed in critical condition at Jacobi Hospital, spokesman Susan
Mueller said.
   The uncle, Onis Rattray, 46, was in stable condition at the
hospital with cuts to the left hand. Both men lived with Rattray.
   Rattray was being held on charges of first-degree assault and
criminal possession of a deadly instrument, the hatchet.
   Rattray escaped from the psychiatric center Saturday evening,
Osborne said.
   ``He got into an unlocked janitor's closet on the second floor,
broke the window and escaped by tying a bunch of sheets together
and climbing from the second floor window,'' Osborne said.
   Rattray was voluntarily admitted to the hospital Feb. 16.,
Osborne said.
   Rattray had left the center without consent Feb. 8, the
spokesman said. Police were called to the family home Feb. 13
because Rattray was behaving irrationally, Howard said. He then
voluntarily readmitted himself.
   Patients who are voluntarily admitted to the hospital may
petition to leave at any time, but the approval process takes up to
three days, Osborne said.
</TEXT>
