<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Governors 1stLd-Writethru a0684 02-22 0974</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Governors, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0684,970</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Cautions Governors Against Costly Moves On Welfare</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new graf 17, ``Rep. Tom ...'', to UPDATE with
reaction; picks up old graf 17, ``Illinois Gov. ...''; ADDS one
graf with Captain Kangaroo.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan cautioned the nation's
governors Monday against pressing for costly federal solutions to
the problems of welfare and child care.
   His remarks to the National Governors' Association were labeled
a disappointment by Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, a
Democratic presidential hopeful, who said Reagan should be backing
the governors' bipartisan welfare reform bill in the Senate.
   Reagan instead said he still strongly supports a less costly
Republican alternative that the House rejected two months ago.
   He also cautioned the governors to go slow on the issue of child
care, where both Democrats and Republicans in Congress are
proposing to expand federal support and subsidies for working
parents.
   ``Maybe it's my conservative bent, but I can't help but feel
uneasy sometimes,'' he told the governors gathered in the East Room
of the White House.
   Welfare programs have become ``a crippling poverty trap . ...
They keep the poor poor,'' Reagan said. ``Now, much of the push for
child care is designed to rectify the ills of earlier programs, and
many of these efforts are timely and good. But in this area, more
than any other, government should tread carefully.''
   Reagan said the alternative bill sponsored by House Minority
Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill., would also give states freedom to
``develop your own ideas on child care.''
   Afterwards, Dukakis told reporters that he was very disappointed.
   ``Just one word from the president, I think, would get this bill
passed and done before the election, and get it off the table as a
partisan issue and get going,'' said Dukakis.
   ``He keeps telling us stories about California, and we're trying
to explain to him that the vast majority of people on welfare these
days are single mothers with young children, and it's a combination
of real training for real jobs, combined with day care, that makes
a difference,'' said Dukakis.
   Howard Baker, Reagan's chief of staff, said Reagan would veto
the House-passed welfare reform bill, but might approve a less
expensive measure still being shaped by the Senate Finance
Committee.
   The governors are pushing Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan's bill,
which would toughen enforcement of child support, help states pay
for job training and make participation mandatory for most
unemployed adults. It would also provide some transitional Medicaid
and welfare benefits for families exiting the relief rolls for work.
   Moynihan, a New York Democrat, has 56 co-sponsors for his bill,
which would cost $2.3 billion over five years, compared to the $4.3
billion House bill, which would raise benefits and prohibit states
from denying welfare to families with both parents in the home.
   Baker said the Moynihan bill is not yet satisfactory, but he
held out the hope that Moynihan and Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., might
be able to fashion a compromise satisfactory to Reagan.
   Heinz, like Moynihan a member of the Senate Finance Committee,
has not introduced an alternative bill.
   Moynihan said in a telephone interview he heard two messages
from Reagan: ``One says that we're going to veto the House bill.
The other says we can try to work something out. I choose to
respond to the second message. There's too much at stake here. If
the president is interested in the subject, I'll be happy to work
with Sen. Heinz on anything.''
   Rep. Tom Downey, D-N.Y., who spearheaded passage of the House
bill, said in an interview, ``The time to do something about
welfare is now and the only person who seems opposed to it or
looking at the past is the president. We're not going to end child
poverty by leaving it to the states to do it. They don't have the
money.''
   Illinois Gov. James Thompson, a Republican, told reporters, ``I
think there's just a fundamental disagreement about how far to go
on welfare reform, especially with regard to cost. The governors
changed their mind, not the president.'' But despite that sticking
point, Thompson said, ``I still hold out hope that between the
administration and the Senate we'll get a bill.''
   Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton, a Democrat who is leading the
governors' push for welfare reform, emerged from the meeting and
said he felt Reagan was open to compromise.
   ``I am encouraged because basically their negotiating strategy
with everybody always is to take the hardest possible line and then
come off of it at the end,'' Clinton said.
   In the private meeting that followed Reagan's speech, Clinton
said, ``I told him we thought his bill was not a good bill and that
we were willing to make some changes in what came out of the House,
but we weren't going to get anywhere if his emissary kept saying,
`Well, we're going to veto whatever passes that we don't like.''
   Clinton said Reagan replied that ``he heard us ... and was
willing to work with us, so I think that's good.''
   Alabama Gov. Guy Hunt, a Republican, said he shared Reagan's
misgivings about the House-passed welfare bill. He said it ``might
really compound the problem'' by increasing federal funding without
giving states more control over welfare rules.
   What the states need is flexibility to allow them to ``gradually
remove (people) from welfare'' instead of terminating their
benefits as soon as they get a job, Hunt said.
   Later, the governors' committee on human resources heard
television's Captain Kangaroo, Bob Keeshan, plead for corporations
to start providing quality day care. ``I'm almost ashamed at times
to be an American,'' the children's performer and advocate said.
``We are half a century behind in addressing day care. We are going
to pay an enormous price a quarter-century down the line.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
