<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 2149EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ArmsTreaty     02-22 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arms Treaty,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nunn: INF Pact Faces Thorough Senate Review Before Ratification
Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assocaited Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Sam Nunn said Monday the new U.S.-Soviet
nuclear arms control treaty won't be ratified until after his Armed
Services Committee the panel finishes its line-by-line examination
of the pact.
   That laborious process began Monday after the State Department
sent the Senate 31 volumes of documents involved in the long
negotiations which led to the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces
(INF) pact.
   ``It is very regrettable that we have to go through this,'' said
the Georgia Democrat, who emerged victorious in a fight with the
Reagan administration over the legal meaning of treaties.
   Nunn, chairman of the armed services panel, said he didn't know
how long it would take the committee to finish its work.
   The panel is one of three Senate committees considering the
treaty, which was signed in December by President Reagan and Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev. Ratification by the full Senate, which
requires a two-thirds vote, is expected later.
   The INF fight was based on a previous dispute between the
Democratic-controlled Congress and the Reagan administration over
the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty and Reagan's Star Wars
anti-missile program.
   A number of Star Wars tests would be banned unless the United
States moved from the current ``narrow'' interpretation of the ABM
treaty to a ``broad'' view.
   The Reagan administration had asserted it wasn't bound by what
previous administrations told Congress about the meaning of the ABM
pact, a view the White House at one point tried to push in the
Senate debate over the INF treaty.
   Nunn threatened to block the treaty until Secretary of State
George P. Shultz promised last month that administration comments
on the treaty were ``authoritative,'' meaning that future
administrations couldn't try to change how the treaty is viewed.
   Since Shultz's promise was delivered, ``we can now proceed,
confident that the treaty the committee is being asked to approve
is the same treaty'' the administration believes it negotiated,
Nunn told Maynard Glitman, one of the chief negotiators for the
U.S. team which worked out the treaty, during a committee meeting
Monday.
   The committee has sent the State Department a list of 135
questions about possible ambiguities in the treaty, Nunn said. Most
are technical questions but some involve queries about possible
interpretation of the pact, which bans missiles with ranges from
300 miles to 3,400 miles.
   Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, told Glitman, ``I'm sorry there was a
reinterpretation of the ABM treaty that made this necessary.''
   ``It's sad we have to go through the exercise we're going
through here,'' said Sen. James Exon, D-Neb.
   While the Armed Services panel was going through a detailed
scrutiny of the pact, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee
continued taking testimony from public witnesses.
   Dr. Edward Teller, the physicist who is considered the father of
both the hydrogen bomb and Reagan's Star Wars program, told the
foreign relations panel he thought the fights over the meanings of
treaties were ``senseless debates.''
   Teller said he supports the treaty, although he is deeply
distrustful of the Soviet Union.
   Speaking of the treaty, he said, ``my personal approach is
careful, doubtful, yet positive,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
