<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PeaceCorps     02-22 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peace Corps,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peace Corps To Get Graduate School Volunteers Under New Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two more universities on Monday announced plans
to help boost the number and expertise of Peace Corps volunteers
with programs giving them graduate-level training or course credits
for their service.
   Starting with about 10 students in the 1988-89 school year, the
University of Alabama at Birmingham will offer candidates for
master's degrees in public health a chance to ``get their training
before they do their (Peace Corps) service,'' said Dr. Juan M.
Navia, chairman of the school's public health department.
   ``Some of our finest (public health graduate) students are the
ones who have served in other countries as Peace Corps volunteers.
And many of them have the frustration: `If only I had know this
then,''' Navia said at a news conference at the Carter Presidential
Center. ``We're going to reverse the order.''
   Peace Corps Director Loret Miller Ruppe also signed an agreement
Monday with the University of South Carolina in Columbia, which
will offer internship credit to special education graduate students
who do a tour of duty in the Peace Corps.
   Mrs. Ruppe said the two programs are similar to one announced
earlier for public health master's degree candidates at Boston
University, also starting next fall. And all three are modeled
after a program for master's degree students in public policy at
Rutgers University, which will send its first group of volunteers
to the Peace Corps this spring.
   ``These programs will help us ensure a steady flow of volunteers
with the skills we need in developing countries,'' Mrs. Ruppe said.
   She said the Corps hopes to double the number of volunteers by
1992 and to increase dramatically the number of minority
volunteers, who now number about 110 out of 5,200.
   The Peace Corps is starting a number of innovative programs to
help meet that goal.
   Harvard University School of Dentistry has agreed to send some
of its fifth-year dental students to the Peace Corps for six-month
stints, in an experiment with shorter tours of duty than the usual
two years, she said.
   Under another new program, teachers in Virginia can take
sabbaticals to spend a year in Peace Corps-sponsored teacher
training centers around the world, she said.
   In Northfield, Vt., some military cadets at Norwich University
are participating in a Peace Corps alternative to campus ROTC and
eventual military service. A bill pending in Congress would
authorize $5 million a year for five years to enable the Peace
Corps to test the ROTC-alternative program elsewhere.
   Both the Alabama and South Carolina programs will target
minorities.
   Also Monday, Helene Robertson of Birmingham, Ala., a 77-year-old
former Peace Corps volunteer to Botswana, received the Lillian
Carter Award for Enduring Voluntary Commitment.
   The award is named after former President Jimmy Carter's mother,
who was in her 60s when she served in the Peace Corps in India.
   Receiving ``Leader for Peace'' awards were Lillian Lewis, wife
of Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., an original Peace Corps volunteer in
1961 and associate director of the Institute for International
Affairs and Development at Atlanta University; Atlanta Mayor Andrew
Young for a recruiting public service announcement he did for the
Peace Corps; and The Coca-Cola Co. for its financing of a Peace
Corps program to re-establish contact with former volunteers.
</TEXT>
