<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Fuller     02-22 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Fuller,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fundamentalist Preacher Otis Fuller Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. David Otis Fuller, a
fundamentalist preacher who helped found a children's radio
ministry and the Grand Rapids Baptist College and Seminary, has
died at age 84.
   Fuller died Sunday at Blodgett Memorial Medical Center, hours
after complaining of faintess during a prayer meeting at Wealthy
Park Baptist Church, where he was pastor until his 1974 retirement.
   Born in Brooklyn, N.Y., Fuller founded the Children's Bible
Hour, a Grand Rapids-based Christian radio program now broadcast by
660 radio stations worldwide.
   ``He was one of the leading fundamentalist preachers in the
country,'' said the Rev. Robert Gage, minister of Wealthy Park
Baptist Church. ``It is going to leave a big void for us.''
   Funeral services are scheduled for Wednesday at Wealthy Park.
   Fuller is survived by his wife, Virginia; a daughter, Mrs.
Beverly Berman of West Hartford, Conn.; sons Alan of Golden, Colo.,
and David of Tuckahoe, N.Y.; a sister, Muriel Fuller of New York
City; 10 grandchildren and one great-grandson.
</TEXT>
