<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Cyprus 1stLd-Writethru a0671 02-22 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cyprus, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0671,0767</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greek and Turkish Cypriot Leaders Spar on Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 6th graf ``Vassiliou, a...'' to UPDATE
with Reagan congratulatory message and planned response. Pickup 7th
graf pvs ``Denktash proposed...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICK LUDINGTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cyprus' Greek and Turkish leaders sparred
Monday only a day after elections, with the Turkish head proposing
talks in neutral territory and the Greek president-elect insisting
they be held on his own turf.
   The dispute over a matter of protocol disappointed some who had
for a new start in talks to reunify Cyprus in a federation.
   The sparring began when Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash
invited Greek Cypriot president-elect George Vassiliou to informal
talks on the future of the island, to be held in a neutral area.
Vassiliou countered with an invitation to Denktash ``to come and
see me at the presidential palace.''
   ``I am the elected president of the Cyprus Republic and in that
capacity I would be most happy to welcome Mr. Denktash as the
leader of the Turkish Cypriot community,'' Vassiliou said in a
radio interview.
   Denktash is president of the breakaway Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus, which was proclaimed in 1983 and is
internationally recognized only by Turkey. He does not recognize
Vassiliou, who will be sworn in next Sunday, as president of all
Cyprus.
   Vassiliou, a millionaire businessman backed by the Communist
Party, defeated veteran right-wing politician Glafcos Clerides in
general elections Sunday. Only Greek Cypriots voted.
   An official announcement said President Reagan sent Vassiliou a
message of congratulations, expressing the wish to continue
relations with Cyprus.
   ``I look forward, through you, to continuing the friendly
relations between our two countries, a relationship which has been
characterized by a special warmth and a constant effort to build
mutual respect and understanding,'' Reagan's message said.
   ``I know that you have the determination to make the effort to
bring about the lasting peace which has so long escaped the people
of Cyprus,'' the message said.
   Vassiliou said he will thank Reagan in a message expressing hope
the United States will more actively to persuade Turkey to withdraw
its troops.
   Denktash proposed in his invitation to Vassiliou that the talks
be held at the Ledra Palace Hotel, a U.N. headquarters on the Green
Line dividing Turkish and Greek Cypriots. He said the meeting
``would be between the leaders of the two politically equal parties
or between the presidents of two equal political entities.''
   Vassiliou had said during his campaign that he was willing to
meet with the Turkish Cypriots without preconditions.
   But his counter-offer to meet Denktash at the presidential
palace in the Greek Cypriot-controlled zone, citing his own role as
president of Cyprus and Denktash only as leader of the Turkish
Cypriot community, was certain to be rebuffed.
   In the interview with the British Broadcasting Corp., Vassiliou
indicated no new flexibility in the conflict between Greek and
Turkish Cypriots.
   He accused Turkey of building up its military presence in the
Turkish Cypriot zone in northern Cyprus since the 1974 invasion
which partitioned the island. The invasion followed a coup by Greek
Cypriot extremists aimed at uniting the entire island with Greece.
   ``The realities of Cyprus are that in these years, Turkey,
instead of recucing its military presence here, has been building
it up in every way,'' he said.
   He also accused Turkey of bringing in 40,000 to 50,000 Turkish
settlers to beef up the Turkish Cypriot minority, which numbered
120,000 at the time of the invasion. The Greek Cypriot population
is more than 500,000.
   After election results were announced early Monday, Vassiliou
said he would work for the withdrawal of Turkish troops and
settlers, but woud try to achieve a spirit of rapprochement with
the Turkish Cypriots.
   Greek-Turkish negotiations have been stalled since President
Spyros Kyprianou, who lost a bid for a third term in the first
round of elections Feb. 14, rejected proposals for a two-zone
federation proposed by the United Nations in 1986.
   The proposals had been accepted by Denktash, who now insists
upon them as the basis for restarting talks.
   Kyprianou had insisted that before any talks began on a
federation, all Turkish troops must withdraw and the Turks must
allow Greek Cypriot refugees, who fled after the 1974 invasion, to
return to their homes in the north.
   The U.N. proposals suggested that talks on troop withdrawal and
the ``right of return'' would be discussed by committees
simultaneously with talks on the nature of the federation.
</TEXT>
