<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Shultz-CoopDining     02-22 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Coop Dining,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dinner at a Cooperative Gives Shultz a Taste of Soviet Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Shultz, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz tasted the
fruits of Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms first-hand Monday as he
hosted a candlelit dinner at a cooperative restaurant that was once
a money-losing bar.
   The red-brick Skazka (``Fairy Tale'') restaurant off
southeastern Moscow's Taganka Square would have been illegal before
last year's decision by Soviet authorities to loosen laws governing
individual labor and cooperative ownership.
   ``As soon as we heard they were authorizing cooperatives, we
decided to start one,'' said Sergei V. Kutuzov, the head of the
nine-member collective that runs the Skazka.
   The restaurant, which can seat 34 customers in its upstairs
dining room, opened April 1 last year. Its hearty Russian fare
swiftly made it so popular with Muscovites and foreign residents
that profits soared to as much as $23,300 a month, Kutuzov said.
   Skazka's friendly waitresses and prompt service are in stark
contrast to the situation that prevails at most of Moscow's
state-owned restaurants, where customers sometimes wait for hours
before being served.
   Cooperatives are also more expensive than state-run restaurants,
which has led some Soviets to oppose them as socially unjust.
   The dinner menu offered Shultz cost between $25 and $33 per
person, Kutuzov said, compared to an average of $3 to $8 for an
evening meal in a government-owned restaurant.
   A table piled with sturgeon in aspic, pickled vegetables inside
a pumpkin, bottles of mineral water and grapes was set out for
Shultz, who had finished two days of talks in Moscow with top
Soviet officials, including Gorbachev, the Communist Party leader.
   Skazka's chefs also prepared homemade noodle soup with
mushrooms, a cabbage soup called ``shchi,'' stuffed pork cutlets,
dumplings with mushroom and chicken and small Russian pancakes.
   Shultz, who was accompanied by his wife Helena and U.S.
Ambassador Jack Matlock, met in the dining room with some of the
Soviet Union's top cultural figures and intellectuals, including
cinematographer Elem Klimov, playwright Mikhail Shatrov, economist
Nikolai Shmelov and writer Vladimir Soloukhin.
   Reporters briefly allowed into the wood-paneled room before
Shultz arrived spotted one apparent concession to the VIP guests _
bottles of Georgian and French wines set out on a table.
   As a cooperative, the Skazka normally does not have the right to
serve alcohol.
   Gorbachev said in mid-January that 13,000 co-ops had been
established in the Soviet Union. He said more than 300,000 people
were working for themselves within guidelines set by the government
to encourage better services and goods than those provided by the
state-run sector.
   The venture has been a clear success for the nine people who put
up a total of $5,000 to launch the Skazka. Last month Kutuzov,
chairman of the Skazka cooperative, took home $1,050, more than
three times the average Soviet wage of $330.
   The building that now contains the restaurant was once a bar
favored by ``Lyubers,'' body-building enthusiasts from a Moscow
suburb that some press reports have said prey on long-haired Soviet
youths who like Western rock music.
   Either because of its tough clientele, or because the
health-conscious Lyubers did not drink enough alcohol, the bar lost
money, Kutuzov said.
   Now its clientele has radically changed, with foreigners making
up as much as 90 percent of the dinner customers on a given
evening, Kutuzov said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
