<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush     02-22 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Stumps in South Carolina, Says Dole Has Raised Stakes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MYRTLE BEACH, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush stumped in
South Carolina Monday, saying Sen. Strom Thurmond's endorsement of
rival Bob Dole raises the stakes in the state's March 5 Republican
presidential primary.
   ``I have great respect for Sen. Thurmond,'' said Bush. ``It's
going to make this an even more dramatic ground of confrontation.''
   The South Carolina GOP primary comes just three days before the
Super Tuesday round of contests in 20 other, mostly Southern
states. The four Republican candidates have said their showing in
South Carolina will be crucial leading into Super Tuesday.
   During a three-hour visit to Myrtle Beach, Bush spoke briefly at
a civic club luncheon, addressed about 1,200 students and visitors
at Myrtle Beach High School and then held a series of meetings with
reporters.
   Gov. Carroll Campbell, the chairman of Bush's Southern campaign
accompanied the vice president and said the Dole campaign has
``created a do-or-die situation'' by pushing for the South Carolina
senator's endorsement.
   ``Everybody loves Strom Thurmond, I love Strom Thurmond. I think
they've raised the stakes. They've said, `Now we've got him; now
we're going to win,''' Campbell said.
   Bush called South Carolina ``a key state'' and campaign aides
said he will likely spend at least four more days campaigning in
the state prior to March 5.
   Bush, with reporters in tow, stopped briefly at a luncheon
meeting of the Myrtle Beach Rotary Club at a local seafood
restaurant.
   ``I think I'm going to win in South Carolina,'' Bush said. ``If
I win in South Carolina, I will be the next president of the United
States.''
   Bush flew to the state from Texas, before heading on for
additional stops in Tennessee and Missouri.
   The visit came on the eve of caucuses in Minnesota and a primary
in South Dakota, but Bush said, ``You've got limited resources and
we've allocated to Super Tuesday and South Carolina.''
</TEXT>
