<DOCNO> AP880222-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 2218EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NoriegaWitness     02-22 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Noriega Witness,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trafficker Who Told Of Payoffs To Noriega To Be Sentenced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A principal witness in the drug conspiracy
case against Panamanian Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega faces up to 20
years in prison when sentenced this week for his part in the ring
which smuggled 500,000 pounds of marijuana and 1{ tons of cocaine
into the United States.
   But Steven Michael Kalish, 35, expects leniency for his
testimony against Noriega, which included Kalish's report that he
made made $900,000 in payoffs to the Panamanian strongman.
   ``Obviously, he's hoping he won't have to spend too much time in
jail,'' said Dick DeGuerin, Kalish's friend and defense attorney in
Houston.
   Kalish pleaded guilty a year ago during the trial of his
partner, Leigh Bruce Ritch, and has since emerged as a principal
witness against Noriega in the Tampa conspiracy case. Noriega also
faces separate racketeering and drug charges in Miami.
   Ritch, 34, is serving a sentence of 30 years in prison.
   In the Tampa case, Kalish testified he gave Noriega cash and
jewelry in exchange for Panamanian banking services and military
protection.
   Kalish told a U.S. Senate panel last month that he became
attracted to Panama in 1983 because of its international banking
facilities. He flew there with $2.4 million in cash and met with
Cesar Rodriguez Contreras at the Bank of Boston Building in Panama
City, Kalish said.
   Rodriguez, who was slain in Colombia in 1986, ``offered me an
entire package of corporate banking and investment services and
even armored car delivery from the airport,'' Kalish testified.
   Rodriguez introduced Kalish to Noriega at the general's home,
Kalish told the committee. At their first meeting, Kalish delivered
a suitcase with $300,000 cash, he said, and discussed his
investment plans in Panama. For the next 10 months, Kalish told the
panel, he used Panama as his base, living in a three-story
Spanish-style house around the corner from Noriega's.
   In November 1983, Kalish bought the Panamanian Defense Forces a
Boeing 727 jet to deliver shipments of drug profits from the United
States to Panama. In exchange for a Bell 212 helicopter Kalish
bought for the defense forces, according to the charges, Noriega
arranged for an irrevocable $2 million line of credit for Kalish
from a Panamanian bank.
   Noriega also provided Kalish with a diplomatic passport and
agreed to let Ritch and Kalish use Panamanian banks to launder more
than $100 million in anticipated profits from a million-pound
marijuana smuggling venture that Kalish was organizing in Colombia
in early 1984, according to the federal charges.
   Kalish began his career in drug trafficking at an early age, his
friends say.
   The son of a mid-level Gulf Oil Corp. executive who died in
1980, Kalish was born in Texas and grew up in Bellaire, a
comfortable suburb of Houston. DeGuerin said Kalish was already
selling marijuana when he dropped out of the 11th grade.
   ``I don't believe he ever had a straight job,'' said DeGuerin.
   By age 27, Kalish had been indicted twice in Houston for trying
to import 140,000 pounds of marijuana in two loads nine days apart
in December 1979. The second seizure _ 100,000 pounds _ was then
the largest ever in Texas. Kalish eventually fled, assumed a new
identity and in 1983 settled in Tampa, where he worked with Ritch,
says Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert Kennedy in Tampa.
   Kalish and Ritch set up a smuggling organization and a
sophisticated nationwide distribution network that made more than
$200 million in four years.
   The Kalish-Ritch organization began to fall apart when the FBI
arrested Kalish on July 26, 1984, as he was boarding a chartered
Lear jet under an assumed name at Tampa International Airport.
</TEXT>
