<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Nofziger     02-22 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nofziger,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nofziger Attorneys Try To Overturn Guilty Verdict, Get New Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lyn Nofziger's defense attorneys filed motions
Monday to set aside the former presidential aide's illegal lobbying
convictions on the grounds that prosecutors failed to prove he
violated the law.
   The defense also filed a motion for a new trial, contending that
U.S. District Judge Thomas A. Flannery erroneously instructed
jurors about determining whether the issues Nofziger lobbied about
were of ``direct and substantial'' interest to the White House.
   Nofziger, 63, was convicted Feb. 11 of three counts of illegally
lobbying former White House colleagues on behalf of Wedtech Corp.,
a maritime engineers union and the manufacturer of the Air Force
A-10 anti-tank plane.
   The former White House political director faces a potential
two-year prison term and a $10,000 fine for each of the three
convictions. He is scheduled to be sentenced March 25.
   In its motions in U.S. District Court, the defense repeated
contentions made throughout the four-week trial that the
prosecution team headed by independent counsel James C. McKay
failed to prove that the issues Nofziger raised with former
colleagues were ``particular matters'' of ``direct and substantial
interest'' to the White House.
   ``The gross insufficiency of the evidence mandates that the
guilty verdict ... against Mr. Nofziger b set aside and that a
judgment of acquittal be entered,'' defense lawyer Robert Plotkin
and E. Lawrence Barcella said in their pleadings.
   In asking for a new trial, the defense said the definition of
``direct and substantial interest'' that Flannery gave the jury
during final instructions ``clearly encompassed interest well
beyond the scope of the statute.''
   This instruction allowed jurors to confuse the ``personal
interest of certain representatives of the White House'' with
``direct and substantial'' interest, the defense said.
   For instance, references in testimony to Pier F. Talenti, a
volunteer on Nofziger's White House staff who visited Wedtech
Corp.'s plant, might be the only basis for the jury to conclude the
White House had an interest in Wedtech's bid for a military engine
contract, the defense said.
   Although he was not called as a witness, Talenti was described
by a former Wedtech executive as expressing interest in the
company's bid for a contract to build small engines for the Army in
1981.
   An Army procurement official also testified that Talenti urged
consideration of Wedtech's bid that year.
   The defense said Flannery's ``internally inconsistent and
confusing'' instruction ``failed adequately to explain the
comparative and relative importance of a matter to the White House,
and it did not instruct the jury to place that interest in its
proper context.''
   Nofziger, who left the White House in early 1982, was convicted,
among other things, for sending an April 8, 1982, memo to
then-presidential counselor Edwin Meese III urging support for
Wedtech's efforts to persuade reluctant Army officials to award the
$32 million contract.
   ``The very purpose of the communication to Mr. Meese was to
create and stimulate interest, a contact that is not prohibited''
by the law, the defense said.
   Meese, now attorney general, testified at the trial that he
couldn't recall receiving Nofziger's note, which suggested he
enlist the support of Reagan and other top administration officials.
</TEXT>
