<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FireSickout     02-22 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fire Sickout,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters Continue to Call in Sick</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All firefighters scheduled to work
Monday night's shift joined scores of other colleagues in calling
in sick, leaving Providence's fire protection to 87 firefighters
who have been on duty around the clock since Friday.
   Meanwhile, a Superior Court judge delayed ruling on the city's
request for contempt citations against 110 firefighters who called
in sick over the weekend in defiance of a back-to-work order.
   Judge Americo Campanella gave union president Leo J. Miller
until 10 a.m. Tuesday to inform all 450 members of the union that
they must to return to work under the temporary restraining order
issued Saturday by another judge.
   Miller was also ordered to furnish a list of all firefighters
who had called in sick over the weekend and outline the nature of
their illness or the illness of family members they said they were
staying home to care for.
   City officials went from home to home Monday leaving notices for
firefighters of the contempt hearing. Campanella indicated his
decision to put off ruling on the matter hinged on the relatively
low number of firefighters contacted either by the city or Miller.
   The union represents 450 of the city's total uniformed force of
479. Campanella indicated his decision to put off ruling on the
matter hinged on the relatively low number of firefighters
contacted either by the city or Miller.
   Miller, a fire captain, denies the union orchestrated any
sickout.
   If found to be a job action as Moise and city officials assert,
the sickout would be illegal under Rhode Island law.
   The dispute apparently concerns language in a contract ratified
by firefighters in December that the city has yet to sign.
   Miller said the city is trying to renege on a provision that
calls for an officer to be placed in charge of each rescue unit.
Union members also complain that promises to replacement worn-out
or damaged equipment like boots, helmets and firecoats have not
been fulfilled.
   All but one of the 51 firefighters scheduled to report for work
at 8 a.m. Saturday called in sick Friday, said Fire Chief Michael
F. Moise.
   An additional 60 called in sick for the shift that was supposed
to begin at 6 a.m. Sunday, Moise said.
   Assistant Fire Chief Gilbert H. McLaughlin Jr. told Campanella
that all of the firefighters scheduled to report at 6 p.m. Monday
had called in sick.
   ``I have nobody coming in,'' McLaughlin testified.
   The union represents 450 of the city's total uniformed force of
479. The firefighters, divided into four platoons, work two 10-hour
days and two 12-hour days, then are off four days.
   Moise said the 87 firefighters in the platoon that has been kept
on duty since Friday evening will stay on the job until the issue
is resolved.
   The chief testified the average absentee level is seven to eight
firefighters for any particular shift.
   Miller agreed the number of sick firefighters was ``unusually
high.''
   Most of the people he contacted after the restraining order was
issued said either they or someone in their family had a 24-hour
virus, Miller said.
   Miller said he called in sick because his mother, who has heart
trouble, also had the flu.
   Ragosta tried to show the sickout presented a danger to the
public health and safety. Moise said he was becoming concerned that
fatigue among firefighters on the job since Friday might affect
their ability to operate sophisticated equipment and their response
time in a crisis.
   He said the sickout was costing $20,000 a day in overtime and
related expenses.
</TEXT>
