<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     02-22 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ron Sexton's reward for winning a school
contest was nothing to snort at. Then again, it probably didn't
make him squeal with delight.
   Sexton, a history teacher and wrestling coach at Wilmington High
School, came in first in a school project to raise money for
Children's Hospital in Columbus. His payoff _ he had to kiss a pig.
   He put his mouth where the smart money was, planting a kiss on
the snout of a pig during a pep rally Friday while the students and
faculty watched.
   Sexton won a contest in which students and teachers put money in
gallon milk jugs as their way of choosing a sow smoocher. There
were 45 teachers up for votes, which cost 25 cents to cast, said
home economics teacher Bonnie Hansen.
   The contest, dubbed ``Squeal of Fortune,'' raised nearly $250.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUBURN, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Auburn residents better not plan to serve
pie this weekend _ not with a horde of Curly, Larry and Moe fans
headed their way.
   Three Stooges aficionados from throughout the nation are
expected to converge on this central Maine city to share
recollections of the zany antics that entertained generations of
moviegoers and television viewers.
   The two-day convention, which begins Saturday, will feature
about 30 dealers in Stooges memorabilia, imitators of the threesome
and, of course, a pie fight.
   ``They kind of created the pie fight,'' said Ron Eugley, the
convention organizer. ``In about a quarter of their shorts, there's
somebody getting a pie in the face.''
   Eugley, a 36-year-old salesman from Auburn, said the convention
has been promoted in the national magazine published by the Three
Stooges fan club and is expected to draw more than 700 fans.
   The convention will be addressed by telephone by Emil Sitka, a
supporting actor for the Stooges who is writing a book about the
late comics.
   Stooges movies will be shown throughout the convention, Eugley
said, including some never seen by the general public.
   ``Curly was married four times _ he had quite the thing for
women _ and we'll have some films of his weddings,'' Eugley said.
He said convention-goers will also see films of Moe Howard
entertaining at a backyard barbecue.
   Proceeds from the convention will go to the American Cancer
Society, in part because Howard died of the disease.
</TEXT>
