<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Near-Miss     02-22 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Near-Miss,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Near Collision Between Helicopter And Jet Fighter: Third in
Two Weeks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An oil rig helicopter and a Phantom jet fighter
came within a half-mile of colliding over the North Sea on Monday,
according to the helicopter firm. It was the third reported
near-miss in two weeks in Britain's crowded skies.
   The earlier incidents involved jetliners carrying hundreds of
passengers and prompted calls for an inquiry into growing air
congestion before the summer travel season begins. The government
on Monday accused air traffic controllers of fomenting ``public
hysteria'' and said there was no cause for alarm.
   Bristow Helicopters said its Puma craft carrying 11 passengers
and two crew members from an oil rig 165 miles northeast of
Aberdeen climbed sharply as it neared the Scottish city after air
traffic controllers warned that it was on a collision course with a
Royal Air Force jet.
   Bristow said its helicopter moved up from an altitude of 2,000
feet and the Phantom passed below. Both aircraft landed safely and
no one was reported injured.
   A Bristow spokesman said the helicopter pilot filed an ``air
miss'' report with the Civil Aviation Authority, or CAA.
   Earlier Monday, Transport Secretary Paul Channon promised an
investigation into an incident Sunday involving a British
Caledonian BA 1-11 and a Pan American Boeing 727.
   Channon told the House of Commons the jetliners came within
2,000 yards while flying over southern England but he said they
were not in danger of colliding.
   He said the number of near-misses had declined sharply in the
last 10 years. ``We musn't be complacent, neither must we
overreact,'' he said.
   In the previous incident this month, a British Airways Lockheed
L1011 and a Balkan Bulgarian Tu 54 with a total of 543 people
aboard narrowly avoided colliding. The CAA called that an
``exceptionally serious'' case and Channon said the authority took
the unusual step of asking the Department of Transport to make an
independent investigation.
   According to the CAA, the number of near-misses per 100,000
flying hours in British air space decreased from 6.2 in 1980 to 2.8
in 1986.
   It said there were 12 incidents involving serious risk last
year, unchanged from 1986.
   Chris Stock, president of Britain's largest air traffic
controllers' union, said the control system is nearly overloaded.
   ``The system is working at full blast,'' said Stock, head of the
1,500-member Guild of Air Traffic Controllers. ``If a mistake is
made then there is very little room to maneuver.''
   He said safety should improve when a new computer system is
inaugurated in 1990 and a new control center in 1995. The guild has
demanded increased manpower in the meantime, saying five job
vacancies at the main control center in West Drayton have not been
filled since September.
   The CAA on Monday claimed the controllers were promoting public
alarm to gain leverage in negotiations over working conditions,
including the number of controllers on duty at peak times.
   ``The controllers are putting pressure on the CAA by harping on
the subject of safety,'' said the authority spokesman who was not
identified in line with government policy. ``Anonymous controllers
are constantly feeding information engendering alarm and concern.''
</TEXT>
