<1ST_LINE>u w AM-WebbResigns 3rdLd-Writethru a0779 02-22 0993</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Webb Resigns, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0779,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Secretary Leaves with a Blast at His Boss</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, bgng: ``An administration ...'' to UPDATE
with Ball's likely nomination and Webb's resignation to be accepted
at White House Tuesday.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navy Secretary James H. Webb abruptly resigned
Monday, accusing Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci of abandoning
the Reagan Administration's goal of a 600-ship Navy and of
demonstrating a lack of leadership and vision.
   ``This building needs to be led,'' Webb said in telling
reporters of his decision. ``It needs leadership. It needs some
vision. I'm saying that if I had a piece of advice to give to
Secretary Carlucci, it would be to spend a lot more time with the
top leaders in this building.
   ``He's been spending a lot of time with the State Department and
a lot of time on the Hill. I think they (Pentagon leaders) need to
feel his vision and to understand what he believes in.''
   Webb, 42, a highly decorated Marine veteran of Vietnam combat
and the author of the best-selling Vietnam war novel, ``Fields of
Fire,'' left after only 10 months in his Pentagon position.
   He told President Reagan in his resignation letter that the
president could have realized his cherished goal of building a
600-ship fleet, were it not for Carlucci.
   An administration official who asked not to be identified said
Carlucci wants to recommend that William L. Ball III, assistant to
the president for legislative affairs, be nominated to replace
Webb. The source said the White House probably would announce
Ball's nomination on Tuesday, at the same time it announces formal
acceptance of Webb's resignation.
   Talking to reporters, Webb accused Carlucci of ordering him to
keep quiet about internal budget fighting, saying the defense chief
had written him a note saying he should deny news stories reporting
it was the Defense Department _ and not the Navy _ proposing to
mothball ships.
   ``Now, I'm not going to deny the truth,'' Webb said.
   Carlucci declined to respond to the criticism, issuing a written
statement saying only that he had learned of Webb's resignation
decision ``with regret.''
   The Pentagon added in a separate statement, however, that if
Webb had decided he could not ``defend the department's decisions''
on the budget, then ``under the circumstances, he has done the
honorable thing.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said: ``Secretary
Carlucci is having to make some very difficult adjustments in the
Pentagon to accommodate budgetary reductions. Secretary Webb
indicates he is unable to operate under these constraints, but I
know the president feels he has given very valuable service to the
country ...''
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the Senate Armed
Services subcommittee that oversees the Navy budget, said in a
statement: ``I'm sorry to see Jim Webb go. In his brief stint, he
impressed the Armed Services Committee as an able secretary.''
   ``Although I am not endorsing his views, his resignation has
obviously launched an important new stage of the debate about
Pentagon priorities and the size and type of Navy we need.''
   Three times, Webb said, the Navy developed a plan for cutting
its fiscal 1989 budget in such a way that the goal of expanding the
fleet to 600 ships could still be reached. And each time, he said,
the Navy's advice was ``ignored'' by Carlucci.
   ``I can only conclude that the decision to reduce the level of
our fleet to a point that it may never reach the 600-ship goal was
motivated by other than military and strategic reasoning,'' Webb
wrote Reagan.
   Webb and others have argued that 600 ships were the minimum
needed for the Navy to meet its worldwide commitments.
   Since his recommendations ``were rejected by your secretary of
defense, I am unable to support him personally or to defend this
amended budget during budget deliberations (in Congress),'' Webb
said.
   ``Consequently, I find it necessary to resign from my position
as ecretary of the Navy.''
   Webb's decision to step down surprised Navy and Pentagon
officials alike.
   He assumed the post only last April, seven months before
Carlucci succeeded Caspar W. Weinberger.
   The Navy, like all the services, was ordered in early December
to slash its fiscal 1989 budget proposal to comply with a new
deficit-reduction plan. Ultimately, Webb said, the Navy ended up
being told to cut $12.3 billion from its original spending plan.
   As finally approved by Carlucci, the Navy has told Congress it
wants $96.4 billion in budget authority and intends to mothball 16
Navy frigates, Webb said.
   The Pentagon said the mothballing would leave the Navy with 580
ships by the end of fiscal 1989 and that it can still build to 600
by fiscal 1992.
   Webb asserted, however, the mothballing is unnecessary and the
Navy would never reach 600 ships.
   ``One of the sad things about this is that this is one of the
few goals of the Reagan administration that was really obtainable,
at pretty low cost,'' Webb said.
   The Navy could have transferred those 16 frigates to the Naval
Reserve ``for well under $100 million'' rather than place them in
mothballs, preserving them as ``deployable'' warships ready for an
emergency, he declared.
   Webb declined to speculate on why Carlucci might have rejected
such options.
   But in another broadside at the new defense secretary, Webb
complained that once Carlucci arrived, ``the number of people who
are participating in the decisions (became) smaller.''
   Webb, one of the youngest men to ever become Navy secretary, is
a Naval Academy graduate.
   He came to the Pentagon in 1984 under Weinberger, assuming the
post of assistant defense secretary for reserve affairs. He had
resigned and was preparing to leave government service in early
1987 when the president asked him to replace John F. Lehman, the
first Navy secretary of the Reagan administration.
   Webb said Monday he intended to return to his work as a novelist
and possibly, journalism as well.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
