<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TVGunfire     02-22 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TV Gunfire,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sniper Fire Again Hits Christian Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police increased patrols Monday at a
fundamentalist Christian television station that has been hit by
sporadic sniper fire twice in a week.
   No one was injured in the latest incident, on Sunday morning,
said WMPV-TV owner Ed Bowlds.
   ``We just think it's some kind of weirdo,'' Bowlds said. ``He's
not trying to hit anybody. That's obvious. It may be somebody
wanting publicity.''
   Glenda McLeod, a producer at the station, said one employee was
inside the building Sunday, but the shots were fired into the
eaves. She also said glass was broken in the front door, but not by
gunfire. She said she thought someone had attempted to break into
the building.
   Police placed the building under surveillance after bullets hit
it Wednesday. There have been no arrests in either incident.
   Police Capt. Tommy Hart said two additional patrol cars were
assigned to the area. He said the sniper could have been encouraged
by the station's on-the-air comment that officers seemed to take a
long time to arrive after the first shooting incident.
   Ms. McLeod said a caller Friday threatened the lives of four
employees, including herself and Bowlds.
   ``We just don't know what this crazy person is up to,'' the
producer said.
   Bowlds has reported other threatening calls since the station
opened three years ago.
</TEXT>
