<DOCNO> AP880222-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 2230EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Haiti     02-22 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Denies Col. Paul Involved In Drug Running</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PIERRE-YVES GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ The army chief of staff denied
Monday night that the commander of Haiti's most repressive and
powerful batallion is involved in cocaine trafficking.
   ``There has been no complaint or judicial file received
implicating Col. Jean-Claude Paul, who has been singled out by the
foreign press'' for denigration, read the communique signed by Gen.
Carl Nicolas and broadcast by the state-run Radio Nationale.
   Paul is the target of a U.S. federal grand jury probe based on
the testimony of Oswaldo Quintana, a U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency
informant who charged that Paul uses his private airstrip and ranch
outside Port-au-Prince to smuggle cocaine from Columbia to Florida.
   The army statement refuted the ``so-called involvement of (Paul)
in affairs of drug trafficking,'' and denounced the foreign press
for its ``campaign of denigration'' against Paul, who is in his
late 40s.
   The statement also warned the local press not to repeat
``unfounded rumors'' of the foreign press.
   Several opposition newspapers reported with banner headlines a
news conference given by Quintana in Miami last week implicating
Paul as a cocaine smuggler.
   The communique stated that if the army high command has reason
to believe that any army officer is guilty of misconduct, ``an
investigating committee will be created, in accordance with the
regulations of the Armed Forces of Haiti.''
   Paul's unit, the widely feared Dessalines Barracks, is
responsible for virtually all army repression and killings of
demonstrators in 1987. Soldiers from the 700-man batallion were
also seen in the streets during the violently-aborted Nov. 29
elections, apparerently protecting gunmen who shot or hacked to
death at least 34 voters.
</TEXT>
