<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Robertson 1stLd-Writethru a0716 02-22 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robertson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0716,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Sugggests Swaggart Scandal Timed To Hurt Him</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New thruout with Robertson interview</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By G.G. RIGSBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENWOOD, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential hopeful Pat
Robertson said Monday that ``somebody planned'' the eruption of a
scandal involving television evangelist Jimmy Swaggart two weeks
before the Super Tuesday primaries. But he wouldn't say who he was
talking about.
   ``Nothing happens to people by accident,'' Robertson, a former
television evangelist, said in an interview Monday with the
Anderson, S.C., Independent-Mail. ``It is kind of funny this came
up two weeks before the most important primaries in the nation.
People probably wonder what went on.''
   Swaggart temporarily stepped down from the pulpit of his
7,500-member church in Baton Rouge, La., on Sunday amid allegations
of sexual misconduct.
   ``I think somebody had something to do with it,'' said
Robertson. ``Somebody else planned all these things, I am afraid.''
   Robertson declined to say who he was referring to, but said the
``political efforts'' will have little effect on his campaign
because his supporters back him too strongly.
   ``It (the scandal) will not affect me because it has nothing
whatsoever to do with me,'' he told the newspaper. ``But I want to
tell people to ask (Vice President) George Bush what he thinks
about all this.''
   Earlier Monday, Robertson had said the troubles Swaggart is
having are ``unfortunate,'' but that he didn't think the
controversy would have any effect on his campaign.
   ``It will have no more effect on me than Gary Hart had on Robert
Dole,'' he said. Hart dropped out of the Democratic presidential
race in May amid reports of his relationship with a Miami model,
then rejoined the field in December.
   In the interview with the Anderson newspaper, Robertson accused
the Bush campaign of ``dirty politics'' and ``trickery'' directed
at his campaign, but offered no proof of such activity.
   ``I have been told of Bush's dirty tricks and I expect to see
them in South Carolina,'' he said. ``His campaign will use every
kind of dirty trick against me because this state is important and
I have a lot of support and George Bush knows that.''
   Bush campaign officials were not immediately available to
respond to Robertson's comments.
   Also on Monday, Robertson called for a return to teaching
methods used 40 years ago, when children could still pray in public
schools.
   Back then, ``We maybe didn't have some of the fancy buildings
and we weren't spending $270 billion a year on education, but
little children could pray in the public schools of America and
we've got to see that once again,'' he said to applause from a
group of about 800 people at Lander College.
   Robertson said in recent math tests, American students performed
just above students in Swaziland. ``Twenty-five percent of the
students in one test couldn't even locate the United States of
America on a map. How can you defend a country when you don't even
know where it is?''
   He said American education should once again stress the basics
such as the multiplication tables, science, geography and American
history.
</TEXT>
