<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Derailment-Drugs     02-22 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Derailment-Drugs,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sources Say Switchman In Amtrak Accident Tested Positive For Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Amtrak switchman who fled his post after a
derailment injured 25 passengers last month has tested positive for
marijuana and at least one other drug, officials familiar with the
tests said Monday night.
   However, one of the officials, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said authorities had not determined whether a link
existed between the Jan. 29 accident and the results of the tests
on Thomas Connor, 30, of Aldan, Pa.
   He said the laboratory that performed the tests has been asked
to clarify the analysis, and the correlation remained ``an open
issue.'' He said he could not identify any other drugs that had
been found.
   Connor was the control tower operator on duty when the train
slammed into a work vehicle in Chester, Pa., near Philadelphia. He
fled his post after realizing he had failed to take the train off a
stretch of track undergoing maintenance.
   Connor did not submit to blood or urine tests until more than 72
hours after the accident. Marijuana can remain in the system for up
to 30 days.
   Connor's lawyer, Arthur Donato of suburban Philadelphia, said he
had not been notified of the results.
   ``I don't believe it,'' Donato said, referring to the sources'
report.
   John Jacobsen, an Amtrak spokesman, said the railroad also had
not been informed of the results.
   The NBC Nightly News reported Monday night that sources had
found Connor tested positive for high amounts of marijuana, cocaine
and a third unidentified drug.
   Bill Loftus, spokesman of the Federal Railroad Administration,
said he could neither comfirm nor deny any reports about the drug
tests, pending notification to Connor and Amtrak.
   Loftus did confirm that the results had been received and said
the railroad administration expected to issue a report on Tuesday.
He said the findings were ``not simple.''
   Connor was suspended without pay by Amtrak, then resigned last
week, citing ``physical and emotional stress.''
   Calls to Connor's home were not answered Monday night.
</TEXT>
