<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 0952EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Chile-HumanRights Adv29   02-22 0934</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile-Human Rights, Adv 29,0959</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs Feb. 29 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Activists Claim Human Rights Violations More Subtle in Chile</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Open violence against dissidents is now
rare in Chile, but specialists contend that widespread human rights
violations continue in more subtle ways and often are cloaked in
apparent legality.
   The 14-year-old military government of President Augusto
Pinochet, who also is the army commander, ``has modernized'' its
repression methods, claims Roberto Garreton, chief lawyer for the
Vicariate of Solidarity, the Roman Catholic Church's human rights
agency.
   Garreton and other lawyers and human rights activists contend
that the military regime has succeeded in politically neutralizing
many dissidents by fear, making violent repression no longer
necessary.
   Speaking in interviews, they said that although torture is still
common, the government has developed other, more subtle methods,
including the continued enforcement of a nationwide state of
emergency that empowers it to severely curtail basic civil rights.
   The government has also issued a number of specially tailored
decrees and laws that give a formal legality to repression and
ensure impunity to many human rights violators, the specialists
maintain.
   As an example, they cited the widenening scope of military
justice. During the last two years, 95 percent of those tried by
military courts were civilians, according to Alejandro Hales,
president of Chile's Bar Association.
   Hales said 90 percent of those tried were eventually freed
without charges, but most of them were kept incommunicado for long
periods, sometimes up to 40 days.
   The specialists contended that repression now often works
through indimidation and threat, including the action of several
shadowy, right-wing extremist groups that kidnap, beat up and
occasionally even kill people. Authorities deny any connection with
such groups and have promised to investigate.
   Nearly 200 Chileans claim to have received death threats in
recent months from the extremist groups, including some well known
dissidents, and many have been briefly kidnapped and physically
abused.
   One group, the September 11 Commando, took responsibility for
the killing of five leftists the day after a bloody but
unsuccsessful attempt to kill Pinochet in 1986. Five young
Communists have been missing since September, and a group called
Chilean Anti-Communist Action claimed responsibility Feb. 15 for
their abduction and disappearance.
   These methods ``have an extremely paralyzing and brutally
frightening effect on most people,'' said Garreton.
   Lawyers and human rights activists, including Hales and
Garreton, said they are convinced that those groups are
``centralized'' and connected to official security services.
   Jaime Troncoso, research director of the independent Chilean
Human Rights Commission, said ``threatening is the new tactic for
repression.''
   The critics point out that, although most cases remain unsolved,
every time a member of one of those groups was discovered, he
proved to be a member of the military or the security services. An
army lieutenant, Patricio Contreras, was killed three years ago by
a bomb he was planting at a church in the southern city of Punta
Arenas. A number of leaflets of the Chilean Anti-Communist Action
group were found at the site.
   Fernando Volio, a Costa Rican who is the United Nations'
officially designated human rights inspector for Chile, has
denounced the existence of the extremist groups. Unless they are
dismantled, he said, ``this society will remain torn apart.''
   In the years after Pinochet and the military seized power in a
bloody 1973 coup, hundreds of leftist dissidents were killed, and
at least 683 cases of political prisoners who disappeared have been
documented by local and foreign human rights groups. The torture of
prisoners was considered widespread.
   Summary executions have long since ceased and arbitrary arrests
have decreased sharply.
   According to figures gathered by the Chilean Human Rights
Commission, 33,903 people were arbitrarily arrested in 1986, while
the figure went down to 6,255 in 1987.
   The commission registered 106 cases of torture of dissidents in
1987, compared to 290 a year earlier.
   The commission's Troncoso stressed in an interview that ``we
have never had a single report proved unfounded. We are extremely
rigorous. There are many claims we do not publish for lack of
evidence.''
   Since the 1973 coup, the U.N. Human Rights Commission regularly
has issued reports that are highly critical of the Chilean
government. The U.S. State Department has also been critical of
Chile in its annual country-by-country report submitted to Congress.
   This year's reports by the U.N. and the State Department, while
still critical, noted an improvement in the general situation of
human rights here. But the U.S. report mentioned continued torture
of prisoners.
   The government rejected the reports. An official statement said
the U.S. report ``reflects only a partial picture of reality, ...
has errors and mentions some facts that have not been proved.''
   Carlos Varas, secretary of a government-appointed Human Rights
Commission, said the U.S. report shows ``a lack of knowledge of the
Chilean situation.''
   The government also complains that its critics fail to refer to
terrorism by leftist guerrilla groups when discussing the human
rights situation.
   Human rights activists criticize government legislation they
contend is tailored to curb dissent. They cite the 1980
Constitution, which outlaws ``totalitarian doctrines,'' such as
Marxism, and an amnesty law that they claim favors scores of human
rights violators.
   They also cite the nationwide state of emergency and widened
state of siege legislation that severely curtail civil rights and
grant authorities wide powers to supress dissent, including the
exile of dissidents, banning of public meetings, censorship of the
mail and communications and restrictions of freedom of the press
and of labor unions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs Feb. 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
