<DOCNO> AP880222-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 0956EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-FrenchEducation Adv01   02-22 0874</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-French Education, Adv 01,0899</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs March 1 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>French Concerned about Their Often-Praised Educational System</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France's system of education, admired worldwide f, time-proven methods,
has become a source of concern
in French homes, where it is increasinglyor
its rigorous regarded as a misfit in
the modern world.
   To its critics of the late 1980s, it is like a fine old car on a
superhighway; it still works and still draws ``ahs'' but needs a
tune-up, or an overhaul, to keep up with the traffic.
   ``The fundamental problems with French education is that it is
an extremely selective system and leaves aside too large a
proportion of youth who don't finish their studies,'' said Olivier
Bertrand of the government-run Center for the Stuy 42 to 43 percent of
French students finish high school and
only about 22 to 23 percent go on to higher studies at a university
or a prestigious ``grande ecole,'' according to Bertrand.
   About 46 percent of French students receive what is known as
``professional formation'' for a specific trade, be it in a
hospital or a bakery.
   ``We are conscious these levels are no longer adapted to the
economic and social needs of today,'' said Bertrand. ``If you
compare it to countries like the United States or Japan, we are far
behind.''
   The Paris-based Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development, which seeks to promote economic and social development
in its 19 member countries, agrees with the system's critics.
   ``The education system is geared toward helping the academically
inclined. It is in fact a highly selective system which eliminates
the weaker pupils at each different level and tends to brand them
as losers,'' it said in a 1984 report on youth employment in France.
   The ``grandes ecoles'' perhaps represent the ultimate example of
selection in the education system. Since the 18th century, higher
education in France has been dominated by the elite, specialized
schools _ not universities _ which turn out the future leaders of
government and industry.
   One of the ``grandes ecoles'' is the Ecole Nationale
d'Administration, whose graduates have a near-monopoly on top jobs
in the government bureaucracy and figure prominently in politics.
   Another is L'Ecole Polytechnique, run by the Defense Ministry,
which turns out most of the nation's top engineers, many of whom
become chief executives in state-owned or private industries.
   Looking toward a more competitive continent when the European
Economic Community's open border policy starts in 1992, France is
scrutinizing its education system and finding it heading for, or
already in, a state of crisis.
   Students ill-prepared for the job market, a lack of funds, a
top-heavy structure and an aging, diminishing university teaching
corps are among other problems.
   A government-ordered report on university professors, released
Feb. 18, spoke of the ``vertiginous degradation'' of their lot, in
pay, lack of work incentives and mediocre working conditions.
   For the student, the lot is determined in a process of
selection, with the first at about age 13 based on performance in
French and mathematics.
   Universities present the opposite problem: any student with a
baccalaureate from high school can enter. There is almost universal
agreement that the 78 state-run universities need to be reformed,
but successive governments have faced a student broadside in trying
to do so.
   ``For the past 20 years, the university has been the sick man of
France,'' said the newsweekly Le Point in a cover story on
universities.
   While 80 percent of university graduates find jobs within 10
months of receiving diplomas, 70 percent of the jobs are either
administrative or not in the graduate's field.
   Even critics of the system say a student who passes the
baccalaureat, the several-days-long exam at the end of high school,
is better equipped academically than an American high school
graduate.
   But, according to current thinking, the student is not
necessarily better prepared to meet the requirements of the job
market.
   ``It is generally charged that national education is lagging
behind in comparison with the needs of companies,'' Bertrand said.
   ``In the universities, teaching is mainly theory,'' said a
24-year-old doctoral student, Laurence Guillochet. ``When you
leave, you have lots in your head but you don't know how to do
anything.''
   Premier Jacques Chirac, a presidential candidate in spring
elections, was confronted with the issue by an unemployed
24-year-old university graduate during a campaign stop in Reims.
   French education, the premier told the woman, has trained too
many people ``in abstract subjects for theoretical jobs.''
   ``It's too general. It does not give the technical expertise our
businesses demand. Our enterprises need more and more people with
technical knowledge.''
   Said Bertand: ``The big idea now is `alternance,' going
alternatively to school then a company for training, like in West
Germany, to get both theory and experience.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs March 1</NOTE>
