<NOTE>For Release Thursday, March 3</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Today is Thursday, March 3, the 63rd day of 1988. There are 303
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On March 3, 1887, Anne Mansfield Sullivan arrived at the Alabama
home of Capt. and Mrs. Arthur H. Keller to become the teacher of
their blind and deaf six-year-old daughter, Helen.
   On this date:
   In 1845, Florida became the 27th state.
   In 1847, the inventor of the telephone, Alexander Graham Bell,
was born in Edinburgh, Scotland.
   In 1849, the Home Department, forerunner of the Interior
Department, was established.
   In 1875, Bizet's opera ``Carmen'' premiered in Paris.
   In 1879, Belva Ann Bennett Lockwood became the first woman to be
admitted to practice before the U.S. Supreme Court.
   In 1885, the U.S. Post Office began offering special delivery
for first-class mail.
   In 1918, Germany, Austria and Russia signed the Treaty of
Brest-Litovsk, which ended Russian participation in World War I.
This treaty was annulled by the November 1918 armistice.
   In 1931, ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' officially became the
national anthem of the United States.
   In 1969, Apollo IX blasted off from Cape Kennedy, Fla., on a
mission to test the lunar module.
   In 1974, nearly 350 people died in one of aviation's worst
disasters as a Turkish Airlines DC-10 crashed shortly after takeoff
from Orly Airport in Paris.
   In 1982, the Senate began debate on whether to expel Sen.
Harrison A. Williams Jr. D-N.J., convicted of bribery and
conspiracy charges in the FBI's ABSCAM probe. Williams resigned
before an expulsion vote could be taken.
   Ten years ago: The remains of comedian Charlie Chaplin were
stolen by extortionists from his grave in Cosier-sur-Vevey,
Switzerland. The body was recovered near Lake Geneva 11 weeks later.
   Five years ago: In a speech in Los Angeles, President Reagan
challenged the television networks to dwell on good news for
``National Volunteer Week.'' The networks declined.
   One year ago: Comedian Danny Kaye, who enthralled audiences with
his tongue-twisting patter in such films as ``Hans Christian
Andersen'' and ``The Court Jester,'' died in Los Angeles at age 74.
   Today's Birthdays: Actor James Doohan is 68. Singer Enzo Stuarti
is 63. Princess Lee Radziwill is 55. Actor Ed Marinaro is 38.
   Thought for Today: ``Until we lose ourselves there is no hope of
finding ourselves.'' _ Henry Miller, American author (1891-1980).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
