<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv 05,0446</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv05</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Saturday, March 5</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Today is Saturday, March 5, the 65th day of 1988. There are 301
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On March 5, 1770, the ``Boston massacre'' took place as British
soldiers who had been taunted by a crowd of colonists opened fire,
killing several people.
   On this date:
   In 1766, a Spanish official, Don Antonio de Ulloa, arrived in
New Orleans to take possession of the Louisiana Territory from the
French.
   In 1867, an abortive Fenian uprising against English rule took
place in Ireland.
   In 1868, the Senate was organized into a Court of Impeachment to
decide charges against President Andrew Johnson.
   In 1933, in Germany, the Nazi Party won a majority of seats in
parliamentary elections.
   In 1946, former British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, during
an address at Westminster College in Fulton, Mo., spoke of an
``Iron Curtain'' stretching from the Baltic to the Adriatic.
   In 1953, Soviet dictator Josef Stalin died at the age of 73
after 29 years in power.
   In 1970, a nuclear non-proliferation treaty went into effect
after 43 nations ratified it.
   In 1976, the British pound fell below $2 for the first time.
   In 1977, President Jimmy Carter took questions from 42 callers
in 26 states on a network radio call-in program moderated by CBS-TV
newsman Walter Cronkite.
   In 1982, comedian John Belushi was found dead of a drug overdose
in a rented bungalow in Hollywood. He was 33.
   In 1984, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled, 5-4, that a city could
use public money to set up a Nativity scene without violating the
Constitutional separation of church and state.
   Ten years ago: Striking miners voted overwhelmingly against a
proposed contract that would have ended a 90-day walkout. President
Jimmy Carter began considering measures to try to force the miners
back to work.
   Five years ago: Bob Hawke and his opposition Labor Party
defeated Australian Prime Minister Malcolm Fraser's conservative
coalition.
   One year ago: President Reagan called on Congress to approve the
final installment of a $100 million aid package for Nicaraguan
Contra rebels, one day after a speech in which he'd called his Iran
initiative a mistake.
   Today's Birthdays: Actor Rex Harrison is 80. Actor Dean
Stockwell is 52. Football player-turned-actor Fred Williamson is
50. Violinist Eugene Fodor is 38. Singer Andy Gibb is 30.
   Thought for Today: ``Having only friends would be dull anyway _
like eating eggs without salt.'' _ Hedda Hopper, American gossip
columnist (1890-1966).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
