<1ST_LINE>a i AM-VenezuelanCampaign Adv01   02-22 0696</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Venezuelan Campaign, Adv 01,0723</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tue AMs, March 1, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Two Centrist Candidates Hold Edge in Venezuelan Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen candidates of various
political hues are in the race for Venezuela's presidency, but
polls give two centrists the leading edge so far in the campaign
for December's balloting.
   A former anti-government guerrilla hopes to become a serious
third option, but the other 11 candidates are given little chance.
   One of the centrists is Eduardo Fernandez, who is known as ``The
Tiger.'' The other is Carlos Andres Perez, a former president who
has been matching practically every every campaign promise
Fernandez has made.
   The former guerrilla is Teodoro Petkoff, a Socialist.
   Fernandez and Perez represent the two political parties that
have dominated Venezuelan politics since dictator Marcos Perez
Jimenez was overthrown in 1958 after six years in power.
   Accion Democratica (AD), the social democratic party now in
power, is fielding Perez, a 69-year-old charismatic leader with
considerable political experience.
   Perez's government in 1973-77 is popularly associated with the
oil-prices boom in 1974.
   He is considered to have a slight edge now for the Dec. 4
election, although the 47-year-old Fernandez, the Copei or
Christian democratic party candidate, has made inroads by raising
the issue of electoral reform.
   After a shaky start, Fernandez took the initiative with calls
for direct elections of state governors, rather than by
presidential appointment, and voting for individual congressional
candidates, rather than by party lists.
   ``I don't think there is an electoral system in the entire world
as primitive as ours,'' Fernandez told reporters recently.
   According to a recent Gaither poll done for Perez's AD, the
promise of reform enabled Fernandez to narrow the distance between
him and Perez to 11 percent by late January, from around 30 percent
in November.
   Following Fernandez's electoral-reforms proposal, Perez came up
with one of his own.
   ``I propose to the nation a Pact for Reform, to deepen and open
our democratic system,'' Perez announced at a public celebration
Jan. 23 marking the 30th anniversary of the Perez Jimenez's
overthrow.
   The 10-point Pact for Reform contains proposals almost identical
to the Fernandez's.
   ``The only thing (Perez) has to do now is support my
candidacy,'' Fernandez complained at a recent rally.
   The two major parties have staked out electoral bases so broad
that voters are sometimes hard pressed to see a difference.
   Fernandez and Perez preach political reforms of the democratic
system, but they agree it should stay democratic.
   They argue about the degree of state intervention in the
economy, but they agree the state should intervene.
   Copei, a member of the Christian Democratic Organization of
America, is considered somewhat more conservative, while AD, which
belongs to the Socialist International, is more labor-oriented.
   But they are both centrist. Their members run from conservative
to liberal, but most are somewhere in between.
   Venezuela's presidency has flipped back and forth between the AD
and Copei five times in the six elections from 1958 to 1983. An AD
candidate succeeded an AD president only once.
   Their success in dominating Venezuelan politics has relegated
all the other parties to marginal political roles.
   The ex-guerrilla Petkoff is carrying the banner of the
Movimiento al Socialismo.
   In the 1960s, when an indigenous guerrilla movement was active,
Petkoff preached a socialism bordering on communism.
   But he gave up his fight, accepting amnesty offered by the
government. He moderated his views and is now a member of Congress.
His party dropped its affiliation with Moscow following the
Soviet-led invasion of Czechoslavakia in 1968.
   But even though Petkoff started his campaign by trimming his
bushy moustache and longish hair in an effort to dispel any
conceptions of radicalism, he isn't expected to win much more than
5 percent of the vote.
   That was as much as his party got into 1978, its best year.
   The remaining candidates are even worse off. They are formally
in the race but are not making much of a difference.
   Venezuela's first woman presidential candidate, Ismenia
Villalba, is running on the slogan, ``Ismenia, take her into your
heart.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, March 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
