<NOTE>$adv06</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 6</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ The Society of Automotive Engineers was founded
shortly after the turn of the century as a clearinghouse for a free
exchange of ideas at a time when inventors were making contraptions
that suited their own tastes. Just as it set the standards for the
production of automobiles, SAE now is proposing interchangeable
parts for spaceships.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By BOB DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARRENDALE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An organization of engineers, best known
by its initials on motor oil cans, hopes to do for spaceships what
it did for automobiles and airplanes.
   The Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE), founded in 1905, is a
global engineering network for the exchange of ideas. Members have
included Henry Ford, Orville Wright, Harvey Firestone, Thomas
Edison and Charles Lindbergh.
   SAE writes standards on such things as what grade of motor oil
works best in cold temperatures, how much reflection comes from a
taillight lens, the process that makes a brake stop a car.
   More than 900 standards cover every passenger car.
   These standards make sure a product performs in a generally
expected way. They are guideposts by which government and industry
have measured performance for 83 years in self-propelled vehicles.
   ``We serve the public by getting the technology out so that
others can build upon it and use it as a steppingstone without
having to reinvent the wheel,'' says Max E. Rumbaugh Jr., executive
vice president of SAE.
   SAE now has its eyes on the stars.
   It created a space standardization advisory committee, which met
for the first time in December, for possible standards on
spaceships. SAE hopes to work with the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration on guidelines that would reduce confusion,
eliminate duplication and cut costs.
   ``The space program has been so unique, we've been experimenting
with technology that is one of a kind,'' says Arshad Hafeez, SAE's
aerospace engineer.
   Six of the 25 members on SAE's exploratory committee are from
NASA, which wants to have a space station in orbit in the next
decade so it can assemble ships in space, among other things.
   ``It's getting to the point where some standardization will help
everybody,'' says Dick Weinstein, manager of engineering standards
and practices for NASA.
   ``There's enough on the horizon that if we don't do something
soon, we could be in big trouble. Everybody will be going in a
different direction.''
   Rumbaugh adds: ``As they start putting things up there like a
space station, you've got to have interchangeability of parts for
repair and maintenance.
   ``You can't be coming back down here when a light bulb goes out
and build a new one to take back up. Standards allow you to reduce
the cost of manufacturing. Making one of a kind costs you a
fortune.''
   SAE has its world headquarters in a three-story, red brick
building about 30 miles north of Pittsburgh near the Pennsylvania
Turnpike and Interstate 79.
   With 52,000 members in 82 countries, it has 25,000 technical
papers on file, holds 20 meetings a year, publishes two magazines
and has an engineering library.
   None of the volumes will make a best-seller list, but they
titillate engineers.
   Esoteric titles include: The Internal Combustion Engine In
Theory And Practice, volumes one and two; Fuel Alternatives For
Spark Ignition And Diesel Engines; Reinforced Thermosetting
Plastics For Ground Vehicle Applications; The Toyota Production
Method; and Human Tolerance To Impact Conditions As Related To
Motor Vehicle Design.
   Some car manuals are available in Spanish, French and German.
   Anyone who pours a can of motor oil can notice the letters SAE
along with numbers corresponding to the viscosity of the oil. SAE
standards cover 11 grades of oil, with lower numbers performing
better in lower temperatures.
   Oil companies voluntarily produce and label their products by
SAE standards.
   Other SAE deeds are less visible.
   ``A lot of the work is sort of boring,'' Rumbaugh says. ``We
don't have a lot of hoopla. SAE just attempts to get the job done.
Oftentimes, a job can get done a heck of a lot better before it
gets a lot of media exposure. We prefer to do things before getting
the hype.''
   SAE was fringhouse for a free exchange of ideas
at a time when inventors were making contraptions that suited their
own tastes.
   Each car still has unique style features. But SAE standards
cover such things as ounded as a cleahow much light is emitted by headlamps,
the
shade of red in a taillight, the area of the windshield that should
be cleared by a wiper and the size of the lug nuts that hold a rim
onto a wheel.
   SAE also helped develop the closed-in auto body, the
self-starter that replaced the hand crank, the hydraulic brake, the
synchronized transmissions that eliminated gear noises and led to
the automatic transmission, shatterproof glass, power steering and
power brakes.
   ``The American automobile industry has thrived on the principle
that the exchange of technical information improves society,''
Rumbaugh says. `` They are less secretive than almost any other
industry in the world.''
   William Sherman, writing in 1980 on The journalists also met with a
member of what Bleibtreu said
was the Contra human rights commission.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Mayor Invites Reporter Back for Second Look</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Mayor Palmer DePaulis has invited a reporter to
take a second look at the city the newsman described in print as a
``Perry Como kind of place'' where the Mormon Church dominates
daily life.
   DePaulis says he doesn't want to appear defensive but sent a
letter to the Los Angeles Times inviting David Lamb to return for a
second look.
   In his letter Feb. 17, DePaulis said Lamb's story overlooked the
city's rich cultural climate and ethnic diversity, as well as its
beautiful mountain scenery.
   ``I wish he could see the 10th St. Patrick's Day Parade, whose
grand marshal this year is consul general of Ireland, or the
Italian-American Columbus Day celebration, ongoing since 1934, or
our annual Greek Festival and Hispanic Fiesta,'' DePaulis wrote.
   The mayor said he might try to find a sponsor for Lamb if the
invitation is accepted.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Lawrenceville Paper Moves to Mornings</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   LAWRENCEVILLE, Ga. _ The Gwinnett Daily News will convert to
morning publication in early May, the newspaper announced in its
Feb. 21 editions.
   It currently publishes in the afternoon five days a week and in
the morning on Saturday and Sunday.
   Executive Editor Jim Osteen said, ``moving to morning
publication will allow us to produce a more expansive, complete
newspaper for our readers. It will also allow our coverage of
sports and the stock market report to be more timely.''
   The Gwinnett Daily News, purchased in June by The New York
Times, becomes the second suburban Atlanta newspaper to switch from
afternoon to morning publication. The Marietta Daily Journal
announced similar plans earlier this year.
   In the last 10 years more than 100 afternoon newspapers across
the country have switched to morning publication.
</TEXT>
