<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Feb 28, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: NATO _ Famous Names</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, one of a four-story package</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   These are some of the top names in NATO:
   PIERRE HARMEL _ A Belgian law professor, premier and Cabinet
minister, his 1967 report on the alliance's long-term goals remains
the basis of NATO strategy. It was the Harmel Report that
identified the twin themes of seeking to establish an East-West
detente while maintaining strong defenses.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   GEN. DWIGHT D. EISENHOWER _ The first Supreme Allied Commander
Europe, serving from December 1950 to May 1952, at Rocquencourt,
France.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LORD ISMAY of Britain _ The first secretary general of NATO,
serving in 1952-57.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JOSEPH M. LUNS of the Netherlands _ NATO's secretary general for
a record 13 years. He was succeeded in 1984 by Britain's Lord
Carrington, the current secretary general.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   GEN. BERNARD W. ROGERS _ An American, he was the longest-serving
NATO supreme commander. He retired last summer after holding the
job for eight years.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MANFRED WOERNER _ Currently West Germany's defense minister, he
is scheduled to replace Carrington as secretary general this
summer. He will be the first West German to hold NATO's highest
political office.
</TEXT>
