<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 0204EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--HomeImprovements:Kitchen-Bath     02-22 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Home Improvements: Kitchen-Bath,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>HOME IMPROVEMENTS: Kitchen-Bath</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY703, NY705</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Baths and kitchens top the list of rooms that homeowners choose
to remodel, says the National Kitchen and Bath Association, which
projects that nearly 10 million consumers will replace one of those
rooms in 1988.
   More than 5.5 million kitchens were remodeled last year,
according to the association.
   ``Both rooms have a high return on investment when it comes time
to sell a home,'' says Francis Jones, executive director of the
trade group.
   Other reasons for what he says is a 14 percent increase over
last year in the number of people remodeling those rooms include
more discretionary income and a trend toward staying home. ``A good
portion of that income is going into home improvements,
particularly the kitchen and bath,'' he says.
   ``Consumers want all the options _ whirlpool tubs, steam
features in their showers, ranges with grill features, wine
coolers.''
   The kitchen, in particular, may be becoming more personalized,
say kitchen designers, who see it as a ``family activity center.''
   ``Kitchens are expanding by combining several adjacent family
areas, often spilling over into the great room,'' says David
Hundley, marketing manager for Wilsonart, producers of decorative
laminate surfacing. ``Kitchens are no longer used just for cooking,
but have become areas to socialize, do the laundry, sew or work at
the home computer.''
   Kitchens are becoming more practical, says a designer,
incorporating several areas into the same space.
   ``The laundry room might be a part of the kitchen, concealed
behind doors, a desk area for the family computer, a baking center
equipped with storage space for bulky mixing tools hidden behind
tambour garages, an area for potting plants, a place to barbecue or
even sew,'' says Gay Fly, president of Gay Fly Interiors, Houston.
   Among the more popular remodeling plans for kitchens are those
that remove the walls between the kitchen and family room, allowing
plenty of space for socializing, according to Richard M. Rozic,
vice president of builder sales for White Consolidated Industries,
appliance manufacturers.
   The bathroom, too, is getting more remodeling attention,
according to many manufacturers and designers.
   Some designers now consider the room a ``stress reduction
center,'' complete with exercise equipment, sauna, whirlpool and
television set.
   ``Oversized and two-person showers designed with
multi-showerheads and controls are popular. Large closets and
utility areas are also showing up,'' says designer Fly.
   ``Everything is designed to accommodate more than one person in
the bathroom.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
