<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--HomeImprovements:Briefs     02-22 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Home Improvements: Briefs,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>HOME IMPROVEMENTS: Briefs</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction for 1987 dropped to 1.62 million units, the
slowest building pace for the housing industry since the recession
year of 1982, the Commerce Department reported.
   The total compared to construction of 1.81 million units in
1986, which had been an exceptionally strong year for the industry.
In 1982, 1.06 million units were built.
   Analysts blamed much of the weakness on widespread overbuilding
in the apartment sector and the adverse effects of the new tax law
on real estate investments.
   Building permits for the year totaled 1.54 million units, 13.1
percent below 1986 and the weakest showing since 1982.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sales of new homes in 1987 fell 10.1 percent below the 1986
level, the government has reported. The Commerce Department said
that sales totaled 674,000 units, compared with sales of 750,000
units in 1986.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   How-to videotapes, for rent or sale, are available in many home
centers, hardware stores and lumber yards and some libraries and
video stores. Brands include Hometime, Wally's Workshop, Ortho and
The DIY Show.
   Hometime, of Eden Prairie, Minn., has 27 titles for under $10
each. (Chevrolet Trucks has underwritten the productions in return
for a commercial on each tape.)
   New titles from Hometime include ``Plumbing'' (how to plan for
and install a new bathroom), ``Furniture Refinishing'' (including
stripping), and ``Lighting'' (indoor and outdoor projects).
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing homes held steady in 1987 at close to 4
million units despite volatile mortgage rates and the October stock
market collapse, a national real estate trade group reported.
   The National Association of Realtors said that sales of existing
single-family homes and condominiums totaled 3.885 million units
last year, down a slight 0.3 percent from the 1986 level of 3.897
million units. Sales in both years were the fastest pace of this
decade.
   Meanwhile, the average price of an existing home rose to a
nationwide median of $84,900, an increase of 5.1 percent in 1987,
slightly ahead of the rise in consumer prices, the association said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
