<DOCNO> AP880222-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 0214EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--HomeImprovements:Fillers     02-22 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Home Improvements: Fillers,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>HOME IMPROVEMENTS: Fillers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   When the tip of a screwdriver needs squaring, clamp it in a
vise. File so that the tool does not rock, otherwise you will not
get a straight blade tip. Always file away from yourself.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   If it becomes necessary to loosen a window that won't budge,
don't use a screwdriver blade between the window and the frame.
Instead, hold a putty knife as flat as you can get it and tap the
handle gently with a light hammer. The screwdriver may work all
right, but it will leave gouges in the wood.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Lacquer thinner is the solvent for lacquer, denatured alcohol
for shellac, and turpentine or mineral spirits for oil-based
finishes. Despite this general rule, read the instructions on the
label to determine what the solvent is for the particular product.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   When you use a wrench or pliers on a kitchen fixture, put
adhesive tape or something similar on the nut to keep it from
getting chewed up.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Always buy a hand tool by picking it up and going through the
motions of using it. The ``feel'' of the tool is important. If it
doesn't seem right, it will be even more uncomfortable when put
into actual use.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   A cheap tool remains a cheap tool through its lifetime. Buying
the least expensive tool you can find is usually poor economy. Not
only won't it last as long as the good one, it will never give you
a fine performance, even at the start.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Accidents occur on extension ladders because people insist on
overreaching, mostly so they don't have to move the ladder so much.
Don't be a casualty of that sort of thinking. Get down and move the
ladder as often as necessary to keep you from stretching.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Never strike anything with the side or cheek of a hammer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Tinner's snips are used for cutting light sheet metal. Larger
snips for cutting heavier metal are referred to as shears. When
snips are used for cutting hardened metal _ rather than soft _ the
cutting edges will be damaged.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Early American Indians quarried natural sharpening stones for
use on the tips of spears and arrows.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   A pushbroom is excellent for spreading blacktop sealer on a
driveway.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   In a poll conducted at the 1988 National Association of Home
Builders convention in Dallas, performance and durability were
ranked as the most important qualities to seek in the purchase of
power tools.
   Ease of use ranked third, followed by warranties, price and
available accessories. When builders were asked to name the first
three types of power tools do-it-yourselfers should buy, they chose
the circular saw, power drills and miter saw. After that, in order,
came the radial arm saw, belt sander, pad sander, router and planer.
   The poll was conducted by Ryobi American Corp., Bensenville, Ill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
