<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   02-22 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0560</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks between Pan Am Corp. and the 4,500-member
union representing reservation clerks broke off. The Teamsters
union vowed to disrupt operations through ``guerrilla warfare'' but
put off any strike.
   Pan Am officials said Sunday that airline service would continue
without interruption even if there eventually is a walkout, and
threatened to discipline any workers disrupting service.
   But the federal mediator involved in the negotiations said he
was optimistic the two sides would return to the bargaining table.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FREEHOLD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Wall Street speculator has been charged
with weapons possession and witness intimidation after authorities
alleged he plotted an attack on convicted financier Ivan F. Boesky.
   The arrest of John A. Mulheren, once a close associated of
Boesky, marked the first public indication of potential violence in
the insider trading scandal.
   Mulheren, a general partner in the firm Jamie Securities Co.,
was arrested in possession of an Israeli-made semi-automatic rifle.
He was ordered held in lieu of $17,500 after a hearing Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. said it has asked a federal court
for $5.7 billion in damages from the Eastman Kodak Co., which was
found in 1985 to have infringed on Polaroid patents in the instant
photography market.
   The request made Friday marks the latest development in a
12-year-old case that forced Kodak out of its $200 million-a-year
instant photography business. A hearing is set for March 18 but a
trial date has not yet been set.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street sent Texaco Inc.'s stock smartly
higher following word that T. Boone Pickens was seeking permission
to buy at least 15 percent of the beleaguered oil giant, a stake
similar to that already held by fellow corporate raider Carl C.
Icahn.
   Texaco, which has been reorganizing itself as it prepares to
emerge from Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection, has been fighting
efforts by Icahn _ its largest shareholder _ to strip the company
of its anti-takeover defenses.
   Company officials have feared that Icahn or another raider would
try to take the company over and sell its assets to boost the value
of their stock. Texaco stock closed Friday at $42.62{ per share, up
$1.87{.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gillette Co. said it would resist Coniston
Partners' attempt to place four representatives on its board of
directors, setting the stage for a battle that analysts say could
end Gillette's lengthy fight to remain independent.
   Coniston, which controls a roughly 6 percent stake in the
consumer products maker, stated in a Securities and Exchange
Commission filing Friday that it intended to nominate four
candidates for the board seats up for election at Gillette's annual
meeting in April.
  
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Broadcasting Co. said it had
tentatively agreed to sell five radio stations to Emmis
Broadcasting Corp., a privately-held concern based in Indianapolis,
for $121.5 million.
   NBC had previously disclosed it was looking for buyers for its
seven radio stations, and reaffirmed Friday that it hoped to sell
the remaining stations.
   The stations which would be sold to Emmis Broadcasting are
WNBC-AM and WYNY-FM in New York, WJIB-FM in Boston, WKQX-FM in
Chicago and KYUU-FM in San Francisco.
</TEXT>
