<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan defended his tax and budget
policies in an election-year economic report to Congress, saying
his administration had turned economic despair into hope.
   Reagan's seventh annual economic report issued Friday headed off
accusations by Democratic presidential candidates that a $2.4
trillion national debt and record trade imbalances during the
Reagan years had hobbled the country and eventually would reduce
Americans' standard of living.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has stayed a lower
court decision that would have cleared the way for a merger
creating the nation's largest glass container company.
   The U.S. Court of Appeals said Friday the stay, which keeps the
proposed merger between Owens-Illinois Inc. and Brockway Inc. on
hold, remains in effect until further notice.
   The merger would make the combined company the largest
manufacturer of glass containers in the industry.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California regulators are seeking Superior
Court approval to liquidate troubled TMIC Insurance Co., which has
been operating under state conservatorship for two years.
   The problems of TMIC, formerly known as Ticor Mortgage Insurance
Co., stem from the $1.4 billion default of Equity Programs
Investment Corp., or EPIC, a Virginia-based land syndicator that
had acquired 20,000 properties for tax-shelters partnerships.
   A spokeswoman for California's insurance commissioner said
Friday the state still hopes an alternative to liquidation can be
worked out before an April 6 court hearing.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The balance of power in the banking industry has
shifted dramatically since the October stock market crash, leaving
many of the nation's largest institutions vulnerable to takeovers,
a study said.
   The report released Friday by MAC Group, a Cambridge-based
financial research firm, rated 19 of the 50 largest U.S. banking
institutions as susceptible to takeovers as of the end of last
year, compared with just four by Sept. 30.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. workers learned their stake of the
automaker's $4.6 billion 1987 profits will average more than $3,700
each when profit-sharing checks are handed out next month.
   Ford officials announced Friday that a record $635 million in
profit-sharing will be distributed to hourly and salaried workers
March 8.
   In 1987, Ford outearned industry-leader General Motors Corp. for
the second consecutive year. While Ford workers reap the benefits,
GM workers will receive no share of profits for the second straight
year.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market jumped ahead Friday on a late outburst of
buying.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 28.18 points to
2,014.59, its highest close since it stood at 2,051.89 on Jan. 7.
For the past week the average showed a net gain of 31.33.
   Bond prices barely budged. The dollar turned in a mixed
performance in foreign exchange, and gold prices rose.
   In other markets, coffee futures for near-term delivery surged
above $1.40 a pound Friday for the first time since December 1986.
Cattle futures advanced sharply, while grains and soybeans,
precious metals, energy futures and stock-index futures all moved
higher.
</TEXT>
