<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 0908EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Strike     02-22 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Strike,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike At Land-Rover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 6,000 employees began a strike Monday over a
pay dispute at Land-Rover, the first walkout against the
state-owned automaker in about six years.
   It was also the second job action against the British automaking
industry this month. Production was resuming Monday at Ford Motor
Co. following a two-week stoppage.
   About 1,000 workers set up picket lines at the gates of the
state-owned Land-Rover plant at Solihull, just outside Birmingham
in the British Midlands.
   Huge traffic jams, some more then a mile long, nearly blocked
roads leading to the plant as the pickets stopped supervisors and
office workers in their cars and urged them not to cross the picket
line.
   The strike over a pay dispute was the first at the company since
November 1981, said a Land-Rover spokeswoman, speaking anonymously
in keeping with British custom.
   She said the strike would mean the loss of 200 Land-Rover and
Range Rover vehicles a day, with a retail value of about 3 million
pounds, or about $5.25 million.
   Land-Rover is a division of Rover Group, the vehicle
manufacturer which the government plans to sell to the private
sector. It is separate from the Rover Group's carmaking division,
Austin Rover.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
