<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Hyundai-Canada     02-22 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Hyundai-Canada,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hyundai To Continue Car Sales In Canada</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hyundai Motor Co. said Monday it would
continue to sell its cars in Canada despite a Canadian ruling that
the South Korean automaker was ``dumping'' its product.
   Hyundai officials also said the automaker will complete an
assembly plant, now under construction in Bremont, Quebec, by early
next year as scheduled.
   They said the plant is to assemble 50,000 cars initially and
have a maximum output of 100,000 cars.
   The Department of National Revenue of Canada last week upheld
its earlier ruling that Hyundai cars were being ``dumped,'' or sold
for less in Canada than in South Korea.
   The Canadian authorities acted on complaints by the Candian
subsidiaries of General Motors Corp.and Ford Motor Co.
   Hyundai officials said they were optimistic that the Canada
Import Tribunal would rule in favor of Hyundai in reviewing the
anti-dumping case by March 20.
   Hyundai officials said Hyundai has stopped shipping Stellar and
Pony models to Canada and now ships only Excel.
   Hyundai marketed 32,985 cars in Canada, including 21,118 Excels.
</TEXT>
