<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     02-22 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0347</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices held in a narrow range today as
traders awaited new signs of the outlook for the economy and
interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 5.64 to 2,008.95
in the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers slightly outnumbered losers in the overall tally of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 546 up, 501 down and 504
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 28.62 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said traders were looking ahead to congressional
testimony Tuesday by Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal
Reserve Board.
   Several statistical reports are also due this week on such
subjects as durable goods orders, the consumer price index and
personal income and consumption.
   Of special interest to Wall Streeters is the Commerce
Department's revised figure for the gross national product in the
fourth quarter of last year, scheduled to be issued Thursday.
   The department earlier estimated GNP growth, after adjustment
for inflation, at a 4.2 percent annual rate in the October-December
period. Many analysts believe the new figure will be higher.
   Economists at Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co., for example, say
it is possible that the report will show growth of 5.5 percent or
more.
   Polaroid rose 1\ to 28} and Eastman Kodak dropped 1{ to 40}.
Late Friday it was disclosed that Polaroid was seeking to recover
as much as $5.7 billion from Kodak in connection with violations of
instant-photography patents.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slipped .19 to 146.77. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up .08 at 280.24.
   On Friday the Dow Jones industrial average jumped 28.18 points
to a six-week high of 2,014.59.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 2 to 1 on the
NYSE, with 999 up, 479 down and 469 unchanged. Big Board volume
totaled 180.30 million shares, against 151.43 million in the
previous session.
</TEXT>
