<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Long-range bullish attitudes prevailed in the grain and soybean
pits, and little selling pressure surfaced this morning after last
Friday's steep sell-off just before the close.
   ``Everybody that needed to get out got out on Friday,'' said
Victor Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``Now
they're all gunning again, coming back for more.''
   Supportive fundamentals included relatively light farmer selling
of grains over the weekend and dry weather in the soybean-growing
region of southern Brazil, Lespinasse said.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent lower to 1{ cents higher with
the contract for delivery in March at $3.22{ a bushel; corn was \
cent lower to 1} cents higher with March at $2.01 a bushel; oats
were } cent lower to \ cent higher with March at $1.91 a bushel;
soybeans were 1 cent to 3{ cents higher with March at $6.34 a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures mostly were higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .42 cent higher with April at
73.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .30 cent
higher with March at 83.35 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent lower
to .43 cent higher with April at 44.15 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .18 cent to .58 cent higher with February at 53.85
cents a pound.
   All livestock futures settled higher on Friday while frozen pork
bellies ended lower.
</TEXT>
