<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CBOT-FraudAllegations     02-22 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CBOT-Fraud Allegations,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CFTC Probing Fraud Allegations Against 22 CBOT Traders: Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commodity Futures Trading Commission has
notified 22 traders at the Chicago Board of Trade that the CFTC
staff will recommend civil charges of prearranged and fraudulent
trading against them, according to a published report.
   But some of the traders involved say the trading technique in
question is practiced daily on many commodity exchanges and is not
prohibited by the exchanges' rules, the Wall Street Journal
reported in today's editions.
   Officials at the CFTC, the federal agency that regulates futures
exchanges, would neither confirm nor deny the report.
   ``The only enforcement action the commission will comment on is
a publicly filed complaint,'' said Kate Hathaway, a CFTC
spokeswoman.
   The case, reportedly involving trading at the world's biggest
market for U.S. Treasury bond futures, may be one of the largest
single instances of alleged futures trading violations.
   The Journal said the allegations concerned certain trades made
in the Board of Trade's huge Treasury bond futures pit in mid-1986.
The traders maintained that the type of trading being investigated
_ loosely known as a ``ginzie'' trade, where a customer gets two
different prices for portions of the same buy or sell order _ is
widespread on futures exchanges, the newspaper said.
   The CFTC notifications are part of a procedure designed to give
potential defendants a chance to argue to the commission that it
should not follow its staff's recommendations.
   The traders received the notices last Wednesday and Thrusday and
were given two weeks to respond with the written arguments to the
CFTC, the Journal reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880222-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 1157EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-RigCount     02-22 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Rig Count,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rig Count Up 10 To 978 In Latest Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of oil and gas rigs working in the
United States rose by 10 this week to total 978, Baker Hughes Inc.
announced Monday.
   This week's total reflects the number of rigs working as of last
Friday. A year ago the count was 839, Baker Hughes stated.
   The previous week, the rig count had dropped by 18 to total 968.
The rig count usually declines during the first few months of the
year.
   Houston-based Baker Hughes, an oil toolmaker, tallies the number
of rigs actively exploring for oil, and not rigs producing oil. The
rig count is the most widely-watched industry index of drilling
activity.
   Hughes Tool Co., which merged this year with Baker International
Corp. of Orange, Calif., has kept track of the number of working
rigs since 1940.
   In December 1981, at the height of the oil boom, the count
reached a peak with 4,500 active rigs. But in the summer of 1986,
the rig count fell to 663 _ the lowest since Hughes began compiling
figures _ as oil prices plunged to less than $10 per 42-gallon
barrel.
   Among the major oil producing states, Texas gained 12 rigs this
week, followed by Kansas, 10; Wyoming, three; North Dakota, two;
and Colorado, one.
   New Mexico posted the largest decrease, losing five. Ohio and
Oklahoma lost two each; Louisiana and Michigan lost one each.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880222-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 1204EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Chi-Chi'sSold     02-22 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Chi-Chi's Sold,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>San Diego Company To Acquire Chi-Chi's Restaurant Chain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foodmaker Inc., the operator and
franchiser of Jack in the Box restaurants, will acquire Chi-Chi's
Inc., a 200-unit Mexican restaurant chain, in a leveraged buyout
for about $230 million, the companies announced Monday.
   Under the agreement, which has been approved by the boards of
both companies, Foodmaker will acquire Chi-Chi's in a $10.15 a
share tender offer. The sale was expected to be completed about
April 1.
   ``We believe it will be an excellent vehicle, along with the
Jack in the Box chain, for growth acceleration and to build
stockholder value,'' said Jack W. Goodall Jr., chairman and
president of Foodmakers.
   San Diego-based Foodmaker will finance the acquisition with
short-term loans from a group of banks led by Wells Fargo Bank NA,
Goodall said, but Foodmaker was confident Chi-Chi's cash flow would
be sufficient to fund the purchase.
   He also said Chi-Chi's headquarters would remain in Louisville
with its current management.
   ``We think this transaction, which is not conditioned upon
obtaining financing, is in the best interest of our stockholders,
and we are pleased that Foodmaker intends to continue the growth of
Chi-Chi's and maintain our headquarters in Louisville,'' said Hal
Smith, chairman and chief executive of Chi-Chi's.
   Chi-Chi's operates and franchises full-service Mexican
restuarants. For the six months ended Oct. 31, Chi-Chi's had net
income of $6.7 million on revenue of $144.5 million.
   Foodmaker Inc., operates and franchises more than 900 Jack in
the Box fast-food restaurants located mainly in the western and
southwestern United States.
   Foodmaker had net earnings of $13.9 million in 1987 on revenue
of $598 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
