<HEAD>Westinghouse Agrees To Venture With Daimler Benz Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Electric Corp. has signed a
preliminary agreement to merge its transportation business with a
subsidiary of West Germany's Daimler Benz, Westinghouse announced
Monday.
   AEG Aktiengesellschaft will own 60 percent and Westinghouse 40
percent of the new company, AEG-Westinghouse Transportation
Systems. Further terms of the agreement were withheld.
   The Westinghouse transportation business employs 850 people and
produces mass transit propulsion equipment and automated people
movers.
   AEG is a diversified company with 1987 sales of about $7
billion. Its transportation business, AEG Railway Systems, employs
about 2,000 people making propulsion equipment for railway cars and
locomotives. It recently introduced people mover products.
   The joint venture is subject to a definitive agreement and
approval from both companies' boards and government regulators. It
would include a Westinghouse plant in the Pittsburgh suburb of West
Mifflin and AEG plants in Los Angeles and in the West German cities
of West Berlin, Frankfurt and Bretten.
</TEXT>
