<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AMer expected by 5:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell Monday against all major
currencies except the Canadian dollar in listless European trading.
   Gold prices rose in Europe after slipping in Hong Kong.
   Dealers attributed the dollar's slide mainly to uncertainty over
the state of the U.S. economy.
   While recent reports that the U.S. trade deficit had narrowed
had supported the dollar, dealers said there were no new incentives
to keep it from falling.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7630 from $1.7505 late
Friday.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell to close at 129.95 Japanese yen from
130.53 yen on Friday. In later trading in London, the dollar
slipped to 129.27 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates
Friday, included: 1.6955 West German marks, down from 1.7075;
1.3930 Swiss francs, down from 1.3985; 5.7500 French francs, down
from 5.7675; 1.9040 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9150; 1,252.25
Italian lire, down from 1,257.75, and 1.2738 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.2702.
   Gold prices rose in thin trading in Europe in response to the
dollar's weakness, bullion dealers said.
   In London, the metal rose to $446 a troy ounce from $442.90 late
Friday. In Zurich, gold rose to $446.50 from $443 late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell to $447.12 an ounce from
$447.51 Saturday.
   Silver bullion rose in London to $6.41 a troy ounce from $6.37
late Friday.
</TEXT>
