<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 1553EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Drexel-Charges     02-22 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drexel-Charges,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drexel Acknowledges SEC Staff Recommended Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time, Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
has acknowledged publicly that the staff of the Securities and
Exchange Commission has recommended that Drexel and some of its
employees face civil charges.
   The investment firm also confirmed it has been under
investigation by a federal grand jury.
   The information is contained in a preliminary prospectus for New
America High Income Fund Inc., a new high-yield ``junk bond'' fund
being Drexel is underwriting. Such information routinely is
required in prospectuses to warn would-be investors of potential
risk.
   The document describing the fund was dated Feb. 16 and mailed to
investors last week.
   It stated Drexel had advised the fund about the SEC staff
recomendations for civil actions against the firm and against some
employees ``relating to transactions, some of which may have
involved `high yield' bonds.''
   ``No assurance can be given that the results of any such SEC
action or grand jury investigation will not have an adverse effect
on Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and-or the market for `high yield'
bonds, a market in which Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. is an
important participant,'' the prospectus said.
   Despite the caveat, sales of the fund apparently were unaffected
on Friday, its first trading day, when it closed unchanged at $10
per share.
   Steven S. Anreder, Drexel's chief spokesman, on Monday declined
to comment outside of the information contained in the prospectus.
   In January, Drexel and several ranking employees _ including
junk-bond chief Michael Milken _ reportedly were informed that the
SEC staff had decided to recommend charges of violations of
security laws.
   On Jan. 27, the Wall Street Journal said the focus of the SEC's
investigation of Drexel involved possible violations of securities
laws in corporate takeover situations, particularly ``stock
parking'' _ the hiding of true ownership of stock in someone else's
name. The practice can be used to evade SEC reporting requirements.
   Drexel and the employees have lodged their opposition to the
decision with the SEC, but the federal agency had not decided
whether to proceed, according to the prospectus.
   The firm previously has acknowledged that an investigation was
under way, but it has maintained that no wrongdoing took place.
   The prospectus says Drexel has furnished documents to a federal
grand jury in New York, and some employees have appeared before the
panel.
   Drexel reportedly has been the object of government scrutiny
since the breaking of the scandal surrounding former arbitrager
Ivan F. Boesky, because of the firm's extensive involvement in
financing of corporate takeovers involved in the scandal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
