<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly lower
Monday after a late sell-off on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   A mixed opening was followed by firmer prices across the board,
but the gains did not hold up.
   The decline near the session's end was led by commission-house
selling of soybeans and soybean oil, said Victor Lespinasse, a
trader for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   ``The beans and oil were the two markets that really collapsed,
and that collapse pulled everything else down,'' he said.
   Soybean traders closely are watching the large Brazilian soybean
crop, which is nearly ready to harvest, Lespinasse said. Weather
conditions in Brazil will have an increasing impact on U.S. soybean
futures as the harvest gets under way.
   At the close, wheat was { cent lower to 1 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $3.22{ a bushel; corn was 1 cent
to 2\ cents lower with March at $1.99{ a bushel; oats were
unchanged to 1 cent lower with March at $1.90} a bushel; soybeans
were 6{ cents lower to 1{ cents higher with March at $6.27 a bushel.
