<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Monsanto-AstroTurf     02-22 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Monsanto-AstroTurf,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Monsanto Selling AstroTurf Unit To German Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Monsanto Co., a pioneer in the development of
synthetic turf for sports fields, said Monday that it had sold its
AstroTurf Industries Inc. subsidiary to a West German company.
   Terms of the sale to Balsam Sportstattenbau GmbH & Co., K.G., of
Steinhagen, West Germany, were not disclosed. Astroturf Industries
will become a wholly-owned subsidiary of Balsam and will remain
based in Dalton, Ga., a company spokesman said.
   Monsanto installed the world's first commercially-produced
synthetic turf playing surface in the Astrodome in Houston in 1966.
Since then, AstroTurf surfaces have been installed in hundreds of
sports stadiums and athletic fields around the world.
   Balsam has offered jobs to ``essentially all'' of the
businesses' 100 employees and will keep its management team intact,
Monsanto Group vice president Earl N. Brasfield said.
   Balsam is the multinational market leader and manufacturer of
sports and recreational surfaces, and has been serving as
Monsanto's European and Asia-Pacific distributor for AstroTurf
recreational surfaces. It also has other U.S.-based subsidiaries
that market and install indoor and outdoor sports floor systems.
   The agreement gives Balsam the rights to the AstroTurf
trademark, but Monsanto will continue using the trademark in its
doormat business.
   Monsanto spokesman Dan Bishop said the buyer asked that the
annual sales figure for AstroTurf not be released.
   But he said AstroTurf sales amounted to less than one-half of
one percent of Monsanto's annual sales. Monsanto had sales of $7.64
billion in 1987.
   Bishop said the sale was made because AstroTurf ``was not part
of our new strategy.'' The company's primary business is in fibers,
plants, resins and specialty chemicals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
