<DOCNO> AP880222-0287 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 1649EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MidAmAgreement     02-22 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MidAm Agreement,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Midam, First Commodity Reach $3.51 Million Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The MidAmerica Commodity Exchange and First
Commodity Corp. of Boston have agreed to a $3.51 million settlement
ending all fraud litigation against First Commodity, the exchange
announced Monday.
   Under the agreement, $3.01 million will be paid directly to
defrauded customers, whose losses totaled more than $51 million in
1984, the exchange said in a news release.
   MidAm will retain First Commodity's $500,000 guarantee deposit
and the now-defunct firm waived all claim to those funds, the news
release stated.
   MidAmerica in 1986 found that First Commodity had violated
exchange rules through its use of promotional materials, fraudulent
and misleading sales practices and its withdrawal of guarantee
funds on deposit with the exchange.
   The exchange expelled the company and fined it $3.51 million.
First Commodity later went out of business.
   ``Plaintiffs in the class action applaud the MidAm's efforts and
contributions in helping settle the largest reported class action
commodity fraud settlement to date,'' said Marvin Miller, one of
the plaintiffs' Chicago attorneys.
   James Brooks, general counsel for First Commodity, could not be
reached to comment immediately on the settlement. An answering
service collected requests for comment from the defunct firm.
   ``The MidAm Board of Directors felt this settlement met all the
objectives of the exchange, the futures industry, and the needs of
defrauded investors,'' said MidAmerica President Thomas R. Donovan.
   The agreement stipulates that First Commodity will pay $3.01
million to a settlement fund to be administered by the federal
district court in Boston, where investor cases were consolidated.
   The fund will be used to compensate those investors for some of
their losses.
   The U.S. District Court ``has preliminarily approved a
settlement class of potentially defrauded FCCB customers eligible
for compensation. This settlement raises the amount in the fund to
a currently estimated $5.3 million,'' the exchange stated.
   William Murschel, an exchange spokesman, said he did not know
how many investors were involved, but the release said ``virtually
every FCCB customer lost money, most of them losing 50-90 percent
of their investments.
   ``Customer out-of-pocket losses in 1984 totaled in excess of $51
million, nearly $30 million of which went to FCCB in the form of
commissions,'' the exchange said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880222-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 1620EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-PanAm Bjt   02-22 0819</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pan Am, Bjt,0845</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pan Am, Teamsters in Standoff; Some Agents Report Bookings Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan Am Corp. and the union representing 4,500
ground employees in 14 cities remained in a stalemate Monday
following the breakup of their talks, and Teamster leaders vowed
``guerrilla war'' against the financially troubled airline.
   Travel agents reported that some customers have shunned Pan Am
flights as a result of the conflict, which was sparked after the
Teamsters' strike deadline passed at 12:01 a.m. Sunday.
   Talks in which management was seeking $35 million in concessions
from the union broke down Sunday afternoon.
   No negotiating sessions were held Monday. The union, which
represents reservation clerks and other ground staff, put off a
strike. But Teamster leaders threatened to use disruptive tactics
against Pan Am, which operates Pan American World Airways, a
Northeast corridor air shuttle and other services.
   Labor unrest also escalated at another major U.S. airline.
Flight attendants at Minneapolis-based Northwest Airlines have
voted overwhelmingly to strike this weekend if a contract dispute
over wages and benefits is not resolved, a union official said.
   Disclosure of the Northwest strike vote came as the two sides
readied to resume negotiations for the first time since last month.
   Sources close to Pan Am, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said they were pessimistic about the prospects for a negotiated
resolution of the conflict with the Teamsters.
   ``We can strike (Pan Am) any time we want,'' said William
Genoese, director of the Teamsters' airline division. ``We're going
to pick our strategic time.''
   In the meantime, Genoese said, ``there's guerrilla war at all
the airports. ... The passengers are really going to suffer in this
situation.'' He said the tactics would include deliberately
misdirecting baggage and cargo and canceling passengers'
reservations.
   Pan Am spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon said there was no evidence so
far of such disruptions.
   ``The operation is running smoothly,'' Hanlon said. ``There is
no evidence of any job action of any sort at any station.'' She
said ``nothing very dramatic'' had happened at John F. Kennedy
International Airport in New York City, Pan Am's major hub.
   The company has said it would maintain operations with
replacement workers in the event of a strike. The Transport Workers
Union at Pan Am voted Friday not to support a Teamsters' strike,
and pilots, flight attendants and flight engineers are not expected
to honor picket lines.
   ``There haven't been any problems whatsoever,'' said Archie
Lenzi, chairman of the Pan Am pilots union's Master Executive
Council, noting that he piloted a flight Sunday from San Francisco
to New York without incident.
   Not all travelers appear to be reassured, however.
   ``It's a very bad situation for everybody,'' said David Perlman,
president of DMS Travel in midtown Manhattan. ``Some people are
shying away (from Pan Am flights).''
   Perlman said his agency has been using double bookings as an
insurance technique for customers booked on Pan Am flights. For
passengers taking Pan Am from Kennedy airport to Europe on Monday
night, for example, he also booked them on flights offered by other
airlines to the same destinations.
   ``I think we have to go on the assumption that if there is a
strike, all (Pan Am) flights will be shut down,'' Perlman said.
   James Cammisa, a travel industry consultant, estimates that a
threatened strike against an airline generally reduces bookings for
the carrier by about 10 percent to 20 percent.
   ``Any kind of strike threat erodes bookings,'' Cammisa said,
noting that the same thing has happened with Eastern Airlines, a
subsidiary of giant Texas Air Corp. with a history of labor
troubles.
   ``The public is very concerned about the turmoil (Pan Am is)
having with their unions,'' said Steven Hoffenberg, chairman of
Towers Financial Corp. The loss of bookings resulting from the
conflict, he said, ``is going to be enough to drain the company and
put them into bankruptcy.''
   Towers, a debt-collection and insurance holding company based in
New York, has said it intends to launch a takeover bid for Pan Am,
with the Teamsters' backing. Towers owns about 100,000 Pan Am
shares, out of a total of around 139 million shares outstanding.
   Pan Am had a net loss last year of $265.3 million on revenue of
$2.9 billion, following a 1986 loss of $462.8 million on revenue of
$2.5 billion. The company recently signed agreements on more than
$330 million in concessions with the unions representing pilots,
flight engineers and flight attendants. Pan Am also went through a
major management shakeup a month ago: Its new chairman, Thomas G.
Plaskett, briefly headed Continental Airlines and also worked at
American Airlines.
   The Teamsters represent workers at airports in Boston, Detroit,
Chicago, Seattle, San Francisco, San Diego, Los Angeles, Honolulu,
Houston, Washington, New York and the Florida cities of Tampa,
Orlando and Miami. The vast majority of the workers are employed in
New York and Miami.
</TEXT>
