<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Steel,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Output Rose 4.0 Percent in Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel production rose to 1.942 million tons in
the week ended Feb. 20, an increase of 4.0 percent from the
previous week's 1.867 million tons, the American Iron and Steel
Institute reported Monday.
   The industry's production amounted to 90.4 percent of capacity
during the week, compared with 86.9 percent in the previous week.
   Estimated figures for the year to date showed production at
13.796 million net tons, a jump of 39.6 percent from the 9.882
million net tons in the previous year. The steel operations of USX
Corp., the nation's largest steel producer, were shut down by a
strike during the first month of 1987.
   Production so far this year used 88.2 percent of capacity,
compared with 63.7 percent a year earlier.
   Net tonnage by district for the week ended Feb. 20: Northeast
Coast, 275,000; Pittsburgh, 206,000; Youngstown, 128,000; Lake
Erie, 148,000; Detroit, 157,000; Chicago, 535,000; Midwest,
178,000; Southern, 218,000; and Western, 97,000.
</TEXT>
