<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted lower Monday against most
other currencies in listless trading that analysts said reflected
uncertainty about the outlook for the U.S. economy and interest
rates.
   Gold prices were narrowly mixed. Republic National Bank in New
York quoted a late bid for gold at $444.25 a troy ounce, down 75
cents from Friday's late bid.
   Traders looking for clues about whether the economy was
expanding or falling into a recession are focusing on reports due
later this week when the government makes its latest revised
estimate of fourth-quarter economic growth and issues reports on
consumer prices, income and spending in January.
   Marc Chandler, currency analyst for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in
Chicago, said the currency market was being pulled in opposite
directions.
   He said the market had been heartened by two consecutive monthly
declines in the U.S. trade deficit, which could indicate the
Federal Reserve may not have to encourage lower interest rates to
assure continued progress in reducing the imbalance.
   But Chandler said dollar traders remain concerned that the trade
deficit still was too large for comfort. He said there has been
speculation that European central banks sold dollars last week,
inhibiting the currency's rise, in an effort to maintain stable
foreign exchange rates.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell to 129.95 Japanese yen from 130.53 yen
on Friday. In later trading in London, the dollar slipped to 129.27
yen. In New York, the dollar fell to 129.35 yen from 130.05 yen
Friday.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7630 from $1.7505 late
Friday. The pound finished at $1.75925 in New York, up from $1.7495
last Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late rates
Friday, included: 1.69785 West German marks, down from 1.7080;
1.39275 Swiss francs, down from 1.3980; 5.7410 French francs, down
from 5.7755; 1,249.50 Italian lire, down from 1,256.75; and 1.27225
Canadian dollars, down from 1.2737.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates Friday,
included: 1.6955 West German marks, down from 1.7075; 1.3930 Swiss
francs, down from 1.3985; 5.7500 French francs, down from 5.7675;
1.9040 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9150; 1,252.25 Italian lire,
down from 1,257.75, and 1.2738 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2702.
   Gold prices edged up in Europe but slipped in New York and Hong
Kong.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold for current delivery fell
20 cents a troy ounce to $444.90 from $445.10 last Friday.
   In London, gold rose to $446 an ounce from $442.90 late Friday.
In Zurich, gold rose to $446.50 an ounce from $443 late Friday.
   In Hong Kong, gold fell to $447.12 an ounce from $447.51
Saturday.
   Silver bullion rose in London to $6.41 a troy ounce from $6.37
late Friday. Later on New York's Comex, silver for current delivery
edged up 1.5 cents an ounce to $6.40.
</TEXT>
