<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Henley-SantaFe     02-22 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Henley-Santa Fe,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Henley Proposes Santa Fe Scrap Part of Restructuring, Sell It More
Stock</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Southern Pacific</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA JOLLA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident investor Henley Group Inc.
proposed Monday that Santa Fe Southern Pacific Corp. scrap part of
its financial restructuring and instead sell $780 million in new
stock to Henley.
   The move, which would boost Henley's stake in Chicago-based
Santa Fe to 34.3 percent from 15.7 percent, was expected to receive
a cool reaction from Santa Fe, which has been fending off Henley's
unwanted overtures since mid-1987.
   Santa Fe spokesman Robert Gehrt said the proposal would be taken
up at Santa Fe's regularly scheduled board meeting Tuesday. He
added there might be a comment after that.
   Henley's proposal calls for Santa Fe to stop the planned payment
of $5 per share in high-yield ``junk bonds'' for each of its 157.3
million shares on March 1. Santa Fe already has made a
$25-per-share cash payout.
   Henley has claimed persistently that the pay-in-kind debentures
would leave shareholders with a large tax liability because of the
way they are structured.
   Instead, Henley proposed that Santa Fe sell Henley $780 million
worth of new stock at $17.50 per share. Proceeds from that deal
would be used to make a onetime $5-per-share cash payout to all
current shareholders.
   The proposed deal would mean 44.6 million new shares for Henley
and would boost Santa Fe's total shares outstanding to 201.9
million.
   Henley now owns 24.6 million shares, or 15.7 percent, of Santa
Fe, a railroad, land and natural resources concern.
   But Henley conditioned its proposal on Santa Fe voiding its
current ``poison pill'' takeover defense that would be triggered if
any holder's stake exceeds 20 percent.
   If any hostile suitor exceeds that limit, other Santa Fe
shareholders would be permitted to buy new stock at half price.
   Henley repeatedly has criticized Santa Fe's adoption of the
``poison pill'' last December, saying it restricted the ability of
major holders such as itself and Toronto-based real estate concern
Olympia & York Developments Ltd. to maneuver.
   In a setback for Henley, Santa Fe earlier this month gave two
seats on its board to officials of Olympia & York. In exchange,
Olympia & York agreed to support Santa Fe's restructuring plans.
   However, in mid-February Olympia & York launched a surprise
tender offer to boost its holdings in Santa Fe to 19.9 percent from
its current 10.5 percent.
   Olympia & York's action has caused speculation that the Canadian
company still intends to push for break-up of Santa Fe as a means
of increasing the company's value.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880222-0298 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 1856EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     02-22 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0696</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock-Index Futures Hit Highest Level Since Oct. 19</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock-index futures overcame selling resistance Monday to settle
at their highest values since the Oct. 19 stock market collapse.
   On other markets, cotton futures collapsed; grains and soybeans
were mostly lower; livestock and meat were mixed; precious metals
were mixed; and energy futures were lower.
   The contract for March delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500
stock index gained 3.90 points to settle at 266.85 on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, topping the previous post-collapse high of 264
points set Jan. 5.
   The March contract had rallied above the psychologicially
important 264-point barrier earlier in the session only to fall
back. But the second surge inspired broad-based follow-through
buying that continued until the close, indicating the market had
potential to move even higher, said Abbe Cocuzza, stock-index
strategist for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Ms. Cocuzza speculated the next point of resistance was 274
points, the level at which the March S&P 500 contract opened on
Oct. 19 after hitting a low of 280.40 in the previous session.
   Cotton futures prices collapsed on the New York Cotton Exchange
in a sell-off linked to the impending expiration of the March
contract.
   Tuesday marks the first notice day for the March cotton
contract. Traders holding ``long,'' or buy, positions rushed to
liquidate those positions to avoid the possibility of being locked
into agreements to take physical delivery of cotton on the
contract's March 9 expiration date, analysts said.
   The sharp decline in the March contract's price touched off
computerized sell programs that drove prices on the three near-term
contracts down the daily limit and sent prices on other contracts
to new life-of-contract lows, said Ernest Simon, cotton specialist
for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   The contract for March delivery of cotton settled at 60.40 cents
a pound, down the 2-cent limit.
   Grain and soybean futures finished mostly lower on the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   A mixed opening was followed by firmer prices across the board,
but the gains did not hold as commission houses became heavy
sellers of soybeans and soybean oil near the close, said Victor
Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   ``The beans and oil were the two markets that really collapsed,
and that collapse pulled everything else down,'' he said.
   Wheat settled } cent lower to 1\ cents higher with March at
$3.22\ a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 2\ cents lower with March at
$1.99\ a bushel; oats were unchanged to 1 cent lower with March at
$1.90} a bushel; soybeans were 6{ cents lower to 3 cents higher
with March at $6.27\ a bushel.
   Cattle futures declined while pork futures rose on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange. Profit-taking and hedge selling pressured the
cattle contracts, and the pork complex rallied on
better-than-expected cash prices, analysts said.
   Live cattle were .15 cent to .75 cent lower with April at 72.80
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to 1.03 cents lower with
March at 82.52 cents a pound; hogs were .12 cent to .33 cent lower
with April at 44.05 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1.10
cents lower to .35 cent higher with February at 54.02 cents a pound.
   Gold retreated slightly while silver gained a bit in light
trading on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   Gold settled 20 cents to 80 cents lower with April at $447.60 a
troy ounce; silver was 1 cent higher across the board with March at
$6.41 a troy ounce.
   Oil prices edged lower after fluctuating in a narrow range. Some
analysts cited reports of overproduction and other problems within
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries that could point
to bigger oil supplies.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 8 cents to 25 cent
lower with March at $16.62 a barrel; heating oil was .01 cent to
.56 cent lower with March at 45.79 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .05 cent to .25 cent lower with March at 46.32 cents a
gallon.
</TEXT>
