<HEAD>Formal Agreement Signed on Bank Acquisition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wells Fargo & Co. has reached a formal
agreement on its proposed acquisition of Barclays Bank of
California for $125.7 million in cash, the two banking companies
said Monday.
   Wells Fargo said the proposed acquisition, announced more than
five weeks ago and subject to approval of federal regulators, is
expected to be completed during late spring.
   The purchase should have ``minimal, if any, dilution on earnings
per share in 1988 and will make a positive contribution to earnings
per share in 1989,'' the company said in a press release.
   Wells Fargo's stock rose $1.62{ a share to $51.62{ Monday on the
New York Stock Exchange. Barclays stock closed unchanged at $32.62{.
   Barclays Bank of California, a subsidiary of Barclays Bank PLC
and the 17th largest bank in the state, had year-end assets of
approximately $1.3 billion. It operates 50 branch offices, has
about 1,100 employees and will continue to maintain corporate
offices in both San Francisco and Los Angeles.
   San Francisco-based Wells Fargo is the parent company of Wells
Fargo Bank, third largest bank in California and ninth biggest in
the nation. It had year-end assets of $44.2 billion.
   The deal continues Wells Fargo's aggressive retail expansion
across California.
</TEXT>
