<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ArcoAlaska     02-22 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arco Alaska,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arco Alaska Plans To Spend More Than $7 Billion In Alaska Over 10
Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlantic Richfield Co.'s Alaska
subsidiary said Monday it is prepared to invest more than $7
billion in the oil-rich state over the next 10 years if petroleum
prices and tax policies are stable.
   About $3 billion would go toward development of known reserves,
Arco Alaska Inc. President Bill Wade told the Anchorage Chamber of
Commerce. Spending of the rest would depend on the discovery of new
oil fields, including any reserves under the Arctic National
Wildlife Refuge if Congress allows exploration there.
   ``To accomplish all of this will require reasonable oil prices
and a stable tax policy,'' Wade said.
   The plan assumes prices in the $20-per-barrel range for a few
years, followed by increases in the mid-1990s, said Arco Alaska
spokeswoman Susan Andrews.
   She said Arco has not asked for any changes in Alaska's tax
structure and does not plan to in the near future.
   Arco Alaska operates half the giant Prudhoe Bay oil field, which
along with other North Slope oil fields supplies 20 percent of the
nation's domestic oil.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
