<DOCNO> AP880222-0302 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-88 2234EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru   02-22 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru,0187</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with morning closing figures</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell to the lowest trading level in two
weeks in early Tokyo trading Tuesday due to further selling by
foreign banks.
   The U.S. currency opened at 129.27 yen, down 0.68 yen from
Monday's close of 129.95, and was quoted at between 128.85 and
129.35 two hours after the start of trading.
   On the stock market, share prices rebounded from morning lows
and were little changed by mid-day.
   The Nikkei index of 225 selected issues ended the morning
session at 24,860.28, up 13.57 points, or 0.05 percent, from
Monday's close. The index rose about 100 points in the last 30
minutes of the morning session from a trading level of around
24,759.
   Volume by the end of the morning session was estimated at 330
million shares, down from 450 million shares during Monday's
morning session.
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa told a news conference Tuesday
that the higher prices of stocks on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
reflected Japan's sound economic fundamentals and optimism by
investors about the future.
</TEXT>
