<1ST_LINE>u f BC-7-Up     02-22 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-7-Up,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Announces Introduction of New Soft Drink</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Seven-Up Co. will introduce an amber colored
soft drink labeled 7-Up Gold designed to reach young adults,
company officials said Monday.
   The company is characterizing the new product as ``the wild side
of 7-Up,'' a natural spice flavored soft drink sweetened with
aspartame.
   ``7-Up Gold is the missing link in the 7-Up family,'' said John
R. Albers, chief executive officer of the company, a subsidiary of
the Dallas-based investment group Hicks & Haas.
   Company officials said they are trying to reach a mostly male
18- to 34-year-old market with the new drink. The company also will
introduce a Diet 7-Up Gold.
   Russ Klein, senior vice president of marketing, said that while
the image of 7-Up is clean-cut and conservative, 7-Up Gold is aimed
at mainstream soft drink consumers who generally drink colas.
   But like all 7-Up products, it will be ``light, refreshing,
thirst quenching, crisp, natural and translucent,'' Klein said.
   Shipments of the new drink will begin in April, in time for the
spring and summer seasons, with national distribution expected by
the end of May, officials said. The company will spend more than
$10 million in advertising for the drink this spring and summer,
Klein said.
   The new drink follows the introduction of Cherry 7-Up and Diet
Cherry 7-Up last year. Those drinks have captured 1.7 percent of
the lucrative soft drink market.
   Albers said 7-Up Gold now gives the company ``the most complete,
competitive line-up'' in the soft drink industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
